overzichten \u2013 Single 1997|url=http://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1997&cat=s|publisher=Dutch Charts. GfK|accessdate=February 3, 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|37\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Sweden ([[Sverigetopplistan]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19970001&newi=0&height=420&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE&navi=no&subframe=Mainframe|title=\u00c5rslista Singlar \u2013 \u00c5r 1997|publisher=[[Sverigetopplistan|Hitlistan]]|language=Swedish|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208230504/http://www.hitlistan.se/netdata/ghl002.mbr/lista?liid=43&dfom=19970001&newi=0&height=420&platform=Win32&browser=MSIE&navi=no&subframe=Mainframe|archivedate=February 8, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|43\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Switzerland ([[Schweizer Hitparade]])<ref name=swissyearend>{{cite web|title=Swiss Year-End Charts 1997 |url=http://swisscharts.com/year.asp?key=1997 |publisher=Swiss Charts. Hung Medien |accessdate=February 3, 2018|language=German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|5\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK Singles]] (Official Charts Company)<ref name=ukyearendcharts>{{cite magazine|title=Top 100 Singles 1997|magazine=[[Music Week]]|page=27|date=January 17, 1998}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|29\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1997 |title=Billboard Top 100 - 1997 |accessdate=August 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090611194337/http://longboredsurfer.com/charts.php?year=1997 |archivedate=June 11, 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |US ''Billboard'' R&B/Hip Hop Chart<ref>http://www.soulsystem.it/yend.asp?date=31/12/1997 </ref>\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |US Mainstream Top 40 (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/Billboard-Airplay/1997/BBAM-1997-12-16.pdf |title=Most Played Mainstream Top 40 Songs Of 1997|magazine=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|volume=5|issue=52|page=38|date=December 26, 1997|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" |US Rhythmic (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/Billboard-Airplay/1997/BBAM-1997-12-16.pdf |title=Most Played Rhythmic Top 40 Songs Of 1997|magazine=[[Billboard Magazine|Billboard]]|volume=5|issue=52|page=42|date=December 26, 1997|access-date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n|align=\"center\"|5\n|-\n|}\n\n===Decade-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1990\u20131999)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"1990sbb\">{{cite book | author = Geoff Mayfield | url = https://books.google.com/?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=RA1-PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false | title = 1999 The Year in Music Totally '90s: Diary of a Decade - The listing of Top Pop Albums of the '90s & Hot 100 Singles of the '90s | work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date = December 25, 1999 | accessdate = October 15, 2010}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|83\n|}\n\n===All-time charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Chart (1958\u20132018)\n! Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/hot-100-60th-anniversary|title=Billboard Hot 100 60th Anniversary Interactive Chart|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|460\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Australia|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|access-date=September 28, 2011}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Belgium|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|access-date=September 28, 2011}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Germany|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Netherlands|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|type=single|award=Gold|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=New Zealand|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go (Love)|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|type=single|award=Gold|id=3766|recent=website|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Norway|type=single|award=Platinum|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Switzerland|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go|type=single|award=Gold|relyear=1996|certyear=1997|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go (Love)|type=single|award=Platinum|relyear=1997|certyear=2016|access-date=November 19, 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=En Vogue|title=Don't Let Go|type=single|relyear=1997|award=Platinum|salesamount=1,300,000|salesref=<ref name=bestselling96/><ref name=bestselling97/>|refname=riaa}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n*The American rock band [[Deepfield]] covered this song on their first album, ''Archetypes and Repetition''.\n*The British girl group [[Sugababes]] performed this song during their [[Change Tour]] in 2008.\n*The song was sampled in the 2009 recording, also titled \"Don't Let Go (Love)\", by the British hip-hop artist [[Professor Green]].\n*The Korean girl group Bella covered this song in the Korean language as their first single in 2011.\n*On November 19, 2011, girl group contestants [[Little Mix]] performed the song on the eighth series of the British television talent contest ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'', leading to En Vogue's version re-entering the UK chart at number 23. In the finals, Little Mix performed the song for a second time and they won the show on December 11. The song is a bonus track on the group's winner's single, \"[[Cannonball (Damien Rice song)#Little Mix version|Cannonball]]\". Following the group's win and their single, the song re-entered the charts again a few weeks later at number 27. On January 25, 2012, they performed the song at The [[National Television Awards]].\n*On June 15, 2013, the contestant [[Cleo Higgins]] performed the song on the second season of British television talent contest ''[[The Voice UK|The Voice]]''.\n* The Australian singer [[Delta Goodrem]] performed the song on her 2016 [[Wings of the Wild Tour]].\n* The Australian singer Greg Gould released an acoustic version of the song on his EP ''Don't Let Go (Love)'' on February 10, 2017. In June 2017, he released a duet version of the song, with newly recorded vocals from the original En Vogue member [[Maxine Jones]].\n* The British [[house music]] producer James Hype released a cover of the song titled \"[[More Than Friends (James Hype song)|More Than Friends]]\", with vocals by the south London artist Kelli-Leigh. \"More Than Friends\" peaked #8 on the UK Singles Chart in August 2017.\n*On the March 20, 2018, episode of reality television singing competition show ''[[The Voice (U.S. series)|The Voice]]'', Team [[Alicia Keys|Keys]] contestants Jordyn Simone and Kelsea Johnson performed an arrangement of the song in a Battle round.\n*[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] did a cover version with [[Craig David]], Kianja and Swarmz for their mixtape [[Other People's Heartache#Part four|Other People's Heartache, Pt. 4]].\n*Singer Whitney Reign performed a shortened version of the song during her challenge against Ali Caldwell during the second season comeback episode of ''[[The Four: Battle for Stardom]]''.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year !! Award !! Result \n|-\n| 1997 || [[Grammy Award]] for Best R&B Vocal Performance by a Duo or Group || {{nominated}}\n|-\n| 1997 || [[Soul Train Music Award|Soul Train Lady of Soul Award]] for Best R&B, Rap or Soul Single by Group, Band or Duo || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1997 || [[Billboard Music Award]] for Top Soundtrack Single || {{nominated}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of number-one R&B singles of 1997 (U.S.)]]\n* [[List of number-one hits in Norway#1997|List of number-one hits in Norway]]\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|en-vogue|dont-let-go-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{En Vogue}}\n\n[[Category:1996 singles]]\n[[Category:En Vogue songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Norway]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Andrea Martin (musician)]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ivan Matias]]\n[[Category:1996 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Organized Noize]]\n[[Category:Contemporary R&B ballads]]\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Matthew Rolston]]\n[[Category:American pop rock songs]]\n", "name_user": "R. fiend", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMusic video", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don%27t_Let_Go_(Love)"}
{"title_page": "Andy Kerr (Scottish politician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox MSP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Andy Kerr\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Andy Kerr.jpg\n| caption = \n| office               = [[Minister for Health and Community Care]]     \n| term_start           = 6 October 2004\n| term_end             = 16 May 2007\n| firstminister        = [[Jack McConnell]]\n| predecessor          = [[Malcolm Chisholm]]\n| successor            = [[Nicola Sturgeon]]<br /><small>(as [[Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing]])</small>\n| constituency_MP2 = [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride]]\n| parliament2 = Scottish\n| majority2 =\n| term_start2 = 6 May 1999\n| term_end2 = 22 March 2011\n| predecessor2 = ''new constituency''\n| successor2 = [[Linda Fabiani]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|3|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[East Kilbride]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| birthname = \n| nationality = \n| party = [[Scottish Labour Party]]\n| spouse = \n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| committees = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Andy Kerr''' (born 17 March 1962, [[East Kilbride]], [[South Lanarkshire]]) is a Scottish [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] politician and former [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride constituency]], a seat which he held from 1999 until 2011.\n\n==Biography==\nKerr was educated at [[Claremont High School (East Kilbride)|Claremont High School]] in [[East Kilbride]] and obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[Social Sciences]] at [[Glasgow Caledonian University]].\n\nPrior to being elected to the [[Scottish Parliament]], he was a senior officer in [[Glasgow City Council]] land services department and served as an adviser in the Leader's office. He was also founder and managing director of ''Achieving'', a quality assurance consultancy.\n\nHe was convener of the [[Scottish Parliament]]'s Transport and Environment [[Scottish Parliament#Committees|Committee]] and served on the [[Confederation of British Industry]] working group designed to bring [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|Members of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) and business closer together as well as being on the cross-party group on ageing and the elderly.\n\nKerr is considered to be an ally of [[Motherwell and Wishaw (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Motherwell and Wishaw]] MSP [[Jack McConnell]], working with him on his two successive bids for the leadership of Scottish Labour and the position of First Minister.\n\nKerr was first appointed [[List of Scottish Executive Ministerial Teams|Minister for Finance and Public Services]] in the [[Scottish Executive]] in November 2001 and moved to become Minister for Health and Community Care in October 2004, replacing [[Malcolm Chisolm]]. As Health Minister, Kerr oversaw significant NHS restructuring.\n\nHe was also responsible for the Scottish ban on  [[smoking ban in public places]] which was introduced on 26 March 2006. In November 2006, he won the [[Scottish Politician of the Year]] award in recognition of his work to bring in the smoking ban.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/6156548.stm Deportation campaign wins award], ''[[BBC News]]'', 17 November 2006</ref> Kerr retained the health portfolio in McConnell's shadow cabinet upon the [[Scottish National Party]]'s victory at the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|2007 election]].\n\nHaving ruled himself out of contention as a successor for Jack McConnell, Kerr voted for Wendy Alexander to become leader of the Scottish Labour Party. On 17 September 2007 he was appointed Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Public Services and Local Government. With [[Wendy Alexander]]'s resignation as leader of the Labour Party in Scotland, Kerr stood for election as the next leader. However, following the victory of Iain Gray in the leadership election, Kerr was appointed Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth.\n\nAt the 2011 Scottish Parliament election, Kerr was one of many Labour casualties, losing his seat after 12 years to [[Linda Fabiani]] of the SNP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-13305003|title=Labour 'class of '99' lose to SNP|date=6 May 2011|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Kerr did not stand on the regional list, so therefore did not return as an MSP.\n\nKerr lives in [[Strathaven]] with his wife and three daughters.\n\nOn 11 July 2011, it was announced that Andy had been appointed to the vacant CEO position at Scottish Charity Organisation, [[Sense Scotland]].<ref>http://www.sensescotland.org.uk/news/new-ceo-announcement.php{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the 2018 [[Labour Party Conference]] Kerr faced accusations of [[sectarianism]] after calling a woman to the stage to speak and appeared to mock the woman saying  \"Did you cross yourself, there? In that case, I might not [call you].\" The reference was to making the [[sign of the cross]], an act common among [[Roman Catholics]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/andy-kerr-should-drop-nec-role-after-anti-catholic-remark-say-snp-250825|title=Scotsman|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-45627895/labour-official-andy-kerr-sorry-for-catholic-jibe|title=BBC news|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\nThe comment was condemned by the Scottish First Minister, [[Nicola Sturgeon]] who called for his resignation as head of the [[National Executive Committee|National Excutive Committee]]. [[Scottish Conservatives|Scottish Conservative]] leader [[Ruth Davidson]] also condemned the comment. The  Scottish Labour Party leader, [[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]] also condemned the comment and when asked on [[BBC Radio Scotland]] if it was \"bigoted\", Leanord stated \"That might be one way of describing it.\"He added: \"There is absolutely no room inside the Labour Party for that kind of remark, whether it\u2019s meant as a form of humour or not.\"It\u2019s completely unacceptable and Andy Kerr has unreservedly apologised for the remark that he made.\"There should be no space for it inside the Labour Party and I condemn it.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.holyrood.com/news/view,richard-leonard-andy-kerr-catholic-comment-completely-unacceptable_9272.htm|title=Holyrood|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nKerr later went on to apologise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-45625635|title=Apology bbc news|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sensescotland.org.uk/what-we-do/latest-news/andy-kerr-announced-as-new-ceo-for-sense-scotland.aspx http://www.sensescotland.org.uk]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Sense Scotland News Story re: appointment of Andy to CEO.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081004143544/http://www.scottishlabour.org.uk/east_kilbride Andy Kerr] Scottish Labour website\n*[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/opinion.cfm?id=462552007#new No butts, it's our liberty that's going up in smoke]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Scotland on Sunday]] opinion piece on the effects of Scotland's smoking ban\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/6491471.stm Ban 'helping smokers to give up'] [[BBC News]]<br />{{s-start}}\n\n{{s-par|sct}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride]] | before=Constituency Created | years=[[1999 Scottish Parliament election|1999]]-[[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011]]|after=[[Linda Fabiani]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Minister for Health and Community Care]] | years=2004\u20132007 | before=[[Malcolm Chisholm]] | after=[[Nicola Sturgeon]]<br><small>(as Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing)</small>}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Minister for Finance and Public Services]] | years=2001\u20132004 | before=[[Angus MacKay (Scottish politician)|Angus MacKay]] | after=[[Tom McCabe]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Scottish Labour Party leadership election, 2008}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerr, Andy}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n[[Category:Labour MSPs]]\n[[Category:People from East Kilbride]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Health ministers of Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Infobox MSP\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = Andy Kerr\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Andy Kerr.jpg\n| caption = \n| office               = [[Minister for Health and Community Care]]     \n| term_start           = 6 October 2004\n| term_end             = 16 May 2007\n| firstminister        = [[Jack McConnell]]\n| predecessor          = [[Malcolm Chisholm]]\n| successor            = [[Nicola Sturgeon]]<br /><small>(as [[Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing]])</small>\n| constituency_MP2 = [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride]]\n| parliament2 = Scottish\n| majority2 =\n| term_start2 = 6 May 1999\n| term_end2 = 22 March 2011\n| predecessor2 = ''new constituency''\n| successor2 = [[Linda Fabiani]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|3|17|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[East Kilbride]], [[Scotland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| birthname = \n| nationality = \n| party = [[Scottish Labour Party]]\n| spouse = \n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| cabinet = \n| committees = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Andy Kerr''' (born 17 March 1962, [[East Kilbride]], [[South Lanarkshire]]) is a Scottish [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] politician and former [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride constituency]], a seat which he held from 1999 until 2011.\n\n==Biography==\nKerr was educated at [[Claremont High School (East Kilbride)|Claremont High School]] in [[East Kilbride]] and obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[Social Sciences]] at [[Glasgow Caledonian University]].\n\nPrior to being elected to the [[Scottish Parliament]], he was a senior officer in [[Glasgow City Council]] land services department and served as an adviser in the Leader's office. He was also founder and managing director of ''Achieving'', a quality assurance consultancy.\n\nHe was convener of the [[Scottish Parliament]]'s Transport and Environment [[Scottish Parliament#Committees|Committee]] and served on the [[Confederation of British Industry]] working group designed to bring [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|Members of the Scottish Parliament]] (MSP) and business closer together as well as being on the cross-party group on ageing and the elderly.\n\nKerr is considered to be an ally of [[Motherwell and Wishaw (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Motherwell and Wishaw]] MSP [[Jack McConnell]], working with him on his two successive bids for the leadership of Scottish Labour and the position of First Minister.\n\nKerr was first appointed [[List of Scottish Executive Ministerial Teams|Minister for Finance and Public Services]] in the [[Scottish Executive]] in November 2001 and moved to become Minister for Health and Community Care in October 2004, replacing [[Malcolm Chisolm]]. As Health Minister, Kerr oversaw significant NHS restructuring.\n\nHe was also responsible for the Scottish ban on  [[smoking ban in public places]] which was introduced on 26 March 2006. In November 2006, he won the [[Scottish Politician of the Year]] award in recognition of his work to bring in the smoking ban.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/6156548.stm Deportation campaign wins award], ''[[BBC News]]'', 17 November 2006</ref> Kerr retained the health portfolio in McConnell's shadow cabinet upon the [[Scottish National Party]]'s victory at the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|2007 election]].\n\nHaving ruled himself out of contention as a successor for Jack McConnell, Kerr voted for Wendy Alexander to become leader of the Scottish Labour Party. On 17 September 2007 he was appointed Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Public Services and Local Government. With [[Wendy Alexander]]'s resignation as leader of the Labour Party in Scotland, Kerr stood for election as the next leader. However, following the victory of Iain Gray in the leadership election, Kerr was appointed Shadow Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth.\n\nAt the 2011 Scottish Parliament election, Kerr was one of many Labour casualties, losing his seat after 12 years to [[Linda Fabiani]] of the SNP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-13305003|title=Labour 'class of '99' lose to SNP|date=6 May 2011|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Kerr did not stand on the regional list, so therefore did not return as an MSP.\n\nKerr lives in [[Strathaven]] with his wife and three daughters.\n\nOn 11 July 2011, it was announced that Andy had been appointed to the vacant CEO position at Scottish Charity Organisation, [[Sense Scotland]].<ref>http://www.sensescotland.org.uk/news/new-ceo-announcement.php{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nDuring the 2018 [[Labour Party Conference]] Kerr faced accusations of [[sectarianism]] after calling a woman to the stage to speak and appeared to mock the woman saying  \"Did you cross yourself, there? In that case, I might not [call you].\" The reference was to making the [[sign of the cross]], an act common among [[Roman Catholics]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/andy-kerr-should-drop-nec-role-after-anti-catholic-remark-say-snp-250825|title=Scotsman|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-politics-45627895/labour-official-andy-kerr-sorry-for-catholic-jibe|title=BBC news|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\nThe comment was condemned by the Scottish First Minister, [[Nicola Sturgeon]] who called for his resignation as head of the [[National Executive Committee|National Excutive Committee]]. [[Scottish Conservatives|Scottish Conservative]] leader [[Ruth Davidson]] also condemned the comment. The  Scottish Labour Party leader, [[Richard Leonard (Scottish politician)|Richard Leonard]] also condemned the comment and when asked on [[BBC Radio Scotland]] if it was \u201cbigoted\u201d, Leanord stated \u201cThat might be one way of describing it.\u201dHe added: \u201cThere is absolutely no room inside the Labour Party for that kind of remark, whether it\u2019s meant as a form of humour or not.\u201cIt\u2019s completely unacceptable and Andy Kerr has unreservedly apologised for the remark that he made.\u201cThere should be no space for it inside the Labour Party and I condemn it.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.holyrood.com/news/view,richard-leonard-andy-kerr-catholic-comment-completely-unacceptable_9272.htm|title=Holyrood|last=|first=|date=|website=www.google.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nKerr later went on to apologise.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-45625635|title=Apology bbc news|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sensescotland.org.uk/what-we-do/latest-news/andy-kerr-announced-as-new-ceo-for-sense-scotland.aspx http://www.sensescotland.org.uk]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Sense Scotland News Story re: appointment of Andy to CEO.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081004143544/http://www.scottishlabour.org.uk/east_kilbride Andy Kerr] Scottish Labour website\n*[http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/opinion.cfm?id=462552007#new No butts, it's our liberty that's going up in smoke]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} [[Scotland on Sunday]] opinion piece on the effects of Scotland's smoking ban\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/6491471.stm Ban 'helping smokers to give up'] [[BBC News]]<br />{{s-start}}\n\n{{s-par|sct}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[East Kilbride (Scottish Parliament constituency)|East Kilbride]] | before=Constituency Created | years=[[1999 Scottish Parliament election|1999]]-[[2011 Scottish Parliament election|2011]]|after=[[Linda Fabiani]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Minister for Health and Community Care]] | years=2004\u20132007 | before=[[Malcolm Chisholm]] | after=[[Nicola Sturgeon]]<br><small>(as Cabinet Secretary for Health and Wellbeing)</small>}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Minister for Finance and Public Services]] | years=2001\u20132004 | before=[[Angus MacKay (Scottish politician)|Angus MacKay]] | after=[[Tom McCabe]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Scottish Labour Party leadership election, 2008}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerr, Andy}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n[[Category:Labour MSPs]]\n[[Category:People from East Kilbride]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 1999\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2003\u20132007]]\n[[Category:Members of the Scottish Parliament 2007\u20132011]]\n[[Category:Finance ministers of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Health ministers of Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Dl2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "repair <br /> botchtagging; fix quot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Kerr_(Scottish_politician)"}
{"title_page": "Mark McGwire", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player and coach}}\n{{for|the American musician|Mark McGuire (musician)}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Mark McGwire\n|image=Mark_McGwire_Padres_coach_May_2017.jpg\n|image_size=240\n|caption= McGwire with the [[San Diego Padres]] in 2017\n|team=\n|number=\n|width=250\n|position=[[First baseman]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1963|10|1}}\n|birth_place=[[Pomona, California]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 22\n|debutyear=1986\n|debutteam=Oakland Athletics\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 7\n|finalyear=2001\n|finalteam=St. Louis Cardinals\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.263\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=583\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=1,414\n|teams=\n'''As player'''\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|1986}}\u2013{{mlby|1997}})\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|1997}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n'''As coach'''\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2016}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}}) \n|highlights=\n* 12\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1987]]\u2013[[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992]], [[1995 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1995]]\u2013[[2000 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2000]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1989}}, {{wsy|2011}})\n* [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|AL Rookie of the Year]] (1987)\n* [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Award]] (1990)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (1992, 1996, 1998)\n* 5\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB home run leader]] (1987, 1996\u20131999)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders|NL RBI leader]] (1999)\n* [[Athletics Hall of Fame]]\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame Museum|St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Country|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Baseball]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Baseball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Baseball at the Pan American Games|1983 Caracas]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Intercontinental Cup (baseball)|Intercontinental Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Intercontinental Cup (baseball)|1983 Brussels]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Mark David McSteroid''' (born October 1, 1963), nicknamed '''Big Mac''', is an [[Americans|American]] former [[professional baseball]] [[first baseman]]. His [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) playing career spanned from 1986 to 2001 while playing for the [[Oakland Athletics]] and the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], winning one [[World Series]] championship each with Oakland as a player in [[1989 World Series|1989]] and with St. Louis as a coach in [[2011 World Series|2011]].  One of the most prolific [[home run]] hitters in baseball history, McGwire holds the major league career record for [[at bats per home run]] ratio (10.6), and is the former record holder for both [[List of Major League Baseball progressive single-season home run leaders|home runs in a single season]] (70 in 1998) and home runs hit by rookie (49 in 1987).  \n\nHe ranks 11th all time in [[home run]]s with 583, and led the major leagues in home runs in five different seasons, while establishing the major league record for home runs hit in a four-season period from 1996 to 1999 with 245.  Further, he demonstrated exemplary patience as a batter, producing a career .394 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and twice leading the major leagues in [[bases on balls]].  Injuries cut short the manifestation of even greater potential as he reached 140 games played in just eight of 16 total seasons.  A right-handed batter and thrower, McGwire stood {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m}} tall and weighed {{convert|245|lb}} during his playing career.\n\nA part of the [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase]] of [[Roger Maris]]' 61 with the Cardinals, McGwire set the [[Major League Baseball single-season home run record|major league single-season home run record]] with 70,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/HR_progress.shtml |title=Progressive Leaders & Records for Home Runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> which [[Barry Bonds]] broke three years later with 73.<ref name=Bonds-testified>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1937594 |title=\"Bonds testified that substances didn't work\", ESPN.com, December 4, 2004, accessed 02/03/11 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=December 4, 2004 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  McGwire also led the league in [[runs batted in]], twice in [[bases on balls]] and [[on-base percentage]], and four times in [[slugging percentage]]. Injuries significantly cut into his playing time in 2000 and 2001 before factoring into his retirement. He finished with 583 home runs, which was [[500 home run club|fifth all-time]] when he retired.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/mcgwima01.shtml|title=Mark McGwire Stats {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-17}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire was a central figure in baseball's [[doping in baseball|steroids scandal]]. In 2010, McGwire publicly admitted to using performance-enhancing drugs during a large portion of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/12/sports/baseball/12mcgwire.html?pagewanted=all|title=McGwire Admits That He Used Steroids - NYTimes.com|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|publisher=}}</ref> In his first ten years of eligibility, McGwire has not been elected into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/11/29/hall-of-fame-todays-game-ballot-mark-mcgwire|title=McGwire gets second HOF shot, but is he worthy?|first=Jay|last=Jaffe|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\n\nMcGwire was born in [[Pomona, California]]. His father was a [[dentist]]. He attended [[Damien High School]] in [[La Verne, California]], where he played baseball, golf, and basketball. He was drafted by the [[Montreal Expos]] in the 1981 amateur draft but did not sign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/mcgwima01.shtml|title=Mark McGwire Stats - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> He played college baseball at the [[University of Southern California]] (where he was a teammate of [[Randy Johnson]] and [[Jack Del Rio]]) under coach [[Rod Dedeaux]].\n\nMcGwire was selected by the Athletics with the 10th overall selection in the [[1984 Major League Baseball draft|1984 MLB draft]]. \n\nHe was a member of the [[silver medal]]-winning entry of the [[United States national baseball team|United States national team]]<nowiki/> that [[Baseball  at the 1984 Summer Olympics|same year]]<nowiki/>at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]], with Japan finishing ahead for gold medal.\n\n==Playing career (1984\u20132001)==\n\n===Oakland Athletics (1984\u20131997)===\n\nAfter three years at Southern California and a stint on the 1984 U.S. Olympic team, the [[Oakland Athletics]] drafted McGwire tenth overall in the [[1984 Major League Baseball draft]].\n\nMcGwire debuted in the major leagues in August [[1986 Oakland Athletics season|1986]], hitting three [[home run]]s and nine [[runs batted in]] in 18 games.\n\n====Rookie home run record and major league leader (1987)====\n\nRetaining his rookie status in [[1987 Major League Baseball season|1987]], McGwire took center stage in baseball with his home runs. He hit just four in the month of April, but followed in May with 15, and another nine in June. Before the All-Star break arrived, he totaled 33 HR and earned a spot on the [[American League]] (AL) [[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star team]]. On August 11, he broke [[Al Rosen]]'s AL rookie record of 37 home runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/APAB/lib00581,122CA98E1CEF7498.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120708140841/http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/APAB/lib00581,122CA98E1CEF7498.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 8, 2012|date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>  Three days later, McGwire broke the major league record of 38, which [[Frank Robinson]] and [[Wally Berger]] jointly held. In September, McGwire hit nine more home runs while posting monthly personal bests of a .351 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], .419 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and 11 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (2B). With 49 HR and two games remaining in the regular season, he chose to sit them out with an opportunity for 50 home runs to be present for the birth of his first child. McGwire also totaled 118 [[runs batted in]] (RBI), .289 batting average, 97 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored, 28 doubles, a .618 [[slugging percentage]] and a .370 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP). McGwire's 49 home runs as a rookie stood as a major league record until [[Aaron Judge]] hit 52 for the [[New York Yankees]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/news/yankees-aaron-judge-sets-rookie-hr-record-mark-mcgwire/xyqbr125vm8k13f1ips4sg1nl|title=Yankees' Aaron Judge breaks Mark McGwire's rookie HR record|date=2017-09-26|work=Sporting News|access-date=2017-12-02}}</ref>\n\nNot only did he lead the AL in home runs in 1987, but he also tied for the major league lead with [[1987 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] right fielder [[Andre Dawson]]. McGwire also led the major leagues in SLG, finished second in the AL in adjusted [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage (OPS+, 164) total bases (344), third in RBI and on-base plus slugging (OPS, .987). He was thus a unanimous choice for the AL [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]] and finished sixth overall in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\n====More All-Star appearances (1988\u201391)====\n\n[[File:Mark McGwire 1989.jpg|thumb|left|McGwire with the A's, 1989]]\n\nFrom [[1988 Oakland Athletics season|1988]] to [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|1990]], McGwire followed with 32, 33, and 39 home runs, respectively, becoming the first Major Leaguer to hit 30+ home runs in each of his first four full seasons.<ref name=\"BaseballRefMain\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcgwima01.shtml |title=Mark McGwire Statistics |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  On July 3 and 4, 1988, he hit game-winning home runs in the 16th inning of both games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TOR/TOR198807030.shtml |title=July 3, 1988 Oakland Athletics at Toronto Blue Jays play by play and box score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=July 3, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE198807040.shtml |title=July 4, 1988 Oakland Athletics at Cleveland Indians Jays play by play and box score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=July 4, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Through May 2009, McGwire was tied for third all-time with [[Joe DiMaggio]] in home runs over his first two calendar years in the major leagues (71), behind [[Chuck Klein]] (83) and [[Ryan Braun]] (79).<ref>[https://nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=1633915 Sandler, Jeremy, \"NL Weekly: The Notebook\", National Post, May 27, 2009, accessed 5/28/09]{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire's most famous home run with the A's was likely his game-winning solo shot in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 3 of the [[1988 World Series]] against the [[1988 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] and former A's [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Jay Howell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/OAK/OAK198810180.shtml |title=October 18, 1988 World Series Game 3 at Network Associates Coliseum Play by Play and Box Score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=October 18, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  McGwire's game-winner brought the A's their only victory in the 1988 World Series, which they lost in five games; however, McGwire and his fellow [[Bash Brother]], [[Jos\u00e9 Canseco]], played a large part in the 1989 championship club that defeated the [[1989 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]] in the famous \"[[1989 World Series|Earthquake Series]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1989_WS.shtml |title=1989 World Series \u2013 OAK vs. SFG |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWorking diligently on his defense at first base, McGwire bristled at the notion that he was a one-dimensional player. He was generally regarded as a good fielder in his early years, even winning a [[Gold Glove Award]] in [[1990 Major League Baseball season|1990]] \u2013 the only one that [[New York Yankees]] legend [[Don Mattingly]] would not win between [[1985 Major League Baseball season|1985]] and [[1994 Major League Baseball season|1994]]. In later years, his mobility decreased and, with it, his defense; however, McGwire's batting averages after his rookie season plummeted to .260, .231, and .235 from 1988 to 1990. In 1991, he bottomed out with a .201 average and 22 homers. [[List of Oakland Athletics managers|Manager]] [[Tony La Russa]] sat him out the final game of the [[1991 Oakland Athletics season|season]] to avoid allowing his batting average to dip below .200. Despite the declining averages during this time of his career, his high [[bases on balls]] totals allowed him to maintain acceptable OBPs. In fact, when he hit .201, his OPS+ was 103, or just over league average.\n\nMcGwire stated in an interview with ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' that 1991 was the \"worst year\" of his life, with his on-field performance and marriage difficulties, and that he \"didn't lift a weight\" that entire season. With all that behind him, McGwire re-dedicated himself to working out harder than ever and received visual therapy from a sports vision specialist.<ref>[http://www.sdccd.edu/events/we/wepdf/we-sp99.pdf] https://web.archive.org/web/20150701040841/http://www.sdccd.edu/events/we/wepdf/we-sp99.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/features/mcgwire/flashbacks/060192/ |work=CNN |accessdate=May 12, 2010 |title=Oakland's Mark McGwire is smiling again, now that he's hitting homers at a record pace |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104193550/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/features/mcgwire/flashbacks/060192/ |archivedate=November 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====Career resurgence (1992\u201397)====\n\nThe \"new look\" McGwire hit 42 homers and batted .268 in 1992, with an outstanding OPS+ of 175 (the highest of his career to that point), and put on a home run hitting show at the [[Home Run Derby]] during the [[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992 All-Star break]]. His performance propelled the [[1992 Oakland Athletics season|A's]] to the American League West Division title in 1992, their fourth in five seasons. The A's lost in the [[1992 American League Championship Series|playoffs]] to the eventual [[1992 World Series|World Series]] champion, the [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]].\n\nFoot injuries limited McGwire to a total of 74 games in [[1993 Oakland Athletics season|1993]] and [[1994 Oakland Athletics season|1994]], and just 9 home runs in each of the two seasons. He played just 104 games in [[1995 Oakland Athletics season|1995]], but his proportional totals were much improved: 39 home runs in 317 at-bats. In [[1996 Oakland Athletics season|1996]], McGwire belted a major league leading 52 homers in 423 at-bats. He also hit a career high .312 average, and led the league in both slugging percentage and on-base percentage.\n\nMcGwire's total of 363 home runs with the Athletics surpassed the previous franchise record. He was selected or voted to nine [[American League]] All-Star Teams while playing for the A's, including six consecutive appearances from [[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1987]] through [[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992]]. He was one of only four players to hit a ball over the roof in the left field of [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]].<ref>The Final Season, p.90, Tom Stanton, Thomas Dunne Books, An imprint of St. Martin's Press, New York, 2001, {{ISBN|0-312-29156-6}}</ref>\n\n===St. Louis Cardinals (1997\u20132001)===\n\n[[File:Mark mcgwire.jpg|thumb|right|McGwire hitting a home run in St. Louis against the Tigers on July 14, 2001]]\nOn July 31, having already amassed 34 home runs to this point in the [[1997 in baseball|1997 season]], McGwire was traded from the [[1997 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] to the [[1997 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] for [[T. J. Mathews]], [[Eric Ludwick]] and [[Blake Stein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/THE-BIG-DEALS-THE-A-S-McGwire-finally-traded-2831502.php|title=THE BIG DEALS / THE A'S / McGwire finally traded -- to Cards|publisher=}}</ref> Despite playing just two-thirds of the season in the American League, he finished ninth in home runs. In 51 games with the Cardinals to finish the 1997 season, McGwire compiled a .253 batting average, 24 home runs, and 42 RBI. Overall in 1997, McGwire led the majors with 58 home runs. He also finished third in the major leagues in slugging percentage (.646), fourth in OPS (1.039), fifth in OPS+ (170), tenth in RBI (123), and ninth in walks (101). He placed 16th in the NL MVP voting.\n\nIt was the last year of his contract, so there was speculation that McGwire would play for the Cardinals only for the remainder of the season, then seek a long-term deal, possibly in Southern California, where he still lived; however, McGwire signed a contract to stay in St. Louis. It is also believed that McGwire later encouraged [[Jim Edmonds]], another Southern California resident who was traded to St. Louis, to forgo free agency and sign a contract with the Cardinals in 2000.\n\n====Single-season home run record chase (1998)====\n\nAs the [[1998 St. Louis Cardinals season|1998 season]] progressed, it became clear that McGwire, [[1998 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]] outfielder [[Ken Griffey Jr.]], and [[1998 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] outfielder [[Sammy Sosa]] were all on track to break [[Roger Maris]]'s single-season home run record. [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase|The race to break the record]] first attracted media attention as the home run leader changed often throughout the season. On August 19, Sosa hit his 48th home run to move ahead of McGwire; however, later that day McGwire hit his 48th and 49th home runs to regain the lead.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nOn September 8, 1998, McGwire hit a pitch by the Cubs' [[Steve Trachsel]] over the left field wall for his record-breaking 62nd home run, setting off massive celebrations at [[Busch Memorial Stadium|Busch Stadium]]. The fact that the game was against the Cubs meant that Sosa was able to congratulate McGwire personally on his achievement. Members of Maris's family were also present at the game. The ball was freely, albeit controversially, given to McGwire in a ceremony on the field by the stadium worker who found it.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nMcGwire finished the 1998 season with 70 home runs (including five in his last three games), four ahead of Sosa's 66, a record that was broken three seasons later in 2001 by [[Barry Bonds]] with 73.<ref name=Bonds-testified/>\n\nMcGwire was honored with the inaugural [[Babe Ruth Home Run Award]] for leading Major League Baseball in home runs.<ref name=harber>{{cite news|last=Harber|first=Paul|title=A statue fit for a home run king|date=July 22, 2001|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8659756.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602104753/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8659756.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 2, 2013|accessdate=November 8, 2011|quote=The first award was given to Mark McGwire after his 70-home-run season in 1998.}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Although McGwire had the prestige of the home run record, Sammy Sosa (who had fewer HR but more RBI and stolen bases) won the 1998 NL MVP award, as his contributions helped propel the Cubs to the [[1998 National League Division Series|playoffs]] (the [[1998 St. Louis Cardinals season|Cardinals]] in 1998 finished third in the NL Central). Many credited the Sosa-McGwire home run chase in 1998 with \"saving baseball\", by both bringing in new, younger fans and bringing back old fans soured by the [[1994\u201395 Major League Baseball strike]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/30/sports/myth-of-men-who-saved-baseball.html|title=Myth of men who saved baseball|date=March 30, 2005|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\n====Later playing career (1999\u20132001)====\nMcGwire kept his high level of offensive production from 1998 going in [[1999 St. Louis Cardinals season|1999]] while setting or extending several significant records. For the fourth consecutive season, he led MLB in home runs with 65. It was also his fourth consecutive season with at least 50 home runs, extending his own major league record. Sosa, who hit 63 home runs in 1999, again trailed McGwire. Thus, they became the first, and still only, players in major league history to hit 60 or more home runs in consecutive seasons. McGwire also set a record from 1998 to 1999 for home runs in a two-season period with 135. Further, he owned the highest four-season HR total, with 245 from 1996 to 1999. In 1999, he drove in an NL-leading 147 runs while only having 145 hits, the highest RBI-per-hit tally for a season in baseball history.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nStatistically in 2000 and 2001, McGwire's numbers declined relative to previous years as he struggled to avoid injury (32 HR in 89 games, and 29 HR in 97 games, respectively). He retired after the 2001 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcgwima01.shtml |title=Baseball-reference.om McGwire stats |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career (2010-2018)==\n[[File:Mark McGwire on June 29, 2011.jpg|220px|thumb|McGwire as coach for the [[2011 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals in 2011]]]]\nAfter his playing career ended, McGwire demonstrated coaching ability, personally assisting players such as [[Matt Holliday]], [[Bobby Crosby]] and [[Skip Schumaker]] before accepting an official role as hitting coach with an MLB team. On October 26, 2009, [[Tony La Russa]], then [[List of St. Louis Cardinals managers|manager]] of the Cardinals, confirmed that McGwire would become the club's fifth [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches|hitting coach]] of his tenure with the Cardinals, replacing [[Hal McRae]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100107&content_id=7887624&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=McGwire to speak, but date not set: Cards GM hopeful new hitting coach will appear soon |publisher=MLB.com |date=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=January 11, 2010}}</ref>  McGwire received a standing ovation prior to the Cardinals home opener on April 12, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news;_ylt=AjP3IcZXdVWvfZt.c6hW8uYRvLYF?slug%3Dap-cardinals-mcgwire  |accessdate=2014-07-21 |df=mdy }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In his three seasons as Cardinals hitting coach, they featured a prolific offense that led the National League in hitting and on-base percentage, and were second in runs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/baseball/mlb/dodgers/la-sp-1103-dodgers-mark-mcgwire-20121103,0,2702730.story |title=Mark McGwire expected to be Dodgers' hitting coach |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn early November, 2012, McGwire rejected a contract extension to return as Cardinals hitting coach for the 2013 season. Instead, he accepted an offer for the same position with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gurnick|first=Ken|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121102&content_id=40155526&vkey=news_stl&c_id=stl|title=Report: McGwire to become Dodgers' hitting coach|publisher=MLB.com via St. Louis Cardinals website|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> in order to be closer to his wife and five children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/mlb-big-league-stew/report-mark-mcgwire-close-joining-los-angeles-dodgers-221746224--mlb.html|title=Report: Mark McGwire close to joining Los Angeles Dodgers as hitting coach|publisher=Yahoo sports|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2013, McGwire was [[Ejection (sports)|ejected]] for the first time as a coach during a [[bench-clearing brawl]] with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]].<ref>\"[http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/06/mlb-ejections-071-072-073-074-075-076.html MLB Ejections 071, 072, 073, 074, 075, 076: Clint Fagan (3\u20138)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801232535/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/06/mlb-ejections-071-072-073-074-075-076.html |date=August 1, 2013 }}.\" ''Close Call Sports/Umpire Ejection Fantasy League''. June 12, 2013.</ref>  He was suspended for two games starting the next day.\n\nOn December 2, 2015, he was named the new bench coach for the [[San Diego Padres]]. He left the team after the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25065289/mark-mcgwire-return-san-diego-padres-bench-coach |title=Mark McGwire not returning as Padres' coach to spend time with family |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=October 23, 2018 |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honors, records and achievements==\nKnown as one of the top sluggers of his era, McGwire ended his career with 583 home runs, which was fifth-most in history when he retired. When he hit his 500th career home run in 1999, he did so in 5,487 career at bats, the fewest in major league history.<ref name=\"atbatto500hr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hi500c.shtml|title=500 Home Run Details|date=|publisher=Baseball-Almanac.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216025541/http://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hi500c.shtml|archive-date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref>  He led all MLB in home runs in five different seasons, including 1987 and each season from 1996 to 1999. Totaling 245 home runs from 1996\u221299, it was the highest four-season home run output in major league history. Further, in each of those four seasons, he exceeded 50 home runs, becoming the first player to do so. He was also the first player to hit 49 or more home runs five times, including his rookie-season record of 49 in 1987. With a career average of one home every 10.61 at-bats, he holds the MLB record for most home runs per at-bat by over a full at-bat more than second-place Babe Ruth (11.76).<ref name=\"atperhr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/ABpHR_career.shtml|title=Career Leaders & Records for at bats per home run|website=Baseball-Reference.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228202538/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/ABpHR_career.shtml|archive-date=February 28, 2009|accessdate=November 7, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2015, McGwire owned three of the four lowest single-season AB/HR ratios in MLB history, which covered his 1996, 1998 and 1999 seasons. They were actually the top three seasons in MLB history until Bonds broke his single-season HR record in 2001. McGwire's 1997 season ranked 13th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/at_bats_per_home_run_season.shtml |title=Single-season leaders & records for AB per HR |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>  Considered one of the slowest running players in the game, McGwire had the fewest career triples (six) of any player with 5,000 or more at-bats, and had just 12 stolen bases while being caught stealing eight times.\n\n===Honors and distinctions===\n\nIn 1999, ''[[The Sporting News]]'' released a list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, ranking McGwire at number 91. The list had been compiled during the [[1998 in baseball|1998 season]] and included statistics through the [[1997 in baseball|1997 season]]. That year, he was elected to the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]. In 2005, ''The Sporting News'' published an update of their list, and McGwire had been moved up to Number 84.\n\nMcGwire first became eligible for [[National Baseball Hall of Fame & Museum|Hall of Fame]] voting in 2007. For election, a player needs to be listed on 75% of ballots cast; falling under 5% removes a player from future consideration. Between 2007 and 2010 McGwire's performance held steady, receiving 128 votes (23.5%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2007|2007]], 128 votes (23.6%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2008|2008]], 118 votes (21.9%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2009|2009]], and 128 votes (23.7%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2010|2010]]. The subsequent ballot in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2011|2011]] showed the first sub-20% total of 115 votes (19.8%), and McGwire's total votes continued to decline (112 votes (19.5%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2012|2012]], 96 votes (16.9%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2013|2013]], 63 votes (11.0%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2014|2014]], and 55 votes (10.0%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2015|2015]]) until he was finally eliminated after receiving only 54 votes (12.3%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2016|2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/hof_2016.shtml|title=2016 Hall of Fame Voting - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nA portion of [[Interstate 70 in Missouri#St. Louis|Interstate 70 in Missouri]] in St. Louis and near Busch Stadium was named \"Mark McGwire Highway\" to honor his 70 home run achievement, along with his various good works for the city. In May 2010, St. Louis politicians succeeded in passing a state bill to change the name of \"Mark McGwire Highway\", a 5-mile stretch of Interstate 70, to \"Mark Twain Highway\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10187/1070716-63.stm|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|first=J. Brady|last=McCollough|title=McGwire learning the 'art of coaching' as hitting instructor with the Cardinals|date=July 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Records===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+'''MLB and team records'''\n|-\n!Accomplishment\n!Record\n!Date(s)\n!Refs\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| Major League Baseball records\n|-\n| Fewest at-bats to 500 career home runs\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5,487\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999\n|<ref name=atbatto500hr/>\n|-\n| Fewest career at bats per home run\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10.6\n|<ref name=atperhr/>\n|-\n| Home runs in a four-season period\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 245\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1996\u20131999\n|\n|-\n| Consecutive 50-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|\n|-\n| 50-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4<sup>\u2020\u2020</sup>\n|\n|-\n| Consecutive 60-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1998\u20131999\n|\n|-\n| Home runs in a two-season period\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 135\n|\n|-\n| Single-season highest RBI/H ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1.014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999\n|\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| Oakland Athletics records\n|-\n| Lowest career AB/HR ratio\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 12.1\n|\n|-\n| Career HR\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 363\n|\n|-\n| Lowest single-season AB/HR ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8.1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995, 1996\n|\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| St. Louis Cardinals records\n|-\n| Lowest career AB/HR ratio\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 7.9\n|\n|-\n| Highest career OPS\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1.222\n|\n|-\n| Highest career OPS+\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 180\n|\n|-\n| Highest career SLG\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| .683\n|\n|-\n| Lowest single-season AB/HR ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7.3\n|rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1998\n|\n|-\n| Most HR in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 70\n|\n|-\n| Most times on base in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 320\n|\n|-\n| Most bases on balls in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 162\n|\n|}\n<small>\u2020 \u2013 ''tied with [[Sammy Sosa]]''</small>\n\n<small>\u2020\u2020 \u2013 ''tied with [[Babe Ruth]] and [[Sammy Sosa]]''</small>\n\n===Playing career totals===\n\nIn 16 seasons playing major league baseball (1986\u20132001), McGwire accumulated the following career totals:<ref name=\"BaseballRefMain\" />\n{{col-begin|width=}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Games played|G]] 1,874\n* [[At bat|ABs]] 6,187\n* [[Run (baseball)|Runs]] 1,167\n* [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]] 1,626\n* [[Double (baseball)|Doubles]] 252\n* [[Triple (baseball)|Triples]] 6\n* [[Home run|HR]] 583\n* [[Runs batted in|RBI]] 1,414\n* [[Grounded into double play|GIDP]] 147\n* [[Base on balls|BB]] 1,317\n* [[Intentional Walk|IBB]] 150\n{{col-break|distance=6}}\n* [[Hit by pitch|HBP]] 75\n* [[Sacrifice bunt|SH]] 3\n* [[Sacrifice fly|SF]] 78\n* [[Strikeout]]s 1,596\n* [[Stolen base|SBs]] 12\n* [[Caught stealing|CS]] 8\n* [[Batting average (baseball)|BA]] .263\n* [[On-base percentage|OBP]] .394\n* [[Slugging percentage|SLG]] .588\n* [[On-base plus slugging|OPS]] .982\n* [[OPS+#Adjusted OPS (OPS+)|OPS+]] 162\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Steroid use==\n\nIn a 1998 article by [[Associated Press]] writer [[Steve Wilstein]], McGwire admitted to taking [[androstenedione]],<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Who Knew? |work=ESPN.com |page= |date=September 11, 2005|accessdate=December 22, 2010 |quote= |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=steroids&num=8}}</ref> an over-the-counter muscle enhancement product that had already been banned by the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]], the [[National Football League|NFL]], and the [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]]; however, use of the substance was not prohibited by [[Major League Baseball]] at the time, and it was not federally classified as an anabolic steroid in the United States until 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=108_cong_bills&docid=f:s2195enr.txt.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 7, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725235620/http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=108_cong_bills |archive-date=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Jose Canseco]] released a book, ''[[Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits & How Baseball Got Big]]'', in 2005. In it, he wrote positively about steroids and made various claims\u2014among them, that McGwire had used performance-enhancing drugs since the 1980s and that Canseco had personally injected him with them.\n\nIn 2005, McGwire and Canseco were among 11 baseball players and executives subpoenaed to testify at a congressional hearing on steroids. During his testimony on March 17, 2005, McGwire declined to answer questions under oath when he appeared before the [[House Government Reform Committee]]. In a tearful opening statement, McGwire said:\n\n{{quote|Asking me or any other player to answer questions about who took [[steroids]] in front of television cameras will not solve the problem. If a player answers 'No,' he simply will not be believed; if he answers 'Yes,' he risks public scorn and endless government investigations&nbsp;... My lawyers have advised me that I cannot answer these questions without jeopardizing my friends, my family, and myself. I will say, however, that it remains a fact in this country that a man, any man, should be regarded as innocent unless proven guilty.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/ALLPOLITICS/03/17/steroids.baseball/ |work=CNN | date=March 18, 2005 | accessdate=May 12, 2010 | title=CNN.com}}</ref>}}\nOn January 11, 2010, McGwire admitted to [[Banned substances in baseball in the United States|using steroids]] on and off for a decade and said, \"I wish I had never touched steroids. It was foolish and it was a mistake. I truly apologize. Looking back, I wish I had never played during the steroid era.\"<ref name=\"ESPNAdmission\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4816607|title=McGwire admits steroids use|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 11, 2010}}</ref> He admitted using them in the 1989/90 offseason and then after he was injured in 1993. He admitted using them on occasion throughout the 1990s, including during the 1998 season. McGwire said that he used steroids to recover from injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100122&content_id=7955290&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Steroid supplier disputes McGwire's motive|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire's decision to admit using steroids was prompted by his decision to become hitting coach of the St. Louis Cardinals. According to McGwire, he took steroids for health reasons rather than to improve performance; however, a drug dealer who claimed to have provided steroids to McGwire asserted that his use was to improve his size and strength, rather than to just maintain his health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100111&content_id=7900244&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl|title=McGwire admits to steroid use: Will appear on MLB Network tonight to discuss admission|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcGwire's brother [[Dan McGwire]] was a [[quarterback]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] and [[Miami Dolphins]] of the [[National Football League|NFL]] in the early 1990s, and was a first-round draft choice out of [[San Diego State University]]. He has another brother, Jay McGwire, a bodybuilder, who wrote a book in 2010 detailing their shared steroid use.<ref>Mark and Me: Mark McGwire and the Truth Behind Baseball's Worst-Kept Secret</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/otl/news/story?id=4941099|title=Book: McGwire's brother shares steroids secrets|date=February 24, 2010|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire married Stephanie Slemer\u2014a former [[pharmaceutical sales representative]] from the St. Louis area\u2014in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] on April 20, 2002. On June 1, 2010, their triplet girls were born: Monet Rose, Marlo Rose, and Monroe Rose. They join brothers Max and Mason. They reside in a [[gated community]] in Shady Canyon [[Irvine, California]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|title=A Moorish fantasy in Irvine's Shady Canyon|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 2, 2008|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/orange/la-re-home2mar02,1,3528751.story|accessdate=May 19, 2008}}</ref> Together they created the Mark McGwire Foundation for Children to support agencies that help children who have been sexually and physically abused come to terms with a difficult childhood. Mark has a son, Matthew (b. 1987), from a previous marriage (1984\u20131990, divorced) to Kathleen Hughes.\n\nPrior to admitting to using steroids, McGwire avoided the media and spent much of his free time playing golf.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=mcgwire&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab1pos1 |title=ESPN.com \u2013 E-Ticket: Fading Away |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> He also worked as a hitting coach for Major League players [[Matt Holliday]], [[Bobby Crosby]], [[Chris Duncan]] and [[Skip Schumaker]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3976320 McGwire Talks About Teaching Hitting] ESPN.com, March 13, 2009</ref>\n\nMcGwire appeared as himself in season 7, episode 13 of the sitcom ''[[Mad About You]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0638994/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_8 |title=Mad About You--IMDB listing |date=February 22, 1999 |website=https://www.imdb.com |publisher=Internet Movie Database |access-date=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire provided his voice for an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' titled \"[[Brother's Little Helper]]\", where he played himself.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles|Biography|Baseball|Olympics}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase]]\n* [[50 home run club]]\n* [[500 home run club]]\n* [[At bats per home run]]\n* [[List of doping cases in sport]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball home run records]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career bases on balls leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career extra base hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career OPS leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career strikeouts by batters leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career slugging percentage leaders]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals team records]]\n* [[Major League Baseball titles leaders]]\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals award winners and league leaders]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Lupica|first=Mike|year=1999|title=Summer of '98: When Homers Flew, Records Fell, and Baseball Reclaimed America |location=Chicago|publisher=Contemporary Books|title-link=Summer of '98}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=118743|espn=1738|br=m/mcgwima01|fangraphs=1008559|brm=mcgwir001mar}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-ach}}}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mo Vaughn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|American League Player of the Month]]|years=June 1996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Juan Gonz\u00e1lez (baseball)|Juan Gonz\u00e1lez]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Finley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Two or more 3-home run games in a season|years=1998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeff Bagwell]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Piazza]]<br />[[Jeff Kent]]<br />[[Jeromy Burnitz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|National League Player of the Month]]|years=September 1997; April & May 1998<br />September 1998<br />July 1999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sammy Sosa]]<br />[[Matt Williams (third baseman)|Matt Williams]]<br />[[Vladimir Guerrero]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Roger Maris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball single-season home run record#Progression|Single season home run record holder]]|years=1998\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Barry Bonds]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Larry Walker]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of National League Slugging Percentage Leaders|National League Slugging Percentage Champion]]|years=1998}}\n{{s-aft|after =Larry Walker}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hal McRae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches|St. Louis Cardinals Hitting Coach]]|years=2010\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Mabry]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Hansen (baseball)|Dave Hansen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Los Angeles Dodgers coaches|Los Angeles Dodgers Hitting Coach]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Turner Ward]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Roberts (outfielder)|Dave Roberts]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[San Diego Padres|San Diego Padres Bench Coach]]|years=2016\u2013}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBA}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{navboxes|list1=\n{{2011 St. Louis Cardinals}}\n{{1989 Oakland Athletics}}\n{{Oakland Athletics}}\n{{MLBACT}}\n{{Commissioner's Historic Achievement Award}}\n{{50 home run club|state=collapsed}}\n{{500 home run club}}\n{{NL home run champions}}\n{{AL home run champions}}\n{{NL RBI champions}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{Marvin Miller Man of the Year Award}}\n{{Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{Baseball America Major League Player of the Year Award}}\n{{SI Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{SN Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{ESPY Male Athlete}}\n{{Home Run Derby champions}}\n{{AL First Baseman Gold Glove Award}}\n{{NL 1B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{AL 1B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{AL Rookie of the Year}}\n{{Oakland Athletics first-round draft picks}}\n{{1984 MLB Draft}}\n{{Pacific-12 Conference Baseball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{1984 College Baseball All-Americans}}\n{{United States baseball roster 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGwire, Mark}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League home run champions]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople in doping cases]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1983 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in baseball]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Huntsville Stars players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers coaches]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball bench coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Modesto A's players]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National League home run champions]]\n[[Category:National League RBI champions]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pomona, California]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Tigers players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans baseball players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player and coach}}\n{{for|the American musician|Mark McGuire (musician)}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Mark McGwire\n|image=Mark_McGwire_Padres_coach_May_2017.jpg\n|image_size=240\n|caption= McGwire with the [[San Diego Padres]] in 2017\n|team=\n|number=\n|width=250\n|position=[[First baseman]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1963|10|1}}\n|birth_place=[[Pomona, California]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=August 22\n|debutyear=1986\n|debutteam=Oakland Athletics\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=October 7\n|finalyear=2001\n|finalteam=St. Louis Cardinals\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.263\n|stat2label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat2value=583\n|stat3label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat3value=1,414\n|teams=\n'''As player'''\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|1986}}\u2013{{mlby|1997}})\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|1997}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n'''As coach'''\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2012}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2016}}\u2013{{mlby|2018}}) \n|highlights=\n* 12\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1987]]\u2013[[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992]], [[1995 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1995]]\u2013[[2000 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2000]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1989}}, {{wsy|2011}})\n* [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|AL Rookie of the Year]] (1987)\n* [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Award]] (1990)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (1992, 1996, 1998)\n* 5\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB home run leader]] (1987, 1996\u20131999)\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders|NL RBI leader]] (1999)\n* [[Athletics Hall of Fame]]\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame Museum|St. Louis Cardinals Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]\n|medaltemplates=\n{{Medal|Country|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Baseball]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Baseball at the 1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Pan American Games]]}}\n{{Medal|Bronze|[[Baseball at the Pan American Games|1983 Caracas]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Intercontinental Cup (baseball)|Intercontinental Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Silver|[[Intercontinental Cup (baseball)|1983 Brussels]]|[[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n\n}}\n\n'''Mark David McGwire''' (born October 1, 1963), nicknamed '''Big Mac''', is an [[Americans|American]] former [[professional baseball]] [[first baseman]]. His [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) playing career spanned from 1986 to 2001 while playing for the [[Oakland Athletics]] and the [[St. Louis Cardinals]], winning one [[World Series]] championship each with Oakland as a player in [[1989 World Series|1989]] and with St. Louis as a coach in [[2011 World Series|2011]].  One of the most prolific [[home run]] hitters in baseball history, McGwire holds the major league career record for [[at bats per home run]] ratio (10.6), and is the former record holder for both [[List of Major League Baseball progressive single-season home run leaders|home runs in a single season]] (70 in 1998) and home runs hit by rookie (49 in 1987).  \n\nHe ranks 11th all time in [[home run]]s with 583, and led the major leagues in home runs in five different seasons, while establishing the major league record for home runs hit in a four-season period from 1996 to 1999 with 245.  Further, he demonstrated exemplary patience as a batter, producing a career .394 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and twice leading the major leagues in [[bases on balls]].  Injuries cut short the manifestation of even greater potential as he reached 140 games played in just eight of 16 total seasons.  A right-handed batter and thrower, McGwire stood {{convert|6|ft|5|in|m}} tall and weighed {{convert|245|lb}} during his playing career.\n\nA part of the [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase]] of [[Roger Maris]]' 61 with the Cardinals, McGwire set the [[Major League Baseball single-season home run record|major league single-season home run record]] with 70,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/HR_progress.shtml |title=Progressive Leaders & Records for Home Runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> which [[Barry Bonds]] broke three years later with 73.<ref name=Bonds-testified>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1937594 |title=\"Bonds testified that substances didn't work\", ESPN.com, December 4, 2004, accessed 02/03/11 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=December 4, 2004 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  McGwire also led the league in [[runs batted in]], twice in [[bases on balls]] and [[on-base percentage]], and four times in [[slugging percentage]]. Injuries significantly cut into his playing time in 2000 and 2001 before factoring into his retirement. He finished with 583 home runs, which was [[500 home run club|fifth all-time]] when he retired.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/mcgwima01.shtml|title=Mark McGwire Stats {{!}} Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2017-03-17}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire was a central figure in baseball's [[doping in baseball|steroids scandal]]. In 2010, McGwire publicly admitted to using performance-enhancing drugs during a large portion of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/12/sports/baseball/12mcgwire.html?pagewanted=all|title=McGwire Admits That He Used Steroids - NYTimes.com|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|publisher=}}</ref> In his first ten years of eligibility, McGwire has not been elected into the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/11/29/hall-of-fame-todays-game-ballot-mark-mcgwire|title=McGwire gets second HOF shot, but is he worthy?|first=Jay|last=Jaffe|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\n\nMcGwire was born in [[Pomona, California]]. His father was a [[dentist]]. He attended [[Damien High School]] in [[La Verne, California]], where he played baseball, golf, and basketball. He was drafted by the [[Montreal Expos]] in the 1981 amateur draft but did not sign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/mcgwima01.shtml|title=Mark McGwire Stats - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> He played college baseball at the [[University of Southern California]] (where he was a teammate of [[Randy Johnson]] and [[Jack Del Rio]]) under coach [[Rod Dedeaux]].\n\nMcGwire was selected by the Athletics with the 10th overall selection in the [[1984 Major League Baseball draft|1984 MLB draft]]. \n\nHe was a member of the [[silver medal]]-winning entry of the [[United States national baseball team|United States national team]]<nowiki/> that [[Baseball  at the 1984 Summer Olympics|same year]]<nowiki/>at the [[1984 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]], with Japan finishing ahead for gold medal.\n\n==Playing career (1984\u20132001)==\n\n===Oakland Athletics (1984\u20131997)===\n\nAfter three years at Southern California and a stint on the 1984 U.S. Olympic team, the [[Oakland Athletics]] drafted McGwire tenth overall in the [[1984 Major League Baseball draft]].\n\nMcGwire debuted in the major leagues in August [[1986 Oakland Athletics season|1986]], hitting three [[home run]]s and nine [[runs batted in]] in 18 games.\n\n====Rookie home run record and major league leader (1987)====\n\nRetaining his rookie status in [[1987 Major League Baseball season|1987]], McGwire took center stage in baseball with his home runs. He hit just four in the month of April, but followed in May with 15, and another nine in June. Before the All-Star break arrived, he totaled 33 HR and earned a spot on the [[American League]] (AL) [[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star team]]. On August 11, he broke [[Al Rosen]]'s AL rookie record of 37 home runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/APAB/lib00581,122CA98E1CEF7498.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120708140841/http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/APAB/lib00581,122CA98E1CEF7498.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 8, 2012|date=August 10, 2008}}</ref>  Three days later, McGwire broke the major league record of 38, which [[Frank Robinson]] and [[Wally Berger]] jointly held. In September, McGwire hit nine more home runs while posting monthly personal bests of a .351 [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]], .419 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and 11 [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (2B). With 49 HR and two games remaining in the regular season, he chose to sit them out with an opportunity for 50 home runs to be present for the birth of his first child. McGwire also totaled 118 [[runs batted in]] (RBI), .289 batting average, 97 [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored, 28 doubles, a .618 [[slugging percentage]] and a .370 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP). McGwire's 49 home runs as a rookie stood as a major league record until [[Aaron Judge]] hit 52 for the [[New York Yankees]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/news/yankees-aaron-judge-sets-rookie-hr-record-mark-mcgwire/xyqbr125vm8k13f1ips4sg1nl|title=Yankees' Aaron Judge breaks Mark McGwire's rookie HR record|date=2017-09-26|work=Sporting News|access-date=2017-12-02}}</ref>\n\nNot only did he lead the AL in home runs in 1987, but he also tied for the major league lead with [[1987 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] right fielder [[Andre Dawson]]. McGwire also led the major leagues in SLG, finished second in the AL in adjusted [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage (OPS+, 164) total bases (344), third in RBI and on-base plus slugging (OPS, .987). He was thus a unanimous choice for the AL [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]] and finished sixth overall in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\n====More All-Star appearances (1988\u201391)====\n\n[[File:Mark McGwire 1989.jpg|thumb|left|McGwire with the A's, 1989]]\n\nFrom [[1988 Oakland Athletics season|1988]] to [[1990 Oakland Athletics season|1990]], McGwire followed with 32, 33, and 39 home runs, respectively, becoming the first Major Leaguer to hit 30+ home runs in each of his first four full seasons.<ref name=\"BaseballRefMain\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcgwima01.shtml |title=Mark McGwire Statistics |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  On July 3 and 4, 1988, he hit game-winning home runs in the 16th inning of both games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/TOR/TOR198807030.shtml |title=July 3, 1988 Oakland Athletics at Toronto Blue Jays play by play and box score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=July 3, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE198807040.shtml |title=July 4, 1988 Oakland Athletics at Cleveland Indians Jays play by play and box score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=July 4, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Through May 2009, McGwire was tied for third all-time with [[Joe DiMaggio]] in home runs over his first two calendar years in the major leagues (71), behind [[Chuck Klein]] (83) and [[Ryan Braun]] (79).<ref>[https://nationalpost.com/sports/story.html?id=1633915 Sandler, Jeremy, \"NL Weekly: The Notebook\", National Post, May 27, 2009, accessed 5/28/09]{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire's most famous home run with the A's was likely his game-winning solo shot in the bottom of the ninth inning of Game 3 of the [[1988 World Series]] against the [[1988 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] and former A's [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Jay Howell]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/OAK/OAK198810180.shtml |title=October 18, 1988 World Series Game 3 at Network Associates Coliseum Play by Play and Box Score |website=Baseball-Reference.com |date=October 18, 1988 |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>  McGwire's game-winner brought the A's their only victory in the 1988 World Series, which they lost in five games; however, McGwire and his fellow [[Bash Brother]], [[Jos\u00e9 Canseco]], played a large part in the 1989 championship club that defeated the [[1989 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]] in the famous \"[[1989 World Series|Earthquake Series]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1989_WS.shtml |title=1989 World Series \u2013 OAK vs. SFG |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWorking diligently on his defense at first base, McGwire bristled at the notion that he was a one-dimensional player. He was generally regarded as a good fielder in his early years, even winning a [[Gold Glove Award]] in [[1990 Major League Baseball season|1990]] \u2013 the only one that [[New York Yankees]] legend [[Don Mattingly]] would not win between [[1985 Major League Baseball season|1985]] and [[1994 Major League Baseball season|1994]]. In later years, his mobility decreased and, with it, his defense; however, McGwire's batting averages after his rookie season plummeted to .260, .231, and .235 from 1988 to 1990. In 1991, he bottomed out with a .201 average and 22 homers. [[List of Oakland Athletics managers|Manager]] [[Tony La Russa]] sat him out the final game of the [[1991 Oakland Athletics season|season]] to avoid allowing his batting average to dip below .200. Despite the declining averages during this time of his career, his high [[bases on balls]] totals allowed him to maintain acceptable OBPs. In fact, when he hit .201, his OPS+ was 103, or just over league average.\n\nMcGwire stated in an interview with ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' that 1991 was the \"worst year\" of his life, with his on-field performance and marriage difficulties, and that he \"didn't lift a weight\" that entire season. With all that behind him, McGwire re-dedicated himself to working out harder than ever and received visual therapy from a sports vision specialist.<ref>[http://www.sdccd.edu/events/we/wepdf/we-sp99.pdf] https://web.archive.org/web/20150701040841/http://www.sdccd.edu/events/we/wepdf/we-sp99.pdf</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/features/mcgwire/flashbacks/060192/ |work=CNN |accessdate=May 12, 2010 |title=Oakland's Mark McGwire is smiling again, now that he's hitting homers at a record pace |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104193550/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/features/mcgwire/flashbacks/060192/ |archivedate=November 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n====Career resurgence (1992\u201397)====\n\nThe \"new look\" McGwire hit 42 homers and batted .268 in 1992, with an outstanding OPS+ of 175 (the highest of his career to that point), and put on a home run hitting show at the [[Home Run Derby]] during the [[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992 All-Star break]]. His performance propelled the [[1992 Oakland Athletics season|A's]] to the American League West Division title in 1992, their fourth in five seasons. The A's lost in the [[1992 American League Championship Series|playoffs]] to the eventual [[1992 World Series|World Series]] champion, the [[1992 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]].\n\nFoot injuries limited McGwire to a total of 74 games in [[1993 Oakland Athletics season|1993]] and [[1994 Oakland Athletics season|1994]], and just 9 home runs in each of the two seasons. He played just 104 games in [[1995 Oakland Athletics season|1995]], but his proportional totals were much improved: 39 home runs in 317 at-bats. In [[1996 Oakland Athletics season|1996]], McGwire belted a major league leading 52 homers in 423 at-bats. He also hit a career high .312 average, and led the league in both slugging percentage and on-base percentage.\n\nMcGwire's total of 363 home runs with the Athletics surpassed the previous franchise record. He was selected or voted to nine [[American League]] All-Star Teams while playing for the A's, including six consecutive appearances from [[1987 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1987]] through [[1992 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1992]]. He was one of only four players to hit a ball over the roof in the left field of [[Tiger Stadium (Detroit)|Tiger Stadium]].<ref>The Final Season, p.90, Tom Stanton, Thomas Dunne Books, An imprint of St. Martin's Press, New York, 2001, {{ISBN|0-312-29156-6}}</ref>\n\n===St. Louis Cardinals (1997\u20132001)===\n\n[[File:Mark mcgwire.jpg|thumb|right|McGwire hitting a home run in St. Louis against the Tigers on July 14, 2001]]\nOn July 31, having already amassed 34 home runs to this point in the [[1997 in baseball|1997 season]], McGwire was traded from the [[1997 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] to the [[1997 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] for [[T. J. Mathews]], [[Eric Ludwick]] and [[Blake Stein]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/sports/article/THE-BIG-DEALS-THE-A-S-McGwire-finally-traded-2831502.php|title=THE BIG DEALS / THE A'S / McGwire finally traded -- to Cards|publisher=}}</ref> Despite playing just two-thirds of the season in the American League, he finished ninth in home runs. In 51 games with the Cardinals to finish the 1997 season, McGwire compiled a .253 batting average, 24 home runs, and 42 RBI. Overall in 1997, McGwire led the majors with 58 home runs. He also finished third in the major leagues in slugging percentage (.646), fourth in OPS (1.039), fifth in OPS+ (170), tenth in RBI (123), and ninth in walks (101). He placed 16th in the NL MVP voting.\n\nIt was the last year of his contract, so there was speculation that McGwire would play for the Cardinals only for the remainder of the season, then seek a long-term deal, possibly in Southern California, where he still lived; however, McGwire signed a contract to stay in St. Louis. It is also believed that McGwire later encouraged [[Jim Edmonds]], another Southern California resident who was traded to St. Louis, to forgo free agency and sign a contract with the Cardinals in 2000.\n\n====Single-season home run record chase (1998)====\n\nAs the [[1998 St. Louis Cardinals season|1998 season]] progressed, it became clear that McGwire, [[1998 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]] outfielder [[Ken Griffey Jr.]], and [[1998 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] outfielder [[Sammy Sosa]] were all on track to break [[Roger Maris]]'s single-season home run record. [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase|The race to break the record]] first attracted media attention as the home run leader changed often throughout the season. On August 19, Sosa hit his 48th home run to move ahead of McGwire; however, later that day McGwire hit his 48th and 49th home runs to regain the lead.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nOn September 8, 1998, McGwire hit a pitch by the Cubs' [[Steve Trachsel]] over the left field wall for his record-breaking 62nd home run, setting off massive celebrations at [[Busch Memorial Stadium|Busch Stadium]]. The fact that the game was against the Cubs meant that Sosa was able to congratulate McGwire personally on his achievement. Members of Maris's family were also present at the game. The ball was freely, albeit controversially, given to McGwire in a ceremony on the field by the stadium worker who found it.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nMcGwire finished the 1998 season with 70 home runs (including five in his last three games), four ahead of Sosa's 66, a record that was broken three seasons later in 2001 by [[Barry Bonds]] with 73.<ref name=Bonds-testified/>\n\nMcGwire was honored with the inaugural [[Babe Ruth Home Run Award]] for leading Major League Baseball in home runs.<ref name=harber>{{cite news|last=Harber|first=Paul|title=A statue fit for a home run king|date=July 22, 2001|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8659756.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130602104753/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8659756.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 2, 2013|accessdate=November 8, 2011|quote=The first award was given to Mark McGwire after his 70-home-run season in 1998.}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Although McGwire had the prestige of the home run record, Sammy Sosa (who had fewer HR but more RBI and stolen bases) won the 1998 NL MVP award, as his contributions helped propel the Cubs to the [[1998 National League Division Series|playoffs]] (the [[1998 St. Louis Cardinals season|Cardinals]] in 1998 finished third in the NL Central). Many credited the Sosa-McGwire home run chase in 1998 with \"saving baseball\", by both bringing in new, younger fans and bringing back old fans soured by the [[1994\u201395 Major League Baseball strike]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/30/sports/myth-of-men-who-saved-baseball.html|title=Myth of men who saved baseball|date=March 30, 2005|publisher=|via=www.nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\n====Later playing career (1999\u20132001)====\nMcGwire kept his high level of offensive production from 1998 going in [[1999 St. Louis Cardinals season|1999]] while setting or extending several significant records. For the fourth consecutive season, he led MLB in home runs with 65. It was also his fourth consecutive season with at least 50 home runs, extending his own major league record. Sosa, who hit 63 home runs in 1999, again trailed McGwire. Thus, they became the first, and still only, players in major league history to hit 60 or more home runs in consecutive seasons. McGwire also set a record from 1998 to 1999 for home runs in a two-season period with 135. Further, he owned the highest four-season HR total, with 245 from 1996 to 1999. In 1999, he drove in an NL-leading 147 runs while only having 145 hits, the highest RBI-per-hit tally for a season in baseball history.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}}\n\nStatistically in 2000 and 2001, McGwire's numbers declined relative to previous years as he struggled to avoid injury (32 HR in 89 games, and 29 HR in 97 games, respectively). He retired after the 2001 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/mcgwima01.shtml |title=Baseball-reference.om McGwire stats |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career (2010-2018)==\n[[File:Mark McGwire on June 29, 2011.jpg|220px|thumb|McGwire as coach for the [[2011 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals in 2011]]]]\nAfter his playing career ended, McGwire demonstrated coaching ability, personally assisting players such as [[Matt Holliday]], [[Bobby Crosby]] and [[Skip Schumaker]] before accepting an official role as hitting coach with an MLB team. On October 26, 2009, [[Tony La Russa]], then [[List of St. Louis Cardinals managers|manager]] of the Cardinals, confirmed that McGwire would become the club's fifth [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches|hitting coach]] of his tenure with the Cardinals, replacing [[Hal McRae]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100107&content_id=7887624&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl |title=McGwire to speak, but date not set: Cards GM hopeful new hitting coach will appear soon |publisher=MLB.com |date=January 7, 2010 |accessdate=January 11, 2010}}</ref>  McGwire received a standing ovation prior to the Cardinals home opener on April 12, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news;_ylt=AjP3IcZXdVWvfZt.c6hW8uYRvLYF?slug%3Dap-cardinals-mcgwire  |accessdate=2014-07-21 |df=mdy }}{{dead link|date=September 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In his three seasons as Cardinals hitting coach, they featured a prolific offense that led the National League in hitting and on-base percentage, and were second in runs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hernandez |first=Dylan |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/baseball/mlb/dodgers/la-sp-1103-dodgers-mark-mcgwire-20121103,0,2702730.story |title=Mark McGwire expected to be Dodgers' hitting coach |newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn early November, 2012, McGwire rejected a contract extension to return as Cardinals hitting coach for the 2013 season. Instead, he accepted an offer for the same position with the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Gurnick|first=Ken|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20121102&content_id=40155526&vkey=news_stl&c_id=stl|title=Report: McGwire to become Dodgers' hitting coach|publisher=MLB.com via St. Louis Cardinals website|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 3, 2012}}</ref> in order to be closer to his wife and five children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/mlb-big-league-stew/report-mark-mcgwire-close-joining-los-angeles-dodgers-221746224--mlb.html|title=Report: Mark McGwire close to joining Los Angeles Dodgers as hitting coach|publisher=Yahoo sports|date=November 2, 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2013, McGwire was [[Ejection (sports)|ejected]] for the first time as a coach during a [[bench-clearing brawl]] with the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]].<ref>\"[http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/06/mlb-ejections-071-072-073-074-075-076.html MLB Ejections 071, 072, 073, 074, 075, 076: Clint Fagan (3\u20138)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130801232535/http://www.closecallsports.com/2013/06/mlb-ejections-071-072-073-074-075-076.html |date=August 1, 2013 }}.\" ''Close Call Sports/Umpire Ejection Fantasy League''. June 12, 2013.</ref>  He was suspended for two games starting the next day.\n\nOn December 2, 2015, he was named the new bench coach for the [[San Diego Padres]]. He left the team after the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25065289/mark-mcgwire-return-san-diego-padres-bench-coach |title=Mark McGwire not returning as Padres' coach to spend time with family |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=October 23, 2018 |accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honors, records and achievements==\nKnown as one of the top sluggers of his era, McGwire ended his career with 583 home runs, which was fifth-most in history when he retired. When he hit his 500th career home run in 1999, he did so in 5,487 career at bats, the fewest in major league history.<ref name=\"atbatto500hr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hi500c.shtml|title=500 Home Run Details|date=|publisher=Baseball-Almanac.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216025541/http://www.baseball-almanac.com/hitting/hi500c.shtml|archive-date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref>  He led all MLB in home runs in five different seasons, including 1987 and each season from 1996 to 1999. Totaling 245 home runs from 1996\u221299, it was the highest four-season home run output in major league history. Further, in each of those four seasons, he exceeded 50 home runs, becoming the first player to do so. He was also the first player to hit 49 or more home runs five times, including his rookie-season record of 49 in 1987. With a career average of one home every 10.61 at-bats, he holds the MLB record for most home runs per at-bat by over a full at-bat more than second-place Babe Ruth (11.76).<ref name=\"atperhr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/ABpHR_career.shtml|title=Career Leaders & Records for at bats per home run|website=Baseball-Reference.com|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228202538/http://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/ABpHR_career.shtml|archive-date=February 28, 2009|accessdate=November 7, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2015, McGwire owned three of the four lowest single-season AB/HR ratios in MLB history, which covered his 1996, 1998 and 1999 seasons. They were actually the top three seasons in MLB history until Bonds broke his single-season HR record in 2001. McGwire's 1997 season ranked 13th.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/at_bats_per_home_run_season.shtml |title=Single-season leaders & records for AB per HR |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>  Considered one of the slowest running players in the game, McGwire had the fewest career triples (six) of any player with 5,000 or more at-bats, and had just 12 stolen bases while being caught stealing eight times.\n\n===Honors and distinctions===\n\nIn 1999, ''[[The Sporting News]]'' released a list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, ranking McGwire at number 91. The list had been compiled during the [[1998 in baseball|1998 season]] and included statistics through the [[1997 in baseball|1997 season]]. That year, he was elected to the [[Major League Baseball All-Century Team]]. In 2005, ''The Sporting News'' published an update of their list, and McGwire had been moved up to Number 84.\n\nMcGwire first became eligible for [[National Baseball Hall of Fame & Museum|Hall of Fame]] voting in 2007. For election, a player needs to be listed on 75% of ballots cast; falling under 5% removes a player from future consideration. Between 2007 and 2010 McGwire's performance held steady, receiving 128 votes (23.5%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2007|2007]], 128 votes (23.6%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2008|2008]], 118 votes (21.9%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2009|2009]], and 128 votes (23.7%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2010|2010]]. The subsequent ballot in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2011|2011]] showed the first sub-20% total of 115 votes (19.8%), and McGwire's total votes continued to decline (112 votes (19.5%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2012|2012]], 96 votes (16.9%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2013|2013]], 63 votes (11.0%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2014|2014]], and 55 votes (10.0%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2015|2015]]) until he was finally eliminated after receiving only 54 votes (12.3%) in [[Baseball Hall of Fame balloting, 2016|2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/hof_2016.shtml|title=2016 Hall of Fame Voting - Baseball-Reference.com|website=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nA portion of [[Interstate 70 in Missouri#St. Louis|Interstate 70 in Missouri]] in St. Louis and near Busch Stadium was named \"Mark McGwire Highway\" to honor his 70 home run achievement, along with his various good works for the city. In May 2010, St. Louis politicians succeeded in passing a state bill to change the name of \"Mark McGwire Highway\", a 5-mile stretch of Interstate 70, to \"Mark Twain Highway\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10187/1070716-63.stm|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|first=J. Brady|last=McCollough|title=McGwire learning the 'art of coaching' as hitting instructor with the Cardinals|date=July 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Records===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|+'''MLB and team records'''\n|-\n!Accomplishment\n!Record\n!Date(s)\n!Refs\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| Major League Baseball records\n|-\n| Fewest at-bats to 500 career home runs\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5,487\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999\n|<ref name=atbatto500hr/>\n|-\n| Fewest career at bats per home run\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10.6\n|<ref name=atperhr/>\n|-\n| Home runs in a four-season period\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 245\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1996\u20131999\n|\n|-\n| Consecutive 50-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|\n|-\n| 50-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4<sup>\u2020\u2020</sup>\n|\n|-\n| Consecutive 60-HR seasons\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2<sup>\u2020</sup>\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1998\u20131999\n|\n|-\n| Home runs in a two-season period\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 135\n|\n|-\n| Single-season highest RBI/H ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1.014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1999\n|\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| Oakland Athletics records\n|-\n| Lowest career AB/HR ratio\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 12.1\n|\n|-\n| Career HR\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 363\n|\n|-\n| Lowest single-season AB/HR ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8.1\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1995, 1996\n|\n|-\n! style=\"background:#dde;\" colspan=\"4\"| St. Louis Cardinals records\n|-\n| Lowest career AB/HR ratio\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 7.9\n|\n|-\n| Highest career OPS\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1.222\n|\n|-\n| Highest career OPS+\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| 180\n|\n|-\n| Highest career SLG\n|colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: center;\"| .683\n|\n|-\n| Lowest single-season AB/HR ratio\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 7.3\n|rowspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1998\n|\n|-\n| Most HR in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 70\n|\n|-\n| Most times on base in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 320\n|\n|-\n| Most bases on balls in a season\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 162\n|\n|}\n<small>\u2020 \u2013 ''tied with [[Sammy Sosa]]''</small>\n\n<small>\u2020\u2020 \u2013 ''tied with [[Babe Ruth]] and [[Sammy Sosa]]''</small>\n\n===Playing career totals===\n\nIn 16 seasons playing major league baseball (1986\u20132001), McGwire accumulated the following career totals:<ref name=\"BaseballRefMain\" />\n{{col-begin|width=}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Games played|G]] 1,874\n* [[At bat|ABs]] 6,187\n* [[Run (baseball)|Runs]] 1,167\n* [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]] 1,626\n* [[Double (baseball)|Doubles]] 252\n* [[Triple (baseball)|Triples]] 6\n* [[Home run|HR]] 583\n* [[Runs batted in|RBI]] 1,414\n* [[Grounded into double play|GIDP]] 147\n* [[Base on balls|BB]] 1,317\n* [[Intentional Walk|IBB]] 150\n{{col-break|distance=6}}\n* [[Hit by pitch|HBP]] 75\n* [[Sacrifice bunt|SH]] 3\n* [[Sacrifice fly|SF]] 78\n* [[Strikeout]]s 1,596\n* [[Stolen base|SBs]] 12\n* [[Caught stealing|CS]] 8\n* [[Batting average (baseball)|BA]] .263\n* [[On-base percentage|OBP]] .394\n* [[Slugging percentage|SLG]] .588\n* [[On-base plus slugging|OPS]] .982\n* [[OPS+#Adjusted OPS (OPS+)|OPS+]] 162\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Steroid use==\n\nIn a 1998 article by [[Associated Press]] writer [[Steve Wilstein]], McGwire admitted to taking [[androstenedione]],<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Who Knew? |work=ESPN.com |page= |date=September 11, 2005|accessdate=December 22, 2010 |quote= |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=steroids&num=8}}</ref> an over-the-counter muscle enhancement product that had already been banned by the [[World Anti-Doping Agency]], the [[National Football League|NFL]], and the [[International Olympic Committee|IOC]]; however, use of the substance was not prohibited by [[Major League Baseball]] at the time, and it was not federally classified as an anabolic steroid in the United States until 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=108_cong_bills&docid=f:s2195enr.txt.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=July 7, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725235620/http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=108_cong_bills |archive-date=July 25, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[Jose Canseco]] released a book, ''[[Juiced: Wild Times, Rampant 'Roids, Smash Hits & How Baseball Got Big]]'', in 2005. In it, he wrote positively about steroids and made various claims\u2014among them, that McGwire had used performance-enhancing drugs since the 1980s and that Canseco had personally injected him with them.\n\nIn 2005, McGwire and Canseco were among 11 baseball players and executives subpoenaed to testify at a congressional hearing on steroids. During his testimony on March 17, 2005, McGwire declined to answer questions under oath when he appeared before the [[House Government Reform Committee]]. In a tearful opening statement, McGwire said:\n\n{{quote|Asking me or any other player to answer questions about who took [[steroids]] in front of television cameras will not solve the problem. If a player answers 'No,' he simply will not be believed; if he answers 'Yes,' he risks public scorn and endless government investigations&nbsp;... My lawyers have advised me that I cannot answer these questions without jeopardizing my friends, my family, and myself. I will say, however, that it remains a fact in this country that a man, any man, should be regarded as innocent unless proven guilty.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/ALLPOLITICS/03/17/steroids.baseball/ |work=CNN | date=March 18, 2005 | accessdate=May 12, 2010 | title=CNN.com}}</ref>}}\nOn January 11, 2010, McGwire admitted to [[Banned substances in baseball in the United States|using steroids]] on and off for a decade and said, \"I wish I had never touched steroids. It was foolish and it was a mistake. I truly apologize. Looking back, I wish I had never played during the steroid era.\"<ref name=\"ESPNAdmission\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=4816607|title=McGwire admits steroids use|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=January 11, 2010}}</ref> He admitted using them in the 1989/90 offseason and then after he was injured in 1993. He admitted using them on occasion throughout the 1990s, including during the 1998 season. McGwire said that he used steroids to recover from injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100122&content_id=7955290&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Steroid supplier disputes McGwire's motive|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire's decision to admit using steroids was prompted by his decision to become hitting coach of the St. Louis Cardinals. According to McGwire, he took steroids for health reasons rather than to improve performance; however, a drug dealer who claimed to have provided steroids to McGwire asserted that his use was to improve his size and strength, rather than to just maintain his health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stlouis.cardinals.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100111&content_id=7900244&vkey=news_stl&fext=.jsp&c_id=stl|title=McGwire admits to steroid use: Will appear on MLB Network tonight to discuss admission|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcGwire's brother [[Dan McGwire]] was a [[quarterback]] for the [[Seattle Seahawks]] and [[Miami Dolphins]] of the [[National Football League|NFL]] in the early 1990s, and was a first-round draft choice out of [[San Diego State University]]. He has another brother, Jay McGwire, a bodybuilder, who wrote a book in 2010 detailing their shared steroid use.<ref>Mark and Me: Mark McGwire and the Truth Behind Baseball's Worst-Kept Secret</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/otl/news/story?id=4941099|title=Book: McGwire's brother shares steroids secrets|date=February 24, 2010|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire married Stephanie Slemer\u2014a former [[pharmaceutical sales representative]] from the St. Louis area\u2014in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] on April 20, 2002. On June 1, 2010, their triplet girls were born: Monet Rose, Marlo Rose, and Monroe Rose. They join brothers Max and Mason. They reside in a [[gated community]] in Shady Canyon [[Irvine, California]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Ryon|first=Ruth|title=A Moorish fantasy in Irvine's Shady Canyon|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 2, 2008|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/orange/la-re-home2mar02,1,3528751.story|accessdate=May 19, 2008}}</ref> Together they created the Mark McGwire Foundation for Children to support agencies that help children who have been sexually and physically abused come to terms with a difficult childhood. Mark has a son, Matthew (b. 1987), from a previous marriage (1984\u20131990, divorced) to Kathleen Hughes.\n\nPrior to admitting to using steroids, McGwire avoided the media and spent much of his free time playing golf.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=mcgwire&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab1pos1 |title=ESPN.com \u2013 E-Ticket: Fading Away |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> He also worked as a hitting coach for Major League players [[Matt Holliday]], [[Bobby Crosby]], [[Chris Duncan]] and [[Skip Schumaker]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3976320 McGwire Talks About Teaching Hitting] ESPN.com, March 13, 2009</ref>\n\nMcGwire appeared as himself in season 7, episode 13 of the sitcom ''[[Mad About You]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0638994/?ref_=nm_flmg_slf_8 |title=Mad About You--IMDB listing |date=February 22, 1999 |website=https://www.imdb.com |publisher=Internet Movie Database |access-date=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcGwire provided his voice for an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' titled \"[[Brother's Little Helper]]\", where he played himself.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Greater Los Angeles|Biography|Baseball|Olympics}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[1998 Major League Baseball home run record chase]]\n* [[50 home run club]]\n* [[500 home run club]]\n* [[At bats per home run]]\n* [[List of doping cases in sport]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball home run records]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career bases on balls leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career extra base hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career OPS leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs scored leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career runs batted in leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career strikeouts by batters leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career slugging percentage leaders]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n* [[List of St. Louis Cardinals team records]]\n* [[Major League Baseball titles leaders]]\n* [[St. Louis Cardinals award winners and league leaders]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Lupica|first=Mike|year=1999|title=Summer of '98: When Homers Flew, Records Fell, and Baseball Reclaimed America |location=Chicago|publisher=Contemporary Books|title-link=Summer of '98}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{commons category}}\n{{Baseballstats|mlb=118743|espn=1738|br=m/mcgwima01|fangraphs=1008559|brm=mcgwir001mar}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-ach}}}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mo Vaughn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|American League Player of the Month]]|years=June 1996}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Juan Gonz\u00e1lez (baseball)|Juan Gonz\u00e1lez]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Finley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Two or more 3-home run games in a season|years=1998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeff Bagwell]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mike Piazza]]<br />[[Jeff Kent]]<br />[[Jeromy Burnitz]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|National League Player of the Month]]|years=September 1997; April & May 1998<br />September 1998<br />July 1999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sammy Sosa]]<br />[[Matt Williams (third baseman)|Matt Williams]]<br />[[Vladimir Guerrero]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Roger Maris]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Major League Baseball single-season home run record#Progression|Single season home run record holder]]|years=1998\u20132000}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Barry Bonds]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Larry Walker]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of National League Slugging Percentage Leaders|National League Slugging Percentage Champion]]|years=1998}}\n{{s-aft|after =Larry Walker}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Hal McRae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of St. Louis Cardinals coaches|St. Louis Cardinals Hitting Coach]]|years=2010\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Mabry]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Hansen (baseball)|Dave Hansen]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Los Angeles Dodgers coaches|Los Angeles Dodgers Hitting Coach]]|years=2013\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Turner Ward]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Dave Roberts (outfielder)|Dave Roberts]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[San Diego Padres|San Diego Padres Bench Coach]]|years=2016\u2013}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBA}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{navboxes|list1=\n{{2011 St. Louis Cardinals}}\n{{1989 Oakland Athletics}}\n{{Oakland Athletics}}\n{{MLBACT}}\n{{Commissioner's Historic Achievement Award}}\n{{50 home run club|state=collapsed}}\n{{500 home run club}}\n{{NL home run champions}}\n{{AL home run champions}}\n{{NL RBI champions}}\n{{Lou Gehrig Memorial Award}}\n{{Marvin Miller Man of the Year Award}}\n{{Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{Baseball America Major League Player of the Year Award}}\n{{SI Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{SN Sportsman of the Year}}\n{{ESPY Male Athlete}}\n{{Home Run Derby champions}}\n{{AL First Baseman Gold Glove Award}}\n{{NL 1B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{AL 1B Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{AL Rookie of the Year}}\n{{Oakland Athletics first-round draft picks}}\n{{1984 MLB Draft}}\n{{Pacific-12 Conference Baseball Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{1984 College Baseball All-Americans}}\n{{United States baseball roster 1984 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGwire, Mark}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League home run champions]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople in doping cases]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1983 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in baseball]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Huntsville Stars players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers coaches]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball bench coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball first basemen]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball hitting coaches]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award winners]]\n[[Category:Modesto A's players]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:National League home run champions]]\n[[Category:National League RBI champions]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Irvine, California]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Pomona, California]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals coaches]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:Tacoma Tigers players]]\n[[Category:USC Trojans baseball players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for the United States in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:All-American college baseball players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball controversies]]\n", "name_user": "107.77.210.175", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_McGwire"}
{"title_page": "Robert Lecker", "text_new": "'''Robert Lecker''' {{post-nominals|FRSC}} is a Canadian scholar, author, and Greenshields Professor of English at [[McGill University]], where he specializes in [[Canadian literature]].<ref name=\"McG\">[https://www.mcgill.ca/english/staff/robert-lecker Faculty page, Department of English, McGill University]</ref> He received the H. Noel Fieldhouse Award for Distinguished Teaching at McGill University in 1996. Lecker is a leading authority on Canadian literature. In 2012, Lecker was named a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] in recognition of his influential studies on literary value in English Canada and Canadian cultural identity.<ref>Royal Society of Canada, [http://www.science.uottawa.ca/sites/default/files/science/pdf/royal_en.pdf \"Class of 2012: List of New Fellows.\"]</ref><ref>[http://publications.mcgill.ca/reporter/2012/09/royal-society-of-canada-honours-12-mcgill-researchers-and-scholars/ \"Royal Society of Canada honours 12 McGill researchers and scholars.\"] ''McGill Reporter'' 6 Sept. 2012.</ref> In addition to his teaching and academic writing, Lecker has held a number of prominent positions in the Canadian publishing industry throughout his career. He founded [[ECW Press]] in 1997, he co-edited the Canadian literary journal ''Essays on Canadian Writing'' between 1975 and 2004, he has edited several anthologies of Canadian and international literature, and he currently heads a literary agency in Montreal, the [https://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nLecker was born and raised in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] and began his university studies at Sir George Williams University (now [[Concordia University]]) in 1970. The following year, he transferred to [[York University]] in [[Toronto]] where he met Jack David, who had founded the critical journal ''Essays on Canadian Writing'' in 1974. Lecker joined the editorial board of ''ECW'' in 1975.\n\n===Academic training and teaching posts===\nLecker completed his BA (1974), MA (1976), and PhD (1980) in English at York and was awarded a number of fellowships and scholarships throughout these years. Lecker discusses his formative experiences at York in his 2006 memoir, ''Dr. Delicious''. His PhD dissertation, \u201cTime and Form in the Contemporary Canadian Novel,\u201d examines disruptive representations of time in seven Canadian novels written between 1968 and 1977.\n\nIn 1977 Lecker and Jack David founded ECW Press, which was originally devoted to publishing reference works and critical studies about Canadian literature. The press expanded and moved into commercial trade publishing in the mid-1990s. Lecker managed the Montreal office and David ran the Toronto office. In 2003, Lecker left the press to start his own literary agency, [http://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency].\n\nBetween 1978 and 1982, Lecker was Assistant Professor of English at the [[University of Maine at Orono]].\n\nLecker began teaching at McGill University in 1982. He was Associate Chair of the Department of English from 1984 to 1986, and directed the M.A. Program from 1989 to 1993. He also served as a sexual harassment and discrimination officer for McGill University from 1995 to 1997 and 2005 to 2007. From 1996 to 1998 Lecker was a member of the adjudication committee for the Canada-U.S. Fulbright Program, and in 1999 he was Chair of that committee.\n\n==Books and articles ==\nLecker is the author of eight books, which are all critical studies of either Canadian authors or theoretical problems related to the study and history of Canadian literature. Over the past 15 years he has focused on two areas in particular: canonicity in Canadian literature and anthology formation as a reflection of the evolution of literary value and taste. He is currently completing a study of Canadian authors and their literary agents with a special emphasis on Montreal agent, Doris Hedges. In addition to his book publications, Lecker has authored over 60 scholarly articles in journals and books in Canada, the US, and overseas, including ''PMLA'','' Critical Inquiry'', ''Canadian Literature'', ''Canadian Poetry'', ''Open Letter'', ''Studies in Canadian Literature'', ''Australasian Canadian Studies'', and the ''American Review of Canadian Studies''.\n\n'''''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation'' (2013)'''\n\n''Keepers of the Code'' is the first book-length history of English-Canadian literary anthologies from 1837 to the present. Lecker aims to show that these anthologies, like all literature, are shaped by the conflict and contact among various individuals and institutions, including publishers, writers, reviewers, professors, tenure committees, funding agencies, critical journals, banks, and the bookselling industry. Lecker comments in detail on approximately 75 anthologies. Although there are scattered articles that focus on these questions in terms of English-Canadian anthologies, this is the first sustained historical study. The book was released in March 2013 and was positively reviewed in the ''Times Literary Supplement''.<ref>Hammill, Faye. Rev. of ''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation'', by Robert Lecker. ''Times Literary Supplement'' 17 May 2013.</ref>\n\n'''''The Cadence of Civil Elegies'' (2006)'''\n\n[[Dennis Lee (author)|Dennis Lee]]\u2019s poem, ''Civil Elegies'', originally published in 1968 and revised in 1972, remains one of the most potent poems devoted to the nature of Canadian identity and civil space. In this study, Lecker shows us the poem\u2019s importance to Canada\u2019s literary canon, by emphasizing Lee's new vision of Canada.\n\n'''''Dr. Delicious: Memoirs of a Life in CanLit'' (2006)'''\n\nLecker's tragicomic memoir, ''Dr. Delicious'', reviews his career as a publisher and editor of Canadian literature and criticism. The book is an irreverent history of an explosive era in Canadian literature, a glimpse into the mind of a preoccupied professor, and a unique record of the generation that made Canadian literature what it is today.\n\n'''''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies: An Enumerative Bibliography'' (1997)'''\n\n''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies'' is first detailed bibliography of Canadian anthologies from 1837 to the present. It lists approximately 2000 anthologies and is the departure point for any comprehensive commentary on anthology formation in Canada.\n\n'''''Making It Real: The Canonization of English-Canadian Literature'' (1995)'''\n\nEight wide-ranging essays are brought together in this study of the origins and development of Canadian literary canons. Lecker explores many of the myths surrounding the teaching, studying, publishing, and promotion of Canadian literature. He focuses on the work of [[Northrop Frye]], [[Frank Davey]], and the [[New Canadian Library]] series.\n\n'''''An Other I: The Fictions of Clark Blaise'' (1988)'''\n\n''An Other I'' is a study of the fiction of [[Clark Blaise]].\n\n'''''Robert Kroetsch'' (1986)'''\n\n''Robert Kroetsch'' is a study of the poetry, fiction, and literary criticism of [[Robert Kroetsch]].\n\n'''''On the Line: Readings in the Short Fiction of Clark Blaise, John Metcalf, and Hugh Hood ''(1982)'''\n\n''On the Line'' includes detailed readings of individual stories by three prominent Canadian writers.\n\nConsult the [https://www.mcgill.ca/english/staff/robert-lecker McGill faculty website] for a full list of Lecker's publications, including academic articles.\n\n==Editorial work==\nLecker edited the 24-volume series entitled ''Canadian Writers and Their Works: Essays on Form, Context, and Development'' with Jack David and Ellen Quigley. This 24-volume series comprises almost 10,000 pages of commentary on 100 Canadian writers from the nineteenth century to the present. Each author is treated in a discrete essay that provides a biography, a critical overview, a description of the writer's milieu, an analysis of each of the writer's works, and a bibliography of primary and secondary material. The volumes are organized chronologically so as to present a historical perspective. The editors coordinated the production of these essays by 100 scholars and released the existing series over a ten-year period.\n\nLecker was the senior editor for several multi-volume series published by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] (New York) and G.K. Hall (Boston), including Masterworks and Critical Essays on World Literature. He was also the Canadian editor for Twayne\u2019s World Authors Series. Lecker has edited numerous anthologies of Canadian literature from 1981 to the present, including one large anthology for [[HarperCollins]] in New York (the only anthology of Canadian literature published by a mainstream American publisher since 1943).\n\n==Robert Lecker Agency==\nIn 2004, Lecker established the [http://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency] in Montreal. The agency provides international literary representation, consulting services, and editorial services.\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n===Books===\n* ''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 2013.\n* ''Dr. Delicious: Memoirs of a Life in CanLit''. Montreal, V\u00e9hicule Press, 2006.\n* ''The Cadence of Civil Elegies''. Toronto: Cormorant, 2006.\n* ''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies: An Enumerative Bibliography''. Compiler. Teeswater, ON: Reference, 1997.\n* ''Making It Real: The Canonization of English-Canadian Literature''. Toronto: Anansi, 1995.\n* ''An Other I: The Fictions of Clark Blaise''. Toronto: ECW, 1988.\n* ''Robert Kroetsch''. Boston: Twayne, 1986.\n* ''On the Line: Readings in the Short Fiction of Clark Blaise, John Metcalf, and Hugh Hood''. Downsview, ON: ECW, 1982.\n\n===Anthologies and Books Edited===\n* ''Anthologizing Canadian Literature: Theoretical and Cultural Perspectives''. Waterloo: Wilfrid Laurier UP. Forthcoming 2014.\n* ''Open Country: Canadian Literature in English''. Toronto: Thomson Nelson, 2007.\n* ''Borderlands: Essays in Canadian-American Relations''. Toronto: ECW, 1991.\n* ''Canadian Canons: Essays in Literary Value''. Toronto: U of Toronto P, 1991. (Shortlisted for the 1993 Canadian Federation for the Humanities Raymond Klibansky Book Prize for best work in the humanities)\n* ''The New Canadian Anthology: English-Canadian Poetry and Short Fiction''. Toronto: Nelson, 1988. With Jack David.\n* ''Introduction to Literature: British, American, Canadian''. New York: Harper & Row, 1987. With Jack David and Peter O'Brien.\n* ''Canadian Writers and Their Works: Essays on Form, Context, and Development'' (CWTW). Twenty-four volumes to date, in two series, 1982-  (Poetry and Fiction). With Jack David and Ellen Quigley.\n* ''Introduction to Fiction''. Toronto: Holt, Rinehart and Winston, 1983. \n* ''The Annotated Bibliography of Canada's Major Authors'' (ABCMA). Eight volumes to date, 1982- . With Jack David.\n* ''Anthology of Maine Literature''. Orono, Maine: U of Maine P, 1982. With Kathleen Brown.\n* ''Canadian Poetry''. Two Volumes. New Press Canadian Classics. Don Mills, ON: General. Volume One, 1982. Volume Two, 1982. With Jack David.\n* ''Introduction to Poetry: British, American, Canadian''. Toronto: Holt, Rinehart and Winston, 1981. With Jack David.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.leckeragency.com Robert Lecker Agency]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lecker, Robert}}\n[[Category:Canadian academics]]\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:McGill University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Robert Lecker''' {{post-nominals|FRSC}} is a Canadian scholar, author, and Greenshields Professor of English at [[McGill University]], where he specializes in [[Canadian literature]].<ref name=\"McG\">[https://www.mcgill.ca/english/staff/robert-lecker Faculty page, Department of English, McGill University]</ref> He received the H. Noel Fieldhouse Award for Distinguished Teaching at McGill University in 1996. Lecker is a leading authority on Canadian literature. In 2012, Lecker was named a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] in recognition of his influential studies on literary value in English Canada and Canadian cultural identity.<ref>Royal Society of Canada, [http://www.science.uottawa.ca/sites/default/files/science/pdf/royal_en.pdf \"Class of 2012: List of New Fellows.\"]</ref><ref>[http://publications.mcgill.ca/reporter/2012/09/royal-society-of-canada-honours-12-mcgill-researchers-and-scholars/ \"Royal Society of Canada honours 12 McGill researchers and scholars.\"] ''McGill Reporter'' 6 Sept. 2012.</ref> In addition to his teaching and academic writing, Lecker has held a number of prominent positions in the Canadian publishing industry throughout his career. He founded [[ECW Press]] in 1997, he co-edited the Canadian literary journal ''Essays on Canadian Writing'' between 1975 and 2004, he has edited several anthologies of Canadian and international literature, and he currently heads a literary agency in Montreal, the [https://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nLecker was born and raised in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]] and began his university studies at Sir George Williams University (now [[Concordia University]]) in 1970. The following year, he transferred to [[York University]] in [[Toronto]] where he met Jack David, who had founded the critical journal ''Essays on Canadian Writing'' in 1974. Lecker joined the editorial board of ''ECW'' in 1975.\n\n===Academic training and teaching posts===\nLecker completed his BA (1974), MA (1976), and PhD (1980) in English at York and was awarded a number of fellowships and scholarships throughout these years. Lecker discusses his formative experiences at York in his 2006 memoir, ''Dr. Delicious''. His PhD dissertation, \u201cTime and Form in the Contemporary Canadian Novel,\u201d examines disruptive representations of time in seven Canadian novels written between 1968 and 1977.\n\nIn 1977 Lecker and Jack David founded ECW Press, which was originally devoted to publishing reference works and critical studies about Canadian literature. The press expanded and moved into commercial trade publishing in the mid-1990s. Lecker managed the Montreal office and David ran the Toronto office. In 2003, Lecker left the press to start his own literary agency, [http://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency].\n\nBetween 1978 and 1982, Lecker was Assistant Professor of English at the [[University of Maine at Orono]].\n\nLecker began teaching at McGill University in 1982. He was Associate Chair of the Department of English from 1984 to 1986, and directed the M.A. Program from 1989 to 1993. He also served as a sexual harassment and discrimination officer for McGill University from 1995 to 1997 and 2005 to 2007. From 1996 to 1998 Lecker was a member of the adjudication committee for the Canada-U.S. Fulbright Program, and in 1999 he was Chair of that committee.\n\n==Books and articles ==\nLecker is the author of eight books, which are all critical studies of either Canadian authors or theoretical problems related to the study and history of Canadian literature. Over the past 15 years he has focused on two areas in particular: canonicity in Canadian literature and anthology formation as a reflection of the evolution of literary value and taste. He is currently completing a study of Canadian authors and their literary agents with a special emphasis on Montreal agent, Doris Hedges. In addition to his book publications, Lecker has authored over 60 scholarly articles in journals and books in Canada, the US, and overseas, including ''PMLA'','' Critical Inquiry'', ''Canadian Literature'', ''Canadian Poetry'', ''Open Letter'', ''Studies in Canadian Literature'', ''Australasian Canadian Studies'', and the ''American Review of Canadian Studies''.\n\n'''''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation'' (2013)'''\n\n''Keepers of the Code'' is the first book-length history of English-Canadian literary anthologies from 1837 to the present. Lecker aims to show that these anthologies, like all literature, are shaped by the conflict and contact among various individuals and institutions, including publishers, writers, reviewers, professors, tenure committees, funding agencies, critical journals, banks, and the bookselling industry. Lecker comments in detail on approximately 75 anthologies. Although there are scattered articles that focus on these questions in terms of English-Canadian anthologies, this is the first sustained historical study. The book was released in March 2013 and was positively reviewed in the ''Times Literary Supplement''.<ref>Hammill, Faye. Rev. of ''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation'', by Robert Lecker. ''Times Literary Supplement'' 17 May 2013.</ref>\n\n'''''The Cadence of Civil Elegies'' (2006)'''\n\n[[Dennis Lee (author)|Dennis Lee]]\u2019s poem, ''Civil Elegies'', originally published in 1968 and revised in 1972, remains one of the most potent poems devoted to the nature of Canadian identity and civil space. In this study, Lecker shows us the poem\u2019s importance to Canada\u2019s literary canon, by emphasizing Lee's new vision of Canada.\n\n'''''Dr. Delicious: Memoirs of a Life in CanLit'' (2006)'''\n\nLecker's tragicomic memoir, ''Dr. Delicious'', reviews his career as a publisher and editor of Canadian literature and criticism. The book is an irreverent history of an explosive era in Canadian literature, a glimpse into the mind of a preoccupied professor, and a unique record of the generation that made Canadian literature what it is today.\n\n'''''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies: An Enumerative Bibliography'' (1997)'''\n\n''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies'' is first detailed bibliography of Canadian anthologies from 1837 to the present. It lists approximately 2000 anthologies and is the departure point for any comprehensive commentary on anthology formation in Canada.\n\n'''''Making It Real: The Canonization of English-Canadian Literature'' (1995)'''\n\nEight wide-ranging essays are brought together in this study of the origins and development of Canadian literary canons. Lecker explores many of the myths surrounding the teaching, studying, publishing, and promotion of Canadian literature. He focuses on the work of [[Northrop Frye]], [[Frank Davey]], and the [[New Canadian Library]] series.\n\n'''''An Other I: The Fictions of Clark Blaise'' (1988)'''\n\n''An Other I'' is a study of the fiction of [[Clark Blaise]].\n\n'''''Robert Kroetsch'' (1986)'''\n\n''Robert Kroetsch'' is a study of the poetry, fiction, and literary criticism of [[Robert Kroetsch]].\n\n'''''On the Line: Readings in the Short Fiction of Clark Blaise, John Metcalf, and Hugh Hood ''(1982)'''\n\n''On the Line'' includes detailed readings of individual stories by three prominent Canadian writers.\n\nConsult the [https://www.mcgill.ca/english/staff/robert-lecker McGill faculty website] for a full list of Lecker's publications, including academic articles.\n\n==Editorial work==\nLecker edited the 24-volume series entitled ''Canadian Writers and Their Works: Essays on Form, Context, and Development'' with Jack David and Ellen Quigley. This 24-volume series comprises almost 10,000 pages of commentary on 100 Canadian writers from the nineteenth century to the present. Each author is treated in a discrete essay that provides a biography, a critical overview, a description of the writer's milieu, an analysis of each of the writer's works, and a bibliography of primary and secondary material. The volumes are organized chronologically so as to present a historical perspective. The editors coordinated the production of these essays by 100 scholars and released the existing series over a ten-year period.\n\nLecker was the senior editor for several multi-volume series published by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]] (New York) and G.K. Hall (Boston), including Masterworks and Critical Essays on World Literature. He was also the Canadian editor for Twayne\u2019s World Authors Series. Lecker has edited numerous anthologies of Canadian literature from 1981 to the present, including one large anthology for [[HarperCollins]] in New York (the only anthology of Canadian literature published by a mainstream American publisher since 1943).\n\n==Robert Lecker Agency==\nIn 2004, Lecker established the [http://www.leckeragency.com/ Robert Lecker Agency] in Montreal. The agency provides international literary representation, consulting services, and editorial services.\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n===Books===\n* ''Keepers of the Code: English-Canadian Literary Anthologies and the Representation of Nation''. Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 2013.\n* ''Dr. Delicious: Memoirs of a Life in CanLit''. Montreal, V\u00e9hicule Press, 2006.\n* ''The Cadence of Civil Elegies''. Toronto: Cormorant, 2006.\n* ''English-Canadian Literary Anthologies: An Enumerative Bibliography''. Compiler. Teeswater, ON: Reference, 1997.\n* ''Making It Real: The Canonization of English-Canadian Literature''. Toronto: Anansi, 1995.\n* ''An Other I: The Fictions of Clark Blaise''. Toronto: ECW, 1988.\n* ''Robert Kroetsch''. Boston: Twayne, 1986.\n* ''On the Line: Readings in the Short Fiction of Clark Blaise, John Metcalf, and Hugh Hood''. Downsview, ON: ECW, 1982.\n\n===Anthologies and Books Edited===\n* ''Anthologizing Canadian Literature: Theoretical and Cultural Perspectives''. Waterloo: Wilfrid Laurier UP. Forthcoming 2014.\n* ''Open Country: Canadian Literature in English''. Toronto: Thomson Nelson, 2007.\n* ''Borderlands: Essays in Canadian-American Relations''. Toronto: ECW, 1991.\n* ''Canadian Canons: Essays in Literary Value''. Toronto: U of Toronto P, 1991. (Shortlisted for the 1993 Canadian Federation for the Humanities Raymond Klibansky Book Prize for best work in the humanities)\n* ''The New Canadian Anthology: English-Canadian Poetry and Short Fiction''. Toronto: Nelson, 1988. With Jack David.\n* ''Introduction to Literature: British, American, Canadian''. New York: Harper & Row, 1987. With Jack David and Peter O'Brien.\n* ''Canadian Writers and Their Works: Essays on Form, Context, and Development'' (CWTW). Twenty-four volumes to date, in two series, 1982-  (Poetry and Fiction). With Jack David and Ellen Quigley.\n* ''Introduction to Fiction''. Toronto: Holt, Rinehart and Winston, 1983. \n* ''The Annotated Bibliography of Canada's Major Authors'' (ABCMA). Eight volumes to date, 1982- . With Jack David.\n* ''Anthology of Maine Literature''. Orono, Maine: U of Maine P, 1982. With Kathleen Brown.\n* ''Canadian Poetry''. Two Volumes. New Press Canadian Classics. Don Mills, ON: General. Volume One, 1982. Volume Two, 1982. With Jack David.\n* ''Introduction to Poetry: British, American, Canadian''. Toronto: Holt, Rinehart and Winston, 1981. With Jack David.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.leckeragency.com Robert Lecker Agency]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lecker, Robert}}\n[[Category:Canadian academics]]\n[[Category:Canadian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:McGill University faculty]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "LiteratureCompanion", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Lecker"}
{"title_page": "Mina (Japanese singer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Japanese-American singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Mina\n| image              = 171030 \ud2b8\uc640\uc774\uc2a4 LIKEY \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4 \ubbf8\ub098 (2).jpg\n| image_size         =\n| landscape          =\n| caption            = Mina in October 2017\n| native_name        = \u540d\u4e95\u5357\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name         = Mina My\u014di<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite web |title=K-POP\u306e\u6700\u6ce8\u76ee\u65b0\u4eba\u300cTWICE\u300d\u306e\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u304c\u53ef\u611b\u304f\u3066\u7f8e\u3057\u3044\uff1c\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb\uff1e |url=https://mdpr.jp/k-enta/detail/1550147 |language=Japanese |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1997|3|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Antonio, Texas]], U.S.<ref name=\"time_article\">{{cite web |last1=Moon |first1=Kat |title=Everything to Know About K-Pop Group Twice |url=https://time.com/5671342/twice-k-pop-everything-to-know/ |website=Time |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|Dancer}}\n| signature          =\n| background       = solo_singer<!--mandatory field-->\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[J-pop]]}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = [[JYP Entertainment|JYP]]\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Twice (band)|Twice]]|[[JYP Nation]]}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Mina My\u014di'''|\u540d\u4e95 \u5357|My\u014di Mina|born March 24, 1997}}, known mononymously as '''Mina''' (Hangul: \ubbf8\ub098; [[Japanese language|Japanese]]: {{Nihongo2|\u30df\u30ca}}), is a Japanese-American singer based in South Korea and a member of the girl group [[Twice (group)|Twice]], formed by [[JYP Entertainment]]. Mina is one of Twice's three Japanese members.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kpopland>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: Taking off to K-Pop Land |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901784.html |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mendez |first1=Michele |title=Who Is Momo? TWICE's \"Dance Machine\"s Story Is An Emotional Rollercoaster |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-momo-twices-dance-machines-story-is-emotional-rollercoaster-19295358 |website=Elite Daily |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMina was born on March 24, 1997 in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]],<ref name=\"Name\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\">{{cite web |last1=Vacco-Bola\u00f1os |first1=Jessica |title=Who Is TWICE's Mina? 5 Things You Need To Know |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-twices-mina-5-things-you-need-to-know-19261743 |website=Elite Daily |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> and grew up in [[Kobe]], [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]], Japan.<ref name=pt1>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: The Story Begins |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901655.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/> Mina trained in [[ballet]] from a young age, having practiced it for over a decade before debuting with Twice.<ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=kpopland/> She attended Obayashi Sacred Heart School.<ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/> In 2017 it was reported that Mina holds dual Japanese and American citizenship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herman |first1=Tamar |title=K-Pop Group TWICE: By The Numbers |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2017/11/09/twice-by-the-numbers/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=December 7, 2019 |date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Debut and career==\n{{Main|Sixteen (TV series)|Twice (group)}}\n===Debut with Twice===\nMina was shopping with her mother in [[Osaka]] when she was approached and offered an audition by a JYP recruiter.<ref name=kpopland/> She later departed for South Korea in 2014 to become a [[Korean idol|K-pop idol]] by becoming a trainee under [[JYP Entertainment]].<ref name=kpopland/><ref>{{cite web |title=JYP\uc758 \ucde8\ud5a5\u2502\u2462 \uc5f4\uc5ec\uc12f \uba85\uc758 [\uc2dd\uc2a4\ud2f4] \uba64\ubc84\ub4e4\uc744 \uc18c\uac1c\ud569\ub2c8\ub2e4 |url=http://www.ize.co.kr/articleView.html?no=2015051720137261442 |website=IZE |accessdate=November 30, 2019 |language=ko |date=May 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: In the Lion's Den |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901797.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> In 2015 Mina participated in the South Korean [[reality television]] show ''[[Sixteen (TV series)|Sixteen]]'', hosted by JYP Entertainment and co-produced by [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Won |first1=Ho-jung |title='Sixteen' compete for spot in JYP's next girl group |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20150429001117 |website=The Korea Herald |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> As one of nine successful participants, she went on to join the newly-formed girl group [[Twice (group)|Twice]].<ref name=\"time_article\"/> In October 2015 Mina officially debuted as a member of Twice with their first extended play, ''[[The Story Begins]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Yu-jin |title=TWICE unveils debut album 'The Story Begins' |url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201510201348537808518_2 |website=The Korea Herald |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The lead single \"[[Like Ooh-Ahh]]\" was the first K-pop debut song to reach 100 million views on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"time_2\"/>\n\n===Health issues===\nOn July 11, 2019, JYP Entertainment announced that Mina would sit out the remainder of Twice's ongoing [[List of Twice concert tours#Twice World Tour 2019\u20132020 \"Twicelights\"|World Tour]] due to sudden extreme anxiety and insecurity problems regarding performing on stage.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |title=Twice: K-Pop star Mina pulls out of tour due to 'extreme anxiety' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/48948583 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name='koreatimes'>{{cite web |last1=Dong |first1=Sun-hwa |title=Extreme anxiety forces TWICE's Mina from world tour |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2019/07/732_272220.html |website=Korea Times |accessdate=December 1, 2019|date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> This incident received coverage in many news organisations across the world.<ref name=\"time_2\"/><ref name=\"bbc\"/><ref name='koreatimes'/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Emma |title=TWICE's Mina pulls out of world tour due to 'extreme anxiety' |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/11/twices-mina-pulls-world-tour-due-extreme-anxiety-10175805/ |website=Metro |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ko |first1=Dong-hwan |title=Fans believe Twice member Mina was forced out of world tour by Anti-Japan bullies |url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/entertainment/article/3019913/fans-believe-twice-member-mina-was-forced-out-world-tour |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderton |first1=Joe |title=K-pop band Twice member Mina pulls out of world tour over mental health struggles |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/a28384623/k-pop-twice-mina-pulls-out-world-tour-mental-health/ |website=Digital Spy |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 13, 2019}}</ref> She was later diagnosed with an [[anxiety disorder]].<ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/><ref name=\"time_2\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Khouri |first1=Samar |title=K-Pop Corner: Twice member Mina diagnosed with anxiety disorder |url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/music/k-pop-corner-twice-member-mina-diagnosed-with-anxiety-disorder-1.66127011 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=August 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=JYP Entertainment update on Mina's health & future activities with TWICE |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/08/27/jyp-entertainment-update-minas-health-future-activities-twice |website=SBS |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=August 27, 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, Mina returned to join fellow Twice members at a fan event.<ref name=metro>{{cite web |last1=Adejobi |first1=Alicia |title=TWICE star Mina's future still undecided despite surprise appearance at fourth anniversary |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/21/twice-star-minas-future-still-undecided-despite-surprise-appearance-fourth-anniversary-10954295/ |website=Metro |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> JYP Entertainment released a statement saying that Mina's \"future schedule has not yet been decided\" and that they would \"prioritise the state of her health above all else\".<ref name=metro/>\n\n==Public image==\nMina is known for being one of Twice's main dancers<ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/><ref name=\"time_2\">{{cite web |last1=Moon |first1=Kat |title=K-Pop Powerhouse TWICE Opens Up About How Their New Album Is More Personal Than Ever |url=https://time.com/5696384/twice-interview-feel-special/ |website=Time |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> and has received recognition in South Korea and abroad.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kind>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: The 1st of Their Kind |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901859.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Her popularity \u2013 in conjunction with that of fellow Japanese members [[Momo Hirai|Momo]] and [[Sana (singer)|Sana]] \u2013 has been credited with improving relations between Japan and South Korea by the ''[[Chosun Ilbo]]''.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kind/> In [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] Korea's annual music poll of 2019, she was voted the 16th most popular idol in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/12/20/heres-who-koreans-voted-top-artists-and-idols-2019|title=Here's who Koreans voted as the top artists and idols of 2019|date=2019-12-20|website=SBS PopAsia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=1072|title=2019\ub144 \uc62c\ud574\ub97c \ube5b\ub0b8 \uac00\uc218\uc640 \uac00\uc694 \u2013 \ucd5c\uadfc 13\ub144\uac04 \ucd94\uc774 \ud3ec\ud568|date=November 28, 2019|publisher=Gallup Korea|language=ko|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Twice discography}}\n\n===Songwriting credits===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Song\n!Album\n!Artist\n!With\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Shot Thru The Heart\"<ref>{{cite web|title=TWICE THE 2ND SPECIAL ALBUM Summer Nights TRACK LIST|url=http://twice.jype.com/notice.asp?idx=1432&page=21&vnum=157|website=TWICE JYPE|accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|''[[Summer Nights (Twice album)|Summer Nights]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Twice\n|[[Hirai Momo|Momo]] and [[Sana (singer)|Sana]]\n|-\n|2019\n|\"21:29\"<ref>{{cite web|title=TWICE THE 8TH MINI ALBUM Feel Special Track List|url=https://twice.jype.com/notice.asp?idx=1891&page=&vnum=377|website=TWICE JYPE|accessdate=December 12, 2019|date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n|''[[Feel Special]]''\n|All Twice members\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Twice (group)}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Korea]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Japanese female singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese idols]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers]]\n[[Category:JYP Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Korean-language singers of Japan]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kobe]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Reality show winners]]\n[[Category:Twice members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese-American singer}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name               = Mina\n| image              = 171030 \ud2b8\uc640\uc774\uc2a4 LIKEY \uc1fc\ucf00\uc774\uc2a4 \ubbf8\ub098 (2).jpg\n| image_size         =\n| landscape          =\n| caption            = Mina in October 2017\n| native_name        = \u540d\u4e95\u5357\n| native_name_lang   = ja\n| birth_name         = Mina My\u014di<ref name=\"Name\">{{cite web |title=K-POP\u306e\u6700\u6ce8\u76ee\u65b0\u4eba\u300cTWICE\u300d\u306e\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc\u304c\u53ef\u611b\u304f\u3066\u7f8e\u3057\u3044\uff1c\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb\uff1e |url=https://mdpr.jp/k-enta/detail/1550147 |language=Japanese |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1997|3|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Antonio, Texas]], U.S.<ref name=\"time_article\">{{cite web |last1=Moon |first1=Kat |title=Everything to Know About K-Pop Group Twice |url=https://time.com/5671342/twice-k-pop-everything-to-know/ |website=Time |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Singer|Dancer}}\n| signature          =\n| background       = solo_singer<!--mandatory field-->\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[J-pop]]}}\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| years_active     = 2015\u2013present\n| label            = [[JYP Entertainment|JYP]]\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Twice (band)|Twice]]|[[JYP Nation]]}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Mina My\u014di'''|\u540d\u4e95 \u5357|My\u014di Mina|born March 24, 1997}}, known mononymously as '''Mina''' (Hangul: \ubbf8\ub098; [[Japanese language|Japanese]]: {{Nihongo2|\u30df\u30ca}}), is a Japanese-American singer based in South Korea and a member of the girl group [[Twice (group)|Twice]], formed by [[JYP Entertainment]]. Mina is one of Twice's three Japanese members.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kpopland>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: Taking off to K-Pop Land |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901784.html |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mendez |first1=Michele |title=Who Is Momo? TWICE's \"Dance Machine\"s Story Is An Emotional Rollercoaster |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-momo-twices-dance-machines-story-is-emotional-rollercoaster-19295358 |website=Elite Daily |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=November 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMina was born on March 24, 1997 in [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]],<ref name=\"Name\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\">{{cite web |last1=Vacco-Bola\u00f1os |first1=Jessica |title=Who Is TWICE's Mina? 5 Things You Need To Know |url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/who-is-twices-mina-5-things-you-need-to-know-19261743 |website=Elite Daily |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 23, 2019}}</ref> and grew up in [[Kobe]], [[Hy\u014dgo Prefecture]], Japan.<ref name=pt1>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: The Story Begins |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901655.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/> Mina trained in ballet from a young age, having practiced it for over a decade before debuting with Twice.<ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=kpopland/> She attended Obayashi Sacred Heart School.<ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/> In 2017 it was reported that Mina holds dual Japanese and American citizenship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Herman |first1=Tamar |title=K-Pop Group TWICE: By The Numbers |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2017/11/09/twice-by-the-numbers/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=December 7, 2019 |date=November 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Debut and career==\n{{Main|Sixteen (TV series)|Twice (group)}}\n===Debut with Twice===\nMina was shopping with her mother in [[Osaka]] when she was approached and offered an audition by a JYP recruiter.<ref name=kpopland/> She later departed for South Korea in 2014 to become a [[Korean idol|K-pop idol]] by becoming a trainee under [[JYP Entertainment]].<ref name=kpopland/><ref>{{cite web |title=JYP\uc758 \ucde8\ud5a5\u2502\u2462 \uc5f4\uc5ec\uc12f \uba85\uc758 [\uc2dd\uc2a4\ud2f4] \uba64\ubc84\ub4e4\uc744 \uc18c\uac1c\ud569\ub2c8\ub2e4 |url=http://www.ize.co.kr/articleView.html?no=2015051720137261442 |website=IZE |accessdate=November 30, 2019 |language=ko |date=May 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: In the Lion's Den |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901797.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 22, 2018}}</ref> In 2015 Mina participated in the South Korean [[reality television]] show ''[[Sixteen (TV series)|Sixteen]]'', hosted by JYP Entertainment and co-produced by [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Won |first1=Ho-jung |title='Sixteen' compete for spot in JYP's next girl group |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20150429001117 |website=The Korea Herald |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=April 29, 2015}}</ref> As one of nine successful participants, she went on to join the newly-formed girl group [[Twice (group)|Twice]].<ref name=\"time_article\"/> In October 2015 Mina officially debuted as a member of Twice with their first extended play, ''[[The Story Begins]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Yu-jin |title=TWICE unveils debut album 'The Story Begins' |url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201510201348537808518_2 |website=The Korea Herald |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The lead single \"[[Like Ooh-Ahh]]\" was the first K-pop debut song to reach 100 million views on [[YouTube]].<ref name=\"time_2\"/>\n\n===Health issues===\nOn July 11, 2019, JYP Entertainment announced that Mina would sit out the remainder of Twice's ongoing [[List of Twice concert tours#Twice World Tour 2019\u20132020 \"Twicelights\"|World Tour]] due to sudden extreme anxiety and insecurity problems regarding performing on stage.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |title=Twice: K-Pop star Mina pulls out of tour due to 'extreme anxiety' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/48948583 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name='koreatimes'>{{cite web |last1=Dong |first1=Sun-hwa |title=Extreme anxiety forces TWICE's Mina from world tour |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2019/07/732_272220.html |website=Korea Times |accessdate=December 1, 2019|date=July 12, 2019}}</ref> This incident received coverage in many news organisations across the world.<ref name=\"time_2\"/><ref name=\"bbc\"/><ref name='koreatimes'/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kelly |first1=Emma |title=TWICE's Mina pulls out of world tour due to 'extreme anxiety' |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/07/11/twices-mina-pulls-world-tour-due-extreme-anxiety-10175805/ |website=Metro |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ko |first1=Dong-hwan |title=Fans believe Twice member Mina was forced out of world tour by Anti-Japan bullies |url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/entertainment/article/3019913/fans-believe-twice-member-mina-was-forced-out-world-tour |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderton |first1=Joe |title=K-pop band Twice member Mina pulls out of world tour over mental health struggles |url=https://www.digitalspy.com/showbiz/a28384623/k-pop-twice-mina-pulls-out-world-tour-mental-health/ |website=Digital Spy |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=July 13, 2019}}</ref> She was later diagnosed with an [[anxiety disorder]].<ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/><ref name=\"time_2\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Khouri |first1=Samar |title=K-Pop Corner: Twice member Mina diagnosed with anxiety disorder |url=https://gulfnews.com/entertainment/music/k-pop-corner-twice-member-mina-diagnosed-with-anxiety-disorder-1.66127011 |website=Gulf News |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=August 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=JYP Entertainment update on Mina's health & future activities with TWICE |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/08/27/jyp-entertainment-update-minas-health-future-activities-twice |website=SBS |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=August 27, 2019}}</ref> In October 2019, Mina returned to join fellow Twice members at a fan event.<ref name=metro>{{cite web |last1=Adejobi |first1=Alicia |title=TWICE star Mina's future still undecided despite surprise appearance at fourth anniversary |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/10/21/twice-star-minas-future-still-undecided-despite-surprise-appearance-fourth-anniversary-10954295/ |website=Metro |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> JYP Entertainment released a statement saying that Mina's \"future schedule has not yet been decided\" and that they would \"prioritise the state of her health above all else\".<ref name=metro/>\n\n==Public image==\nMina is known for being one of Twice's main dancers<ref name=\"time_article\"/><ref name=\"elitedaily1\"/><ref name=\"time_2\">{{cite web |last1=Moon |first1=Kat |title=K-Pop Powerhouse TWICE Opens Up About How Their New Album Is More Personal Than Ever |url=https://time.com/5696384/twice-interview-feel-special/ |website=Time |accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=October 9, 2019}}</ref> and has received recognition in South Korea and abroad.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kind>{{cite web |last1=Jung |first1=Chul-hwan |title=3 Japanese Girls at the Top of K-Pop: The 1st of Their Kind |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/02/19/2018021901859.html?related_all |website=The Chosun Ilbo (English Edition) |accessdate=December 6, 2019 |date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> Her popularity \u2013 in conjunction with that of fellow Japanese members [[Momo Hirai|Momo]] and [[Sana (singer)|Sana]] \u2013 has been credited with improving relations between Japan and South Korea by the ''[[Chosun Ilbo]]''.<ref name=pt1/><ref name=kind/> In [[Gallup (company)|Gallup]] Korea's annual music poll of 2019, she was voted the 16th most popular idol in South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/popasia/blog/2019/12/20/heres-who-koreans-voted-top-artists-and-idols-2019|title=Here's who Koreans voted as the top artists and idols of 2019|date=2019-12-20|website=SBS PopAsia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gallup.co.kr/gallupdb/reportContent.asp?seqNo=1072|title=2019\ub144 \uc62c\ud574\ub97c \ube5b\ub0b8 \uac00\uc218\uc640 \uac00\uc694 \u2013 \ucd5c\uadfc 13\ub144\uac04 \ucd94\uc774 \ud3ec\ud568|date=November 28, 2019|publisher=Gallup Korea|language=ko|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Twice discography}}\n\n===Songwriting credits===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Song\n!Album\n!Artist\n!With\n|-\n|2018\n|\"Shot Thru The Heart\"<ref>{{cite web|title=TWICE THE 2ND SPECIAL ALBUM Summer Nights TRACK LIST|url=http://twice.jype.com/notice.asp?idx=1432&page=21&vnum=157|website=TWICE JYPE|accessdate=November 30, 2019|date=June 30, 2018}}</ref>\n|''[[Summer Nights (Twice album)|Summer Nights]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Twice\n|[[Hirai Momo|Momo]] and [[Sana (singer)|Sana]]\n|-\n|2019\n|\"21:29\"<ref>{{cite web|title=TWICE THE 8TH MINI ALBUM Feel Special Track List|url=https://twice.jype.com/notice.asp?idx=1891&page=&vnum=377|website=TWICE JYPE|accessdate=December 12, 2019|date=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n|''[[Feel Special]]''\n|All Twice members\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Twice (group)}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese singers]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in South Korea]]\n[[Category:American musicians of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Japanese dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Japanese expatriates in South Korea]]\n[[Category:Japanese female singers]]\n[[Category:Japanese idols]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language singers]]\n[[Category:JYP Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Korean-language singers of Japan]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Kobe]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Reality show winners]]\n[[Category:Twice members]]\n", "name_user": "Tetrabyte22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mina_(Japanese_singer)"}
{"title_page": "Leo Gibson", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Leo Gibson\n| image                = \"Leo Gibson (Minnesota Thunder) vs LA Galaxy.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| fullname             = Leo Gibson\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n| birth_place          = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n| height               = {{convert|1.68|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub          = [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber           = 14\n| youthyears1          = 2000\u20132002\n| youthclubs1          = [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]]\n| collegeyears1          = 2002\u20132003\n| college1          = [[King Tornado]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Minnesota Thunder]]\n| caps1                = 48\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2               = [[Detroit Ignition]] (indoor)\n| caps2                = 21\n| goals2               = 12\n| years3               = 2009\n| clubs3               = [[Cleveland City Stars]]\n| caps3                = 27\n| goals3               = 10\n| years4               = 2009\n| clubs4               = [[Rockford Rampage]] (indoor)\n| caps4                = 3\n| goals4               = 8\n| years5               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs5               = [[Philadelphia Kixx]] (indoor)\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 7\n| years6               = 2010\n| clubs6               = [[Charlotte Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 7\n| goals6               = 3\n| years7               = 2010\u2013\n| clubs7               = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (indoor)\n| caps7                = 203\n| goals7               = 251\n| nationalyears1       = \n| nationalteam1        = [[United States national futsal team|United States futsal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalteam2        = [[United States national arena soccer team|United States arena soccer]]\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (asst.)\n| manageryears2 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs2 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 April 2020\n| ntupdate             = July 6, 2014\n}}\n\n'''Leo Gibson''' (born August 9, 1983) is a [[Liberia]]n [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for and is the head coach for the [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League|MASL]].<ref name=\"exmo150226\">{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Althaus |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Missouri)|The Examiner]] |publisher=[[GateHouse Media]] |location=[[Independence, MO]] |title=Not Missing the Point |url=http://www.examiner.net/article/20150226/SPORTS/150229155/0/SEARCH |date=February 26, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College===\nGibson was born in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, but came to the United States in 2002, having previously played for the [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]] youth team in the [[Liberian Premier League]]. He played [[college soccer]] at [[King University|King College]] in Tennessee in 2002 and 2003.\n\n===Professional===\nGibson had a trial with the [[Dallas Burn]] of [[Major League Soccer]] in 2004.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |title=2004 Roster Dance |access-date=2008-08-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210084022/http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |archive-date=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> before eventually signing with the [[Minnesota Thunder]] of the [[USL First Division]] in 2005. However, a hand injury kept him from playing any games that season.<ref>[http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm Liberian forward Leo Gibson tries to replace Melvin Tarley with the Minnesota Thunder] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021060424/http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm |date=2008-10-21 }}</ref>  He remained with the Minnesota through the end of 2008, becoming an integral part of the team in the 2006 and 2007 seasons especially.\n\nIn 2007, the [[California Cougars]] of the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] selected Gibson with the 40th pick in the MISL Draft. He informed the team that he preferred to not play in California and the Cougars traded his rights to the [[Detroit Ignition]] on November 15, 2007 in exchange for a first round pick in the 2008 Supplemental Draft.<ref>[http://www.californiacougars.net/news/?id=641&cat=16 Cougars send Leo Gibson to Ignition for draft picks]</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2009, having been released by Minnesota, Gibson signed for the [[Cleveland City Stars]] for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |title=Minnesota transfers Gibson to Cleveland |access-date=2009-04-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215162301/http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |archive-date=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played 27 games and scored 2 goals for Cleveland before the club folded at the end of the season; after a brief return to indoor soccer with [[Philadelphia Kixx]] in 2009\u201310, he signed with [[USL Second Division]] side [[Charlotte Eagles]] in 2010.\n\nGibson was signed to play in the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u2013)|MISL]]'s return to Kansas City with the [[Missouri Comets]] on October 16, 2010.  Named the MISL\u2019s Offensive Player of the Month in November, it was Gibson\u2019s move to the Comets\u2019 DEFENSIVE end on New Year\u2019s Eve that provided the club its much-needed spark in the back. Despite playing the first seven games on offense, Gibson still tied for the team lead in blocks with 20, which tied him for 6th overall in the league. Gibson was a tenacious defender, but he was often able to find the back of the net for the Comets, finishing 8th in the league in scoring with 45 points and finishing tied for the second most 3-point goals with four.  As a reward for his efforts, Gibson was named 1st Team All-MISL.\n\nGibson was named head coach of the Comets on October 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=COMETS SELECT SCORING LEADER FOR COACH |url=https://www.kccomets.com/news/comets-select-scoring-leader-for-coach |website=KCComets.com |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honors===\n;Kansas City Comets\n*[[Major Indoor Soccer League]]: 2013-14\n\n;Individual\n*All-MISL First Team: 2010-11, 2012-13, 2013-14 <ref>{{cite web |title=2010-11 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010%E2%80%9311_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season#Awards |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*All-MISL Second Team: 2011-12 <ref>{{cite web |title=2011-12 Major Indoor Soccer League Season |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011%E2%80%9312_Major_Indoor_Soccer_League_season |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Major Arena Soccer League]] MVP: 2014-15\n*All-MASL First Team: 2014-15\n*All-MASL Second Team: 2015-16\n*All-MASL Third Team: 2017-18, 2018-19, 2019-20 <ref>{{cite web |title=Awards |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/awards-2018-2019 |website=MASL |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Ed Tepper Humanitarian of the Year: 2017-18\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.clevelandcitystars.com/leo-gibson Cleveland City Stars bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071201120525/http://www.detroitignition.com/players/?id=26 Detroit Ignition bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801171341/http://www.mnthunder.com/igsbase/igstemplate.cfm?SRC=MD008&SRCN=biodetail&GnavID=5&SnavID=73&TnavID=&StaffBioID=17 Minnesota Thunder bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Leo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Detroit Ignition players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liberian footballers]]\n[[Category:Liberian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008) players]]\n[[Category:Monrovia Black Star FC players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Stars players]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monrovia]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:USL Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Missouri Comets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia KiXX (MISL) players]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u20132014) players]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's futsal players]]\n[[Category:Rockford Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Major Arena Soccer League coaches]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Leo Gibson\n| image                = \"Leo Gibson (Minnesota Thunder) vs LA Galaxy.jpg\n| image_size           = 200px\n| fullname             = Leo Gibson\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1983|8|9}}\n| birth_place          = [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]]\n| height               = {{convert|1.68|m|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub          = [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber           = 14\n| youthyears1          = 2000\u20132002\n| youthclubs1          = [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]]\n| collegeyears1          = 2002\u20132003\n| college1          = [[King Tornado]]\n| years1               = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1               = [[Minnesota Thunder]]\n| caps1                = 48\n| goals1               = 9\n| years2               = 2007\u20132009\n| clubs2               = [[Detroit Ignition]] (indoor)\n| caps2                = 21\n| goals2               = 12\n| years3               = 2009\n| clubs3               = [[Cleveland City Stars]]\n| caps3                = 27\n| goals3               = 10\n| years4               = 2009\n| clubs4               = [[Rockford Rampage]] (indoor)\n| caps4                = 3\n| goals4               = 8\n| years5               = 2009\u20132010\n| clubs5               = [[Philadelphia Kixx]] (indoor)\n| caps5                = 9\n| goals5               = 7\n| years6               = 2010\n| clubs6               = [[Charlotte Eagles]]\n| caps6                = 7\n| goals6               = 3\n| years7               = 2010\u2013\n| clubs7               = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (indoor)\n| caps7                = 203\n| goals7               = 251\n| nationalyears1       = \n| nationalteam1        = [[United States national futsal team|United States futsal]]\n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| nationalteam2        = [[United States national arena soccer team|United States arena soccer]]\n| manageryears1 = 2017\u20132018\n| managerclubs1 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] (asst.)\n| manageryears2 = 2019\u2013\n| managerclubs2 =  [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n| pcupdate             = 7 April 2020\n| ntupdate             = July 6, 2014\n}}\n\n'''Leo Gibson''' (born August 9, 1983) is a [[Liberia]]n [[association football|soccer player]] who currently plays for and is the head coach for the [[Missouri Comets|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League|MASL]].<ref name=\"exmo150226\">{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Althaus |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Missouri)|The Examiner]] |publisher=[[GateHouse Media]] |location=[[Independence, MO]] |title=Not Missing the Point |url=http://www.examiner.net/article/20150226/SPORTS/150229155/0/SEARCH |date=February 26, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===College===\nGibson was born in [[Monrovia]], Liberia, but came to the United States in 2002, having previously played for the [[Monrovia Black Star Football Club|Monrovia Black Star]] youth team in the [[Liberian Premier League]]. He played [[college soccer]] at [[King University|King College]] in Tennessee in 2002 and 2003.\n\n===Professional===\nGibson had a trial with the [[Dallas Burn]] of [[Major League Soccer]] in 2004.,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |title=2004 Roster Dance |access-date=2008-08-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210084022/http://www.3rddegree.net/roster-dance/2004-roster-dance/ |archive-date=2012-02-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> before eventually signing with the [[Minnesota Thunder]] of the [[USL First Division]] in 2005. However, a hand injury kept him from playing any games that season.<ref>[http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm Liberian forward Leo Gibson tries to replace Melvin Tarley with the Minnesota Thunder] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021060424/http://www.liberiansoccer.com/Liberian_forward_Leo_Gibson20060112.htm |date=2008-10-21 }}</ref>  He remained with the Minnesota through the end of 2008, becoming an integral part of the team in the 2006 and 2007 seasons especially.\n\nIn 2007, the [[California Cougars]] of the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008)|Major Indoor Soccer League]] selected Gibson with the 40th pick in the MISL Draft. He informed the team that he preferred to not play in California and the Cougars traded his rights to the [[Detroit Ignition]] on November 15, 2007 in exchange for a first round pick in the 2008 Supplemental Draft.<ref>[http://www.californiacougars.net/news/?id=641&cat=16 Cougars send Leo Gibson to Ignition for draft picks]</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2009, having been released by Minnesota, Gibson signed for the [[Cleveland City Stars]] for an undisclosed transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |title=Minnesota transfers Gibson to Cleveland |access-date=2009-04-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215162301/http://usl1.uslsoccer.com/transactions/314725.html |archive-date=2012-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He played 27 games and scored 2 goals for Cleveland before the club folded at the end of the season; after a brief return to indoor soccer with [[Philadelphia Kixx]] in 2009\u201310, he signed with [[USL Second Division]] side [[Charlotte Eagles]] in 2010.\n\nGibson was signed to play in the [[Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u2013)|MISL]]'s return to Kansas City with the [[Missouri Comets]] on October 16, 2010.  Named the MISL\u2019s Offensive Player of the Month in November, it was Gibson\u2019s move to the Comets\u2019 DEFENSIVE end on New Year\u2019s Eve that provided the club its much-needed spark in the back. Despite playing the first seven games on offense, Gibson still tied for the team lead in blocks with 20, which tied him for 6th overall in the league. Gibson was a tenacious defender, but he was often able to find the back of the net for the Comets, finishing 8th in the league in scoring with 45 points and finishing tied for the second most 3-point goals with four.  As a reward for his efforts, Gibson was named 1st Team All-MISL.\n\nGibson was named head coach of the Comets on October 29, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=COMETS SELECT SCORING LEADER FOR COACH |url=https://www.kccomets.com/news/comets-select-scoring-leader-for-coach |website=KCComets.com |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.clevelandcitystars.com/leo-gibson Cleveland City Stars bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071201120525/http://www.detroitignition.com/players/?id=26 Detroit Ignition bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801171341/http://www.mnthunder.com/igsbase/igstemplate.cfm?SRC=MD008&SRCN=biodetail&GnavID=5&SnavID=73&TnavID=&StaffBioID=17 Minnesota Thunder bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gibson, Leo}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Detroit Ignition players]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liberian footballers]]\n[[Category:Liberian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2001\u20132008) players]]\n[[Category:Monrovia Black Star FC players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Thunder players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland City Stars players]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Eagles players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monrovia]]\n[[Category:USL First Division players]]\n[[Category:USL Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Missouri Comets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia KiXX (MISL) players]]\n[[Category:Major Indoor Soccer League (2008\u20132014) players]]\n[[Category:Player-coaches]]\n[[Category:American men's futsal players]]\n[[Category:Rockford Rampage players]]\n[[Category:Major Arena Soccer League coaches]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n", "name_user": "Wikipert22", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Gibson"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing viral pandemic in Italy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak Italy per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents by province\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Italy (Density).svg\n| legend2         = Number of confirmed cases by province<br>(as of 6 April): \n{{legend|#FCEED3|10\u201399 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#F2A88D|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|1000\u20134999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|5,000\u20139,999 confirmed}}{{legend|#630606|\u226510,000 confirmed}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Italy\n| first_case      = Rome\n| arrival_date    = 31 January 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=31|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| index_case      = ''unknown''\n| deaths          = 19,468<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 32,534<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/> {{small|(incl. discharged)}}\n| severe_cases    = 3,381<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| active_cases    = 100,269<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 152,271<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|www.salute.gov.it/nuovocoronavirus}}\n}}\n\nAn ongoing [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to Italy on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists in Rome tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Primi due casi in Italia|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml |website=Corriere della sera |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020|language=it}}</ref> One week later an Italian man repatriated back to Italy from the city of [[Wuhan]], China, was hospitalised and confirmed as the third case in Italy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-idUSKBN20F0UI|title=First Italian dies of coronavirus as outbreak flares in north|date=21 February 2020|agency=Reuters|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> A cluster of cases was later detected, starting with 16 confirmed cases in [[Lombardy]] on 21 February,<ref name=\"ThomReut_IT_16cluster_21Feb\">{{cite news | last1= Anzolin | first1= Elisa | last2= Amante | first2= Angelo | title= Coronavirus outbreak grows in northern Italy, 16 cases reported in one day | date=21 February 2020 | agency=[[Thomson Reuters]] | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI |accessdate=21 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200221225322/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI |archivedate= 21 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 60 additional cases and the first deaths on 22 February.<ref name=\"CorrieredSera_76_recent_cases\" /> By the beginning of March, the virus had spread to all regions of Italy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus. Colpite tutte le regioni. La Protezione civile: ecco i numeri aggiornati |url=https://www.avvenire.it/attualita/pagine/coronavirus-aggiornamento-5-marzo-2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=Avvenire |date=5 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency. In February, eleven municipalities in [[northern Italy]] were identified as the centres of the two main Italian clusters and placed under quarantine. The majority of positive cases in other regions traced back to these two clusters.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/coronavirus_in_italia_aggiornamento_ora_per_ora-249241616/|title=Coronavirus in Italia: aggiornamento ora per ora|date=22 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> On 8 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] expanded the quarantine to all of Lombardy and 14 other northern provinces, and on the following day to all of Italy, [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|placing more than 60 million people in quarantine]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Northern Italy quarantines 16 million people |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51787238 |website=BBC |accessdate=8 March 2020 |date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=All of Italy to be placed on coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-51810673 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-italy-sees-largest-daily-rise-in-deaths-and-confirmed-cases-11953192|title=Coronavirus: Italy deaths jump to 463, with 300 in just one region|publisher=Sky News|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 11 March 2020, Conte prohibited nearly all commercial activity except for supermarkets and pharmacies.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/merkel-coronavirus-germany/2020/03/11/e276252a-6399-11ea-8a8e-5c5336b32760_story.html|title=Italy ramps up coronavirus lockdown, Merkel warns virus could infect two-thirds of Germany|last=Harlan|first=Chico|last2=Morris|first2=Loveday|website=The Washington Post|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Rome|first=Eric Sylvers in Milan and Giovanni Legorano in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-hardens-nationwide-quarantine-11583962093|title=Italy Hardens Nationwide Quarantine|date=12 March 2020|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=12 March 2020|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> On 21 March, the Italian government closed all non-essential businesses and industries, with additional restrictions to movement of people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Safi |first1=Michael |last2=Giuffrida |first2=Angela |last3=Farrer |first3=Martin |title=Coronavirus: Italy bans any movement inside country as toll nears 5,500 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/italian-pm-warns-of-worst-crisis-since-ww2-as-coronavirus-deaths-leap-by-almost-800 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2020, the Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI) published [[medical ethics]] recommendations regarding [[triage]] protocols that might be employed.<ref>{{cite techreport|url=http://www.siaarti.it/SiteAssets/News/COVID19%20-%20documenti%20SIAARTI/SIAARTI%20-%20Covid19%20-%20Raccomandazioni%20di%20etica%20clinica.pdf|title=Raccomandazioni di etica clinica per l\u2019ammissione a trattamenti intensivi e per la loro sospensione, in condizioni eccezionali di squilibrio tra necessit\u00e0 e risorse disponibili|institution=Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI)|language=it|date=6 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312202813/http://www.siaarti.it/SiteAssets/News/COVID19%20-%20documenti%20SIAARTI/SIAARTI%20-%20Covid19%20-%20Raccomandazioni%20di%20etica%20clinica.pdf|archive-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/who-gets-hospital-bed/607807/|title=The Extraordinary Decisions Facing Italian Doctors|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=11 March 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233745/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/who-gets-hospital-bed/607807/|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|quote=Now the Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI) has published guidelines for the criteria that doctors and nurses should follow in these extraordinary circumstances. The document begins by likening the moral choices facing Italian doctors to the forms of wartime triage that are required in the field of \"catastrophe medicine.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-italy-doctors-tough-calls-survival/|title=Italian doctors on coronavirus frontline face tough calls on whom to save|last=Privitera|first=Greta|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Politico]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312125640/https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-italy-doctors-tough-calls-survival/|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|quote=\u2026the Italian Society of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care, who co-authored new guidelines on how to prioritize treatment of coronavirus cases in hospitals\u2026}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|11}}, Italy is one of the world's centres of active coronavirus cases with 100,269 active cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> The total of confirmed cases is 152,271, with 19,468 deaths, and 32,534 recoveries or dismissals.<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5351&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto|title=Covid-19 \u2013 Situazione in Italia|website=salute.gov.it|publisher=Ministero della Salute|language=it|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> By 11 April, Italy had conducted about 963,500 tests for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salute.gov.it/imgs/C_17_pagineAree_5351_26_file.pdf|title=AGGIORNAMENTO 21/03/2020 ORE 17.00|date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Due to the finite number of tests performed, the real number of infected people in Italy, as in other countries, is estimated to be higher than the official count.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Flaxman |first1=Seth |last2=Swapnil |first2=Mishra |last3=Gandy |first3=Axel |display-authors=etal |title=Report 13: Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries |date=30 March 2020 |pages=1\u201335 |doi=10.25561/77731 |url=https://spiral.imperial.ac.uk:8443/handle/10044/1/77731 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=Imperial College London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lau |first=Hien |last2=Khosrawipour |first2=Veria |last3=Kocbach |first3=Piotr |last4=Mikolajczyk |first4=Agata |last5=Ichii |first5=Hirohito |last6=Schubert |first6=Justyna |last7=Bania |first7=Jacek |last8=Khosrawipour |first8=Tanja |date=14 March 2020 |title=Internationally lost COVID-19 cases |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1684118220300736 |journal=Journal of Microbiology, Immunology and Infection  |doi=10.1016/j.jmii.2020.03.013 |pmid=32205091 |pmc=7102572 |issn=1684-1182}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The total number of Italian coronavirus cases could be '10 times higher' than known tally, according to one official |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/italian-coronavirus-cases-seen-10-times-higher-than-official-tally.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=CNBC |date=24 March 2020 }}</ref> On 19 March, Italy became the country with the highest number of confirmed coronavirus deaths in the world, but on 11 April it was overtaken by the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2020/03/19/coronavirus-italy-now-has-more-covid-19-deaths-than-china/2873835001/|title=Grim milestone: Italy's coronavirus deaths surpass China's|first=Eric J. Lyman and Kim|last=Hjelmgaard|website=USA Today}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn 31 December 2019, the Health Commission of [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China, informed the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] about a cluster of acute pneumonia cases with unknown origin in its province. On 9 January 2020, the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CCDC) reported the identification of a [[novel coronavirus]] (later identified as the [[SARS-CoV-2]]) as the cause.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 \u2013 Situazione nel mondo |url=http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5338&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto |website=salute.gov.it |accessdate=4 March 2020 |language=IT}}</ref> In late January 2020, following the [[Mainland China during the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus outbreak|developments of COVID-19 outbreak in mainland China]], on 3 February, Italy set up enhanced screening measures, including thermal cameras and medical staff at airports.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Update section |date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Italy medical cases chart}}\n\n===First confirmed cases===\nOn 31 January, the first two cases of COVID-19 were confirmed in Rome. A Chinese couple, originally from Wuhan, who had arrived in Italy on 23 January via [[Milan Malpensa Airport]], travelled from the airport to [[Verona]], then to Parma, arriving in Rome on 28 January. The next afternoon, they developed a cough, and by evening the man had a fever; the couple were taken to the [[Lazzaro Spallanzani National Institute for Infectious Diseases]] where they tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 and were hospitalised.<ref name=\"prima\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_31/virus-primi-due-casi-italia-due-cinesi-marito-moglie-italia-dieci-giorni-e365df1c-43b3-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml|title=Prima a Milano, poi l'hotel a Roma: le tappe dei 7 giorni di viaggio della coppia contagiata|last=Frignani|first=Rinaldo|date=31 January 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\"/> On 2 February, a team from the same institute composed of scientists [[Maria Rosaria Capobianchi]], [[Francesca Colavita]], and Concetta Castilletti isolated the genomic sequence of the virus and uploaded it to [[GenBank]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armstrong |first1=Mark |title=Italian scientists isolate DNA sequence of coronavirus |url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/02/02/italian-scientists-isolate-dna-sequence-of-coronavirus |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=euronews |date=2 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://tg24.sky.it/cronaca/photogallery/2020/02/02/coronavirus-italia-spallanzani-roma.html |work=[[Sky TG24]]|accessdate=2 February 2020|language=italian|title=Le tre ricercatrici che hanno isolato il Coronavirus allo Spallanzani di Roma.}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency with the duration of six months. Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] said Italy was the first EU country to take this kind of precautionary measure.<ref name=\"thelocal-flight\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200131/italy-suspends-all-china-flights-after-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-rome/|title=Italy suspends all China flights as coronavirus cases confirmed in Rome|date=31 January 2020|website=THELOCAL|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> The government also introduced thermal scanners and temperature checks on international passengers arriving at Italian airports.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_04/coronavirus-controlli-gli-scanner-termici-aeroporti-italiani-c10b73d2-4796-11ea-bec1-6ac729c309c6.shtml|title=Coronavirus, controlli con gli scanner termici negli aeroporti italiani|last=Berberi|first=Leonard|date=2 April 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February, an Italian repatriated from Wuhan tested positive for COVID-19, bringing the total number of cases in Italy to three.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-06-20-intl-hnk/index.html|title=February 6 coronavirus news|first1=Jessie |last1=Yeung |first2=Adam |last2=Renton |first3=Steve|last3=George|date=6 February 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the repatriated Italian recovered and was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.open.online/2020/02/22/coronavirus-bollettino-dello-spallanzani-guarito-il-ricercatore-italiano-verra-dimesso-oggi/|title=Coronavirus, bollettino dello Spallanzani: guarito il ricercatore italiano, verr\u00e0 dimesso oggi. Niccol\u00f2 \"sta benissimo\" \u2013 Il video|date=22 February 2020|website=Open|language=it-IT|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> On 22 and 26 February, the two previously infected Chinese tourists tested negative for COVID-19 at Lazzaro Spallanzani National Institute in Rome.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/mondo/coronavirus_diretta_morti_contagi_oggi_ultime_notizie_26_febbraio_2020-5075865.html|title=Coronavirus, diretta. Contagi a quota 424, primo caso in Puglia, 12 morti. Lombardia, Fontana \u00e8 negativo, ma resta in isolamento per 14 giorni|website=Il Messaggero}}</ref>\n\n===Clusters in northern Italy===\n====Lombardy====\nThe [[Lombardy]] outbreak came to light when a 38-year-old Italian tested positive in [[Codogno]], a [[comune]] in the [[province of Lodi]]. On 14 February, he felt unwell and went to a doctor in [[Castiglione d'Adda]]. He was prescribed treatments for influenza.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> On 16 February, as the man's condition worsened, he went to Codogno Hospital, reporting respiratory problems.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\">{{Cite news |title=Codogno, i medici dell'ospedale in trincea: \"Quelle accuse del premier fanno pi\u00f9 male della malattia\"|language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/codogno_i_medici_dell_ospedale_in_trincea_quelle_accuse_del_premier_fanno_piu_male_della_malattia_-249593374/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> Initially there was no suspicion of COVID-19, so no additional precautionary measures were taken, and the virus was able to infect other patients and health workers.<ref name=\"urlMailand:NZZ\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nzz.ch/international/mailand-coronavirus-epidemie-begann-in-spital-ld.1542330 |title=Mailand: Coronavirus-Epidemie begann in Spital |accessdate=24 February 2020 |website= nzz.ch (Neue Zurcher Zeitung)}}</ref> On 19 February, the wife of the patient revealed he had met an Italian friend who had returned from China on 21 January, who subsequently tested negative.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> Later, the patient, his pregnant wife and a friend tested positive.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> On 20 February, three more cases were confirmed after the patients reported symptoms of [[pneumonia]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, primi tre contagi in Italia: 38enne, sua moglie e un amico in terapia intensiva. La donna insegna in un liceo |language=Italian |publisher=La Repubblica |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/21/news/coronavirus_a_milano_contaggiato_38enne_e_un_italiano_ricoverato_a_codogno-249121707/?ref=RHPPTP-BH-I249146878-C12-P1-S1.12-T1 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Thereafter, extensive screenings and checks were performed on everyone that had possibly been in contact with or near the infected subjects.<ref name=\"Messaggero_22Feb\">{{cite news |url= https://www.ilmessaggero.it/italia/coronavirus_diretta_lombardia_codogno_italiano_ultime_notizie-5064423.html |title=Coronavirus, diretta: morto uomo di 78 anni a Padova, \u00e8 la prima vittima italiana |website=Il Messaggero |date=22 February 2020 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |language=Italian}}</ref> It has been subsequently reported that the origin of these cases has a possible connection to the first European local transmission that occurred in [[Munich]], Germany, on 19 January 2020, consistent with phylogenetic analysis of viral genome.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Munich_Codogno\">{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Riccardo |title=Coronavirus: il paziente tedesco |url=https://rep.repubblica.it/pwa/generale/2020/03/05/news/coronavirus-250377117/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=La Repubblica |date=5 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref><ref name=\"nextstrain\">{{cite web|url=https://nextstrain.org/ncov?dmax=2020-03-08&dmin=2019-12-15&fbclid=IwAR3UreH6NMoS8IjQqWOJpYdTX_Ygc5bW4gcBBf2gWe_QTDwxIL0oLMuwSgY|title=Genomic epidemiology of novel coronavirus (hCoV-19)| website=nextstrain.org|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=pmid32003551>{{cite journal |last1=Rothe |first1=Camilla |last2=Schunk |first2=Mirjam |last3=Sothmann |first3=Peter |last4=Bretzel |first4=Gisela |last5=Froeschl |first5=Guenter |last6=Wallrauch |first6=Claudia |last7=Zimmer |first7=Thorbj\u00f6rn |last8=Thiel |first8=Verena |last9=Janke |first9=Christian |last10=Guggemos |first10=Wolfgang |last11=Seilmaier |first11=Michael |last12=Drosten |first12=Christian  |author-link12=Christian Drosten |last13=Vollmar |first13=Patrick |last14=Zwirglmaier |first14=Katrin |last15=Zange |first15=Sabine |last16=W\u00f6lfel |first16=Roman |last17=Hoelscher |first17=Michael |title=Transmission of 2019-nCoV Infection from an Asymptomatic Contact in Germany |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=5 March 2020 |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=970\u2013971 |doi=10.1056/NEJMc2001468 |pmid=32003551 |pmc=7120970 }}</ref> The 38-year-old man was asymptomatic for weeks, reportedly led an active social life and potentially interacted with dozens of people before spreading the virus at Codogno Hospital.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /><ref name=\"urlMailand:NZZ\" /> Afterward, he was transferred to [[Policlinico San Matteo]] in [[Pavia]],<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.liberoquotidiano.it/news/italia/13566825/coronavirus-paziente-uno-codogno-trasferimento-pavia.html |title=Coronavirus, il 38enne paziente uno di Codogno trasferito nella notte a Pavia |website=liberoquotidiano.it |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> and his wife to [[Ospedale Luigi Sacco|Sacco Hospital]] in Milan.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-25-20-hnk-intl/h_485832164169510b66e7bb07479c75b0 |title=Italian authorities identify first known patient to have caught coronavirus in Lombardy |first1=Helen |last1=Regan |first2=Adam |last2=Renton |date=25 February 2020 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_paziente_1_ancora_grave_ma_stazionario_la_moglie_incinta_sta_bene-249550115/ |title=Coronavirus, \"paziente 1\" ancora grave ma stazionario, la moglie incinta sta bene |language=Italian |date=25 February 2020 |work=la Repubblica |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Emergenza coronavirus (49496308758).jpg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]] volunteers carrying out health checks at [[Guglielmo Marconi Airport]]]]\nOn 21 February 16 more cases were confirmed \u2013 14 in Lombardy, including the doctor who prescribed treatments to the 38-year-old Codogno man,<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> and two in [[Veneto]]. On 22 February, a 77-year-old woman from [[Casalpusterlengo]], who suffered from pneumonia and visited the same emergency room as the 38-year-old from Codogno, died in Lombardy.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/lombardia/coronavirus-morta-una-donna-in-lombardia-seconda-vittima-italiana_15150431-202002a.shtml|title=Coronavirus, morta una donna in Lombardia: seconda vittima italiana |website=Tgcom24 |language=Italian |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> Including the 78-year-old man who died in Veneto, the number of cases in Italy rose to 79.<ref name=\"CorrieredSera_76_recent_cases\" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, in Veneto la prima vittima, Adriano Trevisan, 78 anni. Venti contagiati in Italia. Conte: \"Nuove misure\" |date=22 February 2020 |work=la Repubblica |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/cina_coronavirus_italia_virus_wuhan_influenza_codogno_lombardia_veneto_adriano_trevisan-249215365/}}</ref> Of the 76 newly discovered cases, 54 were found in Lombardy, including one patient in [[San Raffaele Hospital]] in Milan<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_22/coronavirus-italia-nuovi-contagi-lombardia-veneto-245e72d4-5540-11ea-8418-2150c9ca483e.shtml |title=Coronavirus, due casi a Milano |first=Simona |last=Ravizza |date=22 February 2020 |website=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and eight patients in [[Policlinico San Matteo]] in [[Pavia]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, a Pavia 8 pazienti ricoverati al San Matteo: anche una coppia di medici |language=Italian |website=Il Messaggero |date=22 February 2020 |url= https://www.ilmessaggero.it/italia/coronavirus_pavia_medici_contagiati_pieve_porto_morone_chignolo_po_cosa_sta_succedendo_22_febbraio_2020-5068178.html |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> 17 in Veneto, two in [[Emilia-Romagna]], two in [[Lazio]] and one in [[Piedmont]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Simona |last=Ravizza |title=Coronavirus, due casi a Milano |date=22 February 2020 |language=Italian |website=Corriere della Sera |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_22/coronavirus-italia-nuovi-contagi-lombardia-veneto-245e72d4-5540-11ea-8418-2150c9ca483e.shtml |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, a 68-year-old woman with cancer from [[Trescore Cremasco]] died in [[Crema, Lombardy|Crema]]. The number of cases in Italy rose to 152, including fourteen patients being treated at Policlinico San Matteo in Pavia.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/23/news/coronavirus_italia-249329434/ |title=Coronavirus, terza vittima in Italia: \u00e8 una donna ricoverata a Crema. 152 casi positivi |date=23 February 2020 |website=la Repubblica |language=Italian |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.globalist.it/news/2020/02/23/coronavirus-sale-a-14-il-numero-dei-casi-ricoverati-a-pavia-2053548.html |title=Coronavirus, sale a 14 il numero dei casi ricoverati a Pavia |publisher=globalist.it |language=Italian |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> On 24 February, an 84-year-old man with pre-existing medical conditions from [[Villa di Serio]] died in [[Bergamo]] while hospitalised in the Papa Giovanni XXIII Hospital.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.it/entry/quarto-morto-in-italia-per-il-coronavirus-aveva-84-anni_it_5e5381b7c5b6b82aa65555f4 |title=Quarto morto in Italia per il coronavirus, aveva 84 anni |date=24 February 2020 |website=L'HuffPost |language=Italian |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> An 88-year-old man from [[Caselle Landi]], who resided in Codogno, died on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/coronavirus-quarta-vittima-a-bergamo-in-lombardia-scoperti-150-casi_15242453-202002a.shtml |title=Coronavirus, in Italia si contano sei vittime e 230 contagi &#124; In Lombardia il numero maggiore dei casi |website=Tgcom24}}</ref><ref name=\"Repubblica_24Jan\" /> An 80-year-old man from [[Castiglione d\u2019Adda]] died at the Luigi Sacco Hospital in Milan. He was previously hospitalised in Lodi because of a heart attack, and then transferred to Milan when confirmed as positive.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Jan\">{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, sei morti in Italia, 229 contagi. Le vittime di oggi hanno tutte pi\u00f9 di 80 anni |language=Italian |website=la Repubblica |date=24 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/ |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ansa.it/canale_saluteebenessere/notizie/sanita/2020/02/24/coronavirus-_60aae600-8535-44d9-86de-48c4b71478ef.html |title=Coronavirus: sesta vittima in Italia, morto 80enne a Milano. Smentita dalla Regione Lombardia la morte della donna a Brescia \u2013 Salute & Benessere |date=22 February 2020 |website=ANSA.it}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_24/coronavirus-chi-sono-vittime-italia-74e27360-56f6-11ea-b89d-a5ca249e9e1e.shtml |title=L'ex muratore , gli anziani ricoverati: chi sono le vittime |last=Del Frate |first=Claudio |date=24 February 2020 |website=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> A 62-year-old man with pre-existing medical conditions from Castiglione d'Adda died in [[Ospedale Sant'Anna|Sant'Anna Hospital]] in [[Como]].<ref>{{cite web |location=Italy |url= https://www.fanpage.it/attualita/corona-la-settima-vittima-e-un-62enne-di-castiglione-dadda-era-ricoverato-allospedale-di-como/ |title=Coronavirus, c'\u00e8 la settima vittima italiana: un 62enne di Castiglione d'Adda, era ricoverato a Como |website=Fanpage}}</ref> Lombardy governor [[Attilio Fontana]] announced that the number of cases in Lombardy had risen to 172, with a total of 229 confirmed in Italy.<ref name=\"Corriere_24Feb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_24/coronavirus-italia-ultime-notizie-oggi-nord-23035e06-56ce-11ea-b89d-a5ca249e9e1e.shtml|title=Coronavirus in Italia, i contagi sono pi\u00f9 di 200: gli ultimi aggiornamenti|last=Online|first=Chiara Severgnini e Redazione|date=24 February 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, quarto morto, \u00e8 un 84enne di Bergamo. |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=24 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/ |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, sette morti in Italia, 229 contagi |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=24 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/ |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> On 25 February, an 84-year-old man from [[Nembro]], a 91-year-old man from [[San Fiorano]] and an 83-year-old woman from Codogno died from complications caused by the infections.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Del Frate |first=Claudio |title=L'ex muratore , gli anziani ricoverati: chi sono le vittime |language=Italian |work=Corriere della Sera |date=24 February 2020 |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_24/coronavirus-chi-sono-vittime-italia-74e27360-56f6-11ea-b89d-a5ca249e9e1e.shtml |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus in Lombardia, salgono a 206 le persone contagiate |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=25 February 2020 |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_in_lombardia_salgono_a_206_le_persone_contagiate-249527654/ |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Repubblica_25Feb_count\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_toscana-249520102/ |title=Coronavirus, 325 casi in Italia. Altri tre morti in Lombardia e uno in Veneto, le vittime diventano 11 |date=25 February 2020 |work=la Repubblica |language=Italian |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe number of cases in Emilia-Romagna rose to 23, spreading through the provinces of [[Province of Piacenza|Piacenza]], [[Province of Parma|Parma]], [[Province of Modena|Modena]] and [[Province of Rimini|Rimini]]. These were all linked to the Lombardy cluster.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://parma.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_primi_due_casi_in_provincia_di_parma-249436934/ |title=Coronavirus, primi due casi in provincia di Parma|date=24 February 2020 |website=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ilrestodelcarlino.it/cronaca/coronavirus-oggi-1.5043974 |title=Coronavirus oggi Emilia Romagna: 19 contagiati, uno \u00e8 a Modena. Numero verde 800033033 |first=il Resto del |last=Carlino |date=24 February 2020 |work=il Resto del Carlino}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://bologna.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_23_contagiati_in_emilia_romagna-249540542/ |title=Coronavirus: 23 contagiati in Emilia Romagna. Accertamenti su un riminese tornato dall'estero |date=25 February 2020 |website=la Repubblica |language=Italian |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, salgono a quattro i casi positivi nel territorio di Parma |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=25 February 2020 |url= https://parma.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_parma_altri_due_casi_a-249527788/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, caso positivo a Bardi. Il sindaco: \"Non ci sono criticit\u00e0\" |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |url= https://parma.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_caso_positivo_a_bardi_il_sindaco_non_esiste_al_momento_nessuna_criticita_-249613641/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> A new case linked to the outbreak in Lombardy appeared in [[Palermo]], Sicily, when a 60-year-old woman from Bergamo tested positive and was admitted to Cervello Hospital.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_25/coronavirus-turista-bergamasca-positiva-palermo-isolata-comitiva-d492dee2-57a7-11ea-a2d7-f1bec9902bd3.shtml |title=Coronavirus, turista bergamasca positiva a Palermo. Isolata la comitiva |first=Salvo |last=Toscano |date=25 February 2020 |work=Corriere della Sera}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://palermo.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/palermo_caso_sospetto_a_palermo_turista_di_bergamo_ricoverata_al_cervello-249516268/ |title=Il coronavirus arriva a Palermo: turista di Bergamo positiva ai primi test |date=25 February 2020 |work=la Repubblica |language=Italian |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> A 49-year-old man who previously visited Codogno tested positive in [[Pescia]], Tuscany.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus Toscana, niente panico: ecco cosa fare |language=Italian |website=la Repubblica |date=25 February 2020 |url= https://firenze.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_toscana_niente_panico_ecco_cosa_fare-249543095/ |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> Officials in [[Liguria]] confirmed that a 72-year-old female tourist from Castiglione d'Adda tested positive in [[Alassio]] while she was staying in a hotel. The woman was treated at a hospital in [[Genoa]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ansa.it/english/news/general_news/2020/02/25/coronavirus-first-case-in-liguria_263ab67d-5a38-4f81-80bc-4e4ca3b0cc95.html |title=Coronavirus: First case in Liguria |date=25 February 2020 |publisher=ANSA |location=Italy |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> Later in the day, a second case in Liguria was confirmed, a 54-year-old man who had visited Codogno for work and tested positive in [[La Spezia]].<ref name=\"Repubblica_liveupdate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/coronavirus_in_italia_aggiornamento_ora_per_ora-249241616/|title=Coronavirus in Italia: aggiornamento ora per ora|date=22 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Le ultime notizie sul coronavirus in Italia |url=https://www.ilpost.it/2020/03/03/coronavirus-italia-ultime-notizie-aggiornamenti/ |accessdate=4 March 2020 |work=Il Post |date=3 March 2020 |language=it-IT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, ad Alassio il primo caso in Liguria, interdetti due alberghi, il secondo caso a Spezia |language=Italian |website=la Repubblica |date=25 February 2020 |url= https://genova.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_primo_caso_anche_in_liguria-249547990/ |accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> On 26 February, a 69-year-old man from Lodi with pre-existing medical conditions died in Emilia-Romagna.<ref name=\"TwelfthVictim\">{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, dodicesima vittima in Italia. Primi contagi tra minori, 6 in Lombardia. Guarita la prima ammalata |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |trans-title=Coronavirus, twelfth victim in Italy. First infections among minors, 6 in Lombardy. Heal the first sick woman |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_contagi_in_nove_regioni_ricciardi_il_95_per_cento_dei_malati_guarisce_-249601102/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> The mayor of [[Borgonovo Val Tidone]], Pietro Mazzocchi, tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 and underwent a voluntary isolation at home.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/on-the-front-lines-of-coronavirus-with-italy-s-first-sick-mayor-1.4829931 |title=On the front lines of coronavirus with Italy's first sick mayor |last=Feuillatre |first=Cecile |date=27 February 2020 |publisher=CTV News |location=Canaa |accessdate=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAdditional cases involving six minors were identified in Lombardy. A 4-year-old girl from Castiglione d'Adda was admitted to Policlinico San Matteo in Pavia, and a 15-year-old was hospitalised in Seriate Hospital in Bergamo. Two 10-year-olds from [[Cremona]] and Lodi tested positive and were discharged. A 17-year-old from [[Valtellina]] who attended a school in Codogno, and a school friend from [[Sondrio]], also tested positive.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"TwelfthVictim\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url= https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/coronavirus-325-i-casi-in-italia-il-contagio-si-allarga-a-9-regioni-11-le-vittime_15336711-202002a.shtml |title=Coronavirus, 12 le vittime in Italia: in Lombardia contagiati anche sei minori \u2013 Guarita la cinese ricoverata allo Spallanzani |website=Tgcom24 |language=Italian |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> Officials in [[Apulia]] confirmed that a 33-year-old man from [[Taranto]], who returned from Codogno on 24 February, tested positive and was admitted to San Giuseppe Moscati Hospital.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, primo paziente positivo in Puglia. \u00c8 un uomo di 43 anni di Taranto tornato da Codogno |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |url= https://bari.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_primo_paziente_positivo_in_puglia_e_un_tarantino_arrivato_da_codogno-249657611/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> A close advisor to Lombardy governor [[Attilio Fontana]] tested positive for SARS-CoV-2. Although Fontana tested negative, he decided to put himself in preventive isolation as well.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, positiva collaboratrice di Fontana: il governatore in auto-isolamento. Contagiati anche minori |language=Italian |website=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_fontana_259_contagiati_anche_minor-249606130/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> Officials in Campania confirmed two new cases. A 24-year-old woman from [[Caserta]], who had visited Milan, tested positive. A 25-year-old Ukrainian woman from Cremona, who previously visited Lombardy, tested positive at a hospital in [[Vallo della Lucania]]. Both were transferred to Hospital Domenico Cotugno in [[Naples]], where they underwent isolation.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, dalla Campania due casi positivi: sono due donne giunte dal Nord |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=26 February 2020 |url= https://napoli.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_dalla_campania_un_tampone_positivo_allo_spallanzani_di_roma-249646115/ |accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, a woman who had returned from Milan in the days before the emergency in Lombardy had started tested positive for the virus in Catania, Sicily.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, a Catania donna positiva. Borrelli: \"A Palermo guariti due dei tre pazienti\" |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=27 February 2020 |url= https://palermo.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/27/news/coronavirus_a_catania_donna_positiva_tornata_da_milano-249700426/ |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 February, two 88-year-olds and an 80-year-old died in Lombardy.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus in Lombardia, 40 persone guarite. Altri anziani morti. I medici nella zona rossa: \"Noi lasciati soli\" |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=27 February 2020 |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/27/news/coronavirus_in_lombardia_vertice_tra_i_prefetti_a_fine_settimana_decisione_su_riapertura_scuole_e_stadi-249689409/ |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> Officials in [[Abruzzo]] confirmed that a 50-year-old man from [[Brianza]], Lombardy tested positive and was admitted to the intensive-care unit at Giuseppe Mazzini Hospital at [[Teramo]]. He and his family were staying in his holiday home at [[Roseto degli Abruzzi]].<ref name=\"Repubblica_liveupdate\" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus: primo caso in Abruzzo, \u00e8 un turista Brianza |language=Italian |work=la Repubblica |date=27 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/27/news/coronavirus_primo_caso_in_abruzzo_e_un_turista_brianza-249686482/ |accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref> On 28 February, four people died, including an 85-year-old Lombardy resident in one of the quarantine zones at a hospital in Piacenza, a 77-year-old and two others over the age of 80.<ref name=\"Repubblica_liveupdate\" /> {{As of|2020|03|01|df=y}}, there were 984 confirmed cases and 73 recoveries in Lombardy.<ref name=\"Repubblica_liveupdate\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, in Italia 1.694 casi: 41 i morti. I dati regione per regione al 1 marzo |url=https://www.corriere.it/salute/malattie_infettive/20_marzo_01/coronavirus-italia-positivi-sono-1577-34-morti-83-guariti-dati-1-marzo-215bf998-5be0-11ea-ae74-e93752023e91.shtml |accessdate=2 March 2020 |work=Corriere della Sera |date=3 January 2020 |language=it}}</ref> On 4 March, Emilia-Romagna's regional minister of health, Raffaele Donini, and minister for territories, Barbara Lori, were declared positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/04/coronavirus-la-diretta-positivi-2-assessori-dellemilia-romagna-ce-donini-salute-pronto-nuovo-piano-durgenza-per-terapie-intensive/5724878/|title=Coronavirus, la diretta \u2013 Positivi 2 assessori dell'Emilia-Romagna: c'\u00e8 Donini (Salute). Pronto nuovo piano d'urgenza per terapie intensive|date=4 March 2020|website=Il Fatto Quotidiano}}</ref> Governor [[Stefano Bonaccini]] and the other members of the regional government tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bologna.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/03/04/news/coronavirus_positivo_l_assessore_regionale_alla_sanita_donini-250207091/|title=Coronavirus, Emilia Romagna: positivo l'assessore regionale alla Sanit\u00e0 Donini|date=4 March 2020|website=la Repubblica}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March, Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] extended the [[quarantine]] lockdown to cover all the region of Lombardy and 14 other [[Northern Italy|northern provinces]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51787238|title=Coronavirus: Northern Italy quarantines 16 million people|website=BBC|date=8 March 2020}}</ref> On 10 March, Prime Minister Conte increased the quarantine lockdown to cover all of Italy, including travel restrictions and a ban on public gatherings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51810673|title=Coronavirus: Italy extends emergency measures nationwide|website=BBC|date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the [[Associated Press]] dubbed the [[UEFA Champions League]] match between Bergamo club [[Atalanta B.C.]] and Spanish club [[CF Valencia|Valencia]] at the [[San Siro]] in Milan on 19 February as \"Game Zero\". The match was the first time Atalanta has progressed to a [[2019\u20132020 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16 match]], and had an attendance of over 40,000 people \u2013 about one third of Bergamo's population. By 24 March, almost 7,000 people in the [[province of Bergamo]] had tested positive for COVID-19, and more than 1,000 people had died from the virus \u2013 making Bergamo the most hard-hit province in all of Italy during the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/ae59cfc0641fc63afd09182bb832ebe2|title=Game Zero: Spread of virus linked to Champions League match|agency=Associated Press|date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Veneto====\n[[File:Emergenza Covid19 Ospedale di Padova.jpg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]]'s first aid spot in [[Padua]]]]\nA secondary cluster of infections occurred in the region of Veneto, initially thought to be the result of a farmer being infected when visiting the primary source in Codogno.<ref name=\"urlMailand:NZZ\"/> The farmer was tested, and the following day, the test was confirmed negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.padova24ore.it/negativo-al-test-sul-corona-virus-contadino-albettone-joe-formaggio-occorre-senso-responsabilita/|title=Negativo al test sul corona virus il contadino di Albettone. Joe Formaggio: \"Occorre senso di responsabilit\u00e0\"|date=24 February 2020|website=Padova24Ore|language=it-IT|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 February 2020, two people tested positive in Veneto. The next day, one of them, a 78-year-old man, died at the Schiavonia Hospital in [[Monselice]], making him the first fatality in Italy. The man lived in the municipality of [[V\u00f2]], which was put under quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/adriano_trevisan_la_prima_vittima_di_coronavirus_in_italia-249260446/|title=Adriano Trevisan, la prima vittima di coronavirus in Italia|date=22 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February, a 76-year-old woman with pre-existing medical conditions died in [[Treviso]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tribunatreviso.gelocal.it/treviso/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/primo-caso-di-coronavirus-a-treviso-donna-di-76-anni-in-rianimazione-1.38516066|title=Primo caso di coronavirus a Treviso. Donna di 76 anni in rianimazione|date=25 February 2020|website=Tribuna di Treviso|language=it-IT|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, an additional case involving a minor was identified. An 8-year-old girl who lived in [[Codevigo]] tested positive.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilgazzettino.it/nordest/venezia/coronavirus_veneto_casi_mappa_contagio_diretta_ultime_notizie-5074003.html|title=Coronavirus: i contagiati sono saliti a 87: nuovi pazienti a Limena, Treviso e Chioggia|website=ilgazzettino.it}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, Veneto governor Luca Zaia mentioned that after the first two cases, he ordered all 3,300 V\u00f2 residents to be tested. Of 6,800 swabs, 1.7% were confirmed positive. This epidemiological study would be used for outbreak investigation by the [[University of Padua]].<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ansa.it/sito/notizie/cronaca/2020/02/28/zaia-da-test-vo-studio-epidemiologico_2c3d88f3-6a4a-4e00-b255-9e1e2feb2768.html|title=Zaia, da test Vo' studio epidemiologico \u2013 Cronaca|date=28 February 2020|website=Agenzia ANSA|language=it|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 28 February, there were 151 confirmed cases in Veneto, with 70 cases in the municipality of V\u00f2, including the two fatalities.<ref name=\"Repubblica_liveupdate\" /><ref name=\":10\" />\n\nBy 14 March, no new cases were detected in the municipality of [[V\u00f2]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, a Vo' Euganeo nessun nuovo caso positivo |url=https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/veneto/coronavirus-a-vo-euganeo-nessun-nuovo-caso-positivo_16143366-202002a.shtml |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Tgcom24 |date=14 March 2020 |language=IT}}</ref>\n\n=== Spread to other regions ===\n{{Update section |date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Trasporto di pazienti in bio-contenimento - 7.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.13|[[Paramedic]]s carrying a patient under [[biocontainment]], in [[Cervia]]]]\n\nA number of cases have emerged in multiple regions that might be isolated and not associated with the Northern Italy clusters.\n\nOn 25 February, the first case in [[Florence]], Tuscany involved a 63-year-old entrepreneur with companies in Asia who had returned from the Philippines and Singapore on 6 January. He tested positive and was admitted to Santa Maria Annunziata Hospital.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\"Repubblica_25Feb_Tuscany\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_toscana-249520102/|title=Coronavirus, primi casi a Firenze e a Palermo. 270 casi in Italia. Salgono a 206 in Lombardia e 38 in Veneto|date=25 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first case in [[Rimini]] involved a 71-year-old man from [[Cattolica]] who returned from Romania on 22 February. He tested positive and was admitted to Infermi Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bologna.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/coronavirus_il_71enne_riminese_risultato_positivo_e_rientrato_dalla_romania-249606750/|title=Coronavirus, il paziente 1 in Romagna \u00e8 un cuoco riminese. Chiuso il ristorante|date=26 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chiamamicitta.it/coronavirus-a-rimini-venturi-caso-spinoso-paziente-ha-avuto-molti-contatti/|title=Coronavirus, a Rimini caso anomalo. Venturi: \"Paziente ha viaggiato molto\"|date=25 February 2020|website=Chiamamicitta|language=it-IT|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> A 51-year-old man from [[Piandimeleto]] who went to Romania with the man also tested positive and underwent self-quarantine at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/un-italian-care-l-a-insotit-in-romania-pe-barbatul-de-71-de-ani-infectat-are-si-el-coronavirus-1266637|title=Primul italian venit \u00een Rom\u00e2nia ar fi infectat cu coronavirus trei persoane \u00een Italia|website=digi24.ro|language=ro|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> On 26 February, one of people with whom he had interacted in Romania tested positive.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=https://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/primul-caz-de-coronavirus-in-romania-1266806|title=Primul caz de coronavirus \u00een Rom\u00e2nia. Suspiciuni despre un al doilea caz \u00een Gorj|trans-title=First coronavirus case in Romania. Suspicions about a second case in Gorj|language=ro|website=Digi24|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February, the [[Norwegian Institute of Public Health]] confirmed that a 26-year-old Norwegian man living in Florence tested positive and was admitted to Santa Maria Annunziata Hospital. He had stayed in Norway for 14 days and returned to Florence five days before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lanazione.it/firenze/cronaca/coronavirus-toscana-1.5046897|title=Coronavirus in Toscana: quattro positivi, altri due casi di contagio a Firenze / DIRETTA|last=Nazione|first=La|date=26 February 2020|website=La Nazione|language=Italian|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.no/20200226/norwegian-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-in-italy|title=Norwegian student tests positive for coronavirus in Italy|website=thelocal.no|access-date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe passenger ferry ''GNV Rhapsody'' was placed under isolation in the port of Genoa with 58 crew members on board after a passenger tested positive for the virus after having sailed to Tunisia on the ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.portnews.it/en/coronavirus-gnv-rhapsody-in-isolation/|title=Coronavirus, GNV Rhapsody in isolation|date=4 March 2020|website=PortNews|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, [[President of Lazio]] and leader of the [[Democratic Party (Italy)|Democratic Party]], [[Nicola Zingaretti]], tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/roma/news/coronavirus_zingaretti_positivo_nicola_lazio_isolamento_famiglia-5096996.html|title=Coronavirus, Zingaretti positivo: sto bene, sono in isolamento. Controlli sullo staff. La solidariet\u00e0 della politica|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> Ten days before, he was in Milan attending public events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/27/foto/coronavirus_zingaretti_pd_milano-249756747/1/#1|title=\"Milano non-si ferma per il coronavirus\": spritz e tramezzini con il segretario Pd Zingaretti|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/italy-pandemic-s-new-epicenter-has-lessons-for-the-world/ar-BB11vMrO?ocid=msedgdhp|title=Italy, Pandemic's New Epicenter, Has Lessons for the World|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The following day, [[List of presidents of Piedmont|President of Piedmont]] [[Alberto Cirio]] also tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, anche il governatore del Piemonte positivo \u2013 La Stampa |url=https://www.lastampa.it/cronaca/2020/03/08/news/anche-il-governatore-del-piemonte-alberto-cirio-positivo-al-coronavirus-1.38566278 |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=[[La Stampa]] |date=8 March 2020 |language=it-IT}}</ref>\n\nA US Navy sailor stationed in [[Naples]] tested positive on 6 March. Health officials in the US military began \"a thorough contact investigation\" to determine if any other personnel may have been exposed to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/07/politics/us-navy-sailor-coronavirus-europe/index.html|title=US Navy sailor in Italy tests positive for coronavirus|publisher=CNN|accessdate=8 March 2020|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, it was announced that [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and [[Italy national football team|national team]] footballer [[Daniele Rugani]] had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51844945|title=Coronavirus: Juventus centre-back Daniele Rugani tests positive for virus|publisher=BBC|accessdate=11 March 2020|date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGIMBE (Italy's Group for Evidence-based Medicine), in a report from 18 March, analysed data from the [[Istituto Superiore di Sanit\u00e0]] and found that healthcare workers represented over 8% of all detected coronavirus cases.<ref name=\"aj-oddone-rising-number\">{{cite web |last1=Oddone |first1=Elisa |title=Rising number of medical staff infected with coronavirus in Italy |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/rising-number-medical-staff-infected-coronavirus-italy-200318183939314.html |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |accessdate=19 March 2020 |date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2020, [[Italica Grondona]] became the world's oldest person to recover successfully from the [[coronavirus]] at the age of 102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://themalaysianreserve.com/2020/03/30/covid-19-102-year-old-italian-woman-survives-the-virus/|title=COVID-19: 102-year-old Italian woman survives the virus|date=30 March 2020|website=The Malaysian Reserve|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/29/102-year-old-woman-from-italy-recovers-from-coronavirus/|title=102-year-old woman from Italy recovers from coronavirus|last=Salo|first=Jackie|date=29 March 2020|website=New York Post|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> She was successfully recovered from the coronavirus after being tested positive with mild symptoms and was hospitalised in [[Genoa]] on 9 March for 20 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7news.com/6063077/|title=102-year-old woman recovers from COVID-19 after 20-day hospitalization in Italy|date=30 March 2020|website=ABC7 San Francisco|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, it was announced that Juventus forward [[Paulo Dybala]] and former [[Italy national football team|Italy national team]] captain [[Paolo Maldini]] had tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51991426|title=Coronavirus: Paulo Dybala and Paolo Maldini test positive|publisher=BBC|accessdate=22 March 2020|date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Under national lockdown ===\n{{See also|#Nationwide measures}}\nStarting on 8 March, the region of Lombardy together with 14 additional northern and central provinces in Piedmont, Emilia-Romagna, Veneto, and Marche, were put under lockdown.<ref name=\"bbc_lombardy_lockdown\" /> Two days later, the government [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|extended the lockdown measures to the whole country]].<ref name=\"cnn_italy_lockdown\" />\n\nTwo weeks later, the number of new cases per day started to show signs of slowing down, while the number of new deaths rose slightly.<ref>{{cite news |title=Italy's coronavirus deaths rise slightly, but new cases continue to slow |url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200330/latest-coronavirus-deaths-italy |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Local.it |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\nOn 31 March, the president of the Italian National Institute of Health, Silvio Brusaferro, announced that the pandemic had reached its peak in the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=\"L'Italia ha raggiunto il picco\", dice l'Istituto Superiore di Sanit\u00e0 |url=https://www.agi.it/cronaca/news/2020-03-31/coronavirus-istituto-superiore-sanit-picco-8038210/ |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Agi |date=31 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref> The news was confirmed also by the head of the Civil Protection, Angelo Borrelli.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, Borrelli: Raggiunto il picco ma non abbassare la guardia - Salute & Benessere |url=https://www.ansa.it/canale_saluteebenessere/notizie/sanita/2020/03/30/coronavirus-curva-contagi-italia-lombardia-guariti-bandiere-lutto_947f659c-647e-4242-ac48-e2b793e46846.html |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=ANSA |date=30 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref>\n\nThree weeks into the lockdown, its effects began to show. Italy reported declines in the number of new cases and of new deaths per day. The country also saw a steady decrease in the occupancy of intensive care units.<ref>{{cite news |title=LATEST: Pressure on Italy's intensive care wards eases as new coronavirus cases slow again |url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200406/latest-coronavirus-numbers-italy |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=The Local.it |date=6 April 2020}}</ref> On 5 April, Italy had the lowest number of new daily deaths in two and a half weeks,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Colten |first1=Jerrold |last2=Orihuela |first2=Rodrigo |title=Europe's Slowing Virus Deaths Bolster Leaders on Lockdowns |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-05/italy-reports-lowest-daily-coronavirus-fatalities-since-march-19 |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=5 April 2020}}</ref> and one day later the lowest number of new daily cases in three weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Follain |first1=John |title=Italy Reports Lowest New Virus Infections in Almost Three Weeks |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-04-06/italy-reports-lowest-new-virus-infections-in-almost-three-weeks |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\n\n===First measures===\nOn 31 January 2020, the [[Council of Ministers of Italy|Italian Council of Ministers]] appointed [[Angelo Borrelli]], head of the [[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]], as Special Commissioner for the COVID-19 emergency.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tg24.sky.it/politica/approfondimenti/angelo-borrelli-chi-e.html|title=Chi \u00e8 Angelo Borrelli, capo della protezione civile nominato commissario per l'emergenza coronavirus &#124; Sky TG24|website=tg24.sky.it}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fanpage.it/politica/coronavirus-angelo-borrelli-nominato-commissario-straordinario-ecco-chi-e/|title=Coronavirus, Angelo Borrelli commissario straordinario: potr\u00e0 anche requisire gli hotel|website=Fanpage}}</ref>\n\n[[File:2020 coronavirus task force.jpg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Conte II Cabinet|Italian government]] task force to face the COVID-19 outbreak in the [[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]] situation room on 23 February. Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] and Health Minister [[Roberto Speranza]] are in the foreground, from behind.]]\n\nOn 22 February, [[Conte II Cabinet|the government]] announced a new decree imposing the quarantine of more than 50,000 people from 11 different municipalities in [[Northern Italy]]. The quarantine zones are called the Red Zones and the areas in Lombardy and Veneto outside of them are called the Yellow Zones.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/21/news/coronavirus_codogno_castiglione_d_adda_contagiati_misure_sicurezza-249154447/|title=Coronavirus, in dieci comuni lombardi: 50 mila persone costrette a restare in casa. Quarantena all'ospedale milanese di Baggio|date=21 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> Penalties for violations range from a \u20ac206 fine to three months of imprisonment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/coronavirus-chi-viola-quarantena-rischia-l-arresto-fino-tre-mesi-ACrcnLLB|title=Coronavirus, come funziona la quarantena e cosa rischia chi la viola (l'arresto)|website=Il Sole 24 ORE}}</ref> The [[Italian army|Italian military]] and law enforcement agencies were instructed to secure and implement the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51602007|title=Venice Carnival closes amid coronavirus outbreak|date=23 February 2020|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nSchools were closed in ten municipalities in Lombardy, one in Veneto and one in Emilia Romagna. All public events were cancelled and some commercial activities{{which|date=February 2020}} were halted or were allowed to resume only until 6&nbsp;pm.<ref name=\"Facebook_Pavia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/comunePV/posts/2439843176121889|title=Comune di Pavia|website=facebook.com|access-date=23 February 2020}}{{Primary source inline|date=February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_21/scuole-chiuse-il-coronavirus-lombardia-lodi-piacenza-codogno-a190ccee-54bd-11ea-9196-da7d305401b7.shtml|title=Quali sono i Comuni che hanno chiuso le scuole per il Coronavirus|last=online|first=Redazione|date=21 February 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> All religious services were cancelled.<ref name=\"Repubblica_23Feb_Carnival\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/23/news/coronavirus_scuole_chiuse_e_niente_carnevale_tutti_i_provvedimenti-249355737/|title=Coronavirus, scuole chiuse e niente Carnevale di Venezia. I provvedimenti Regione per Regione|date=23 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> Regional train services to the most affected areas were suspended, with trains skipping stops at Codogno, [[Maleo, Lombardy|Maleo]] and Casalpusterlengo stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_22/coronavirus-treni-fermi-ore-lecce-milano-nessuno-stop-comuni-rischio-lodigiano-431e997c-553d-11ea-8418-2150c9ca483e.shtml|title=Coronavirus, treni fermi per ore a Lecce e Milano. I convogli non-fermano nei Comuni a rischio del Lodigiano|last=online|first=Redazione|date=22 February 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/coronavirus_il_comune_di_milano_sospende_dal_lavoro_i_dipendenti_che_abitano_delle_zone_coinvolte-249252812/|title=Coronavirus, per una settimana didattica sospesa nelle universit\u00e0 lombarde. Comune di Milano e grandi aziende: i lavoratori a rischio restano a casa|date=22 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nPeople with symptoms were advised to call the [[112 (emergency telephone number)|112]] emergency number, instead of going directly to hospitals, in an effort to limit the disease's spread.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanmatteo.org/site/home/area-comunicazione/in-primo-piano.html|title=Coronavirus, aggiornamenti ed avvisi \u2013 Policlinico San Matteo Pavia Fondazione IRCCS|website=sanmatteo.org|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health (Italy)|Ministry of Health]] provided a website and a direct line (1500) from which people could obtain the latest updates and information, as well as report suspected cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salute.gov.it/nuovocoronavirus|title=Nuovo coronavirus|last=Salute|first=Ministero della|website=salute.gov.it|language=IT|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nEducational trips to destinations in Italy and abroad were suspended. Universities in Lombardy, Veneto, [[Trentino Alto-Adige]], Piedmont and [[Emilia-Romagna]] suspended all activities from 23 February until 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.unipv.it/?p=46130|title=news.unipv \u2013 Coronavirus: Sospensione delle attivit\u00e0 didattiche dal 24/2 all'1/03|website=news.unipv|language=it-IT|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unimi.it/it/coronavirus-misure-urgenti-la-comunita-universitaria|title=Coronavirus: misure urgenti per la comunit\u00e0 universitaria {{!}} Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Milano Statale|website=unimi.it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unibg.it/node/9238|title=Sospensione precauzionale delle attivit\u00e0 didattiche |publisher=Universit\u00e0 degli studi di Bergamo |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unive.it/pag/14024/?tx_news_pi1%5Bnews%5D=8621&cHash=aa65321bb25bdccbf08c0c18299d48de|title=Coronavirus: lezioni ed esami sospesi dal 24/02 al 29/02|website=Universit\u00e0 Ca' Foscari Venezia|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unito.it/avvisi/coronavirus-aggiornamenti-sulla-gestione-della-situazione|title=Coronavirus: aggiornamenti sulla gestione della situazione|date=23 February 2020|website=Universit\u00e0 di Torino|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://magazine.unibo.it/archivio/2020/coronavirus-sospensione-attivita-didattica-e-misure-precauzionali-contro-la-diffusione-dell2019infezione|title=Coronavirus: Sospensione Attivit\u00e0 Didattica e misure precauzionali contro la diffusione dell'infezione|website=magazine.unibo.it|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February 2020, Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] suspended all sporting events in the regions of Lombardy and Veneto, which included three [[Serie A]] football matches in those regions, as well as one in [[Piedmont]], that were to be played the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/150398/serie-games-suspended-coronavirus|title=Serie A games suspended for Coronavirus|publisher=Football Italia|date=22 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/150407/coronavirus-also-cancels-torino-parma|title=Coronavirus also cancels Torino-Parma|publisher=Football Italia|date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/feb/23/three-serie-a-matches-coronavirus-outbreak-inter-milan|title=Four Serie A matches called off due to coronavirus outbreak|date=23 February 2020 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> The following week, six Serie A matches were initially to be played behind closed doors, but all were later suspended,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/51637700|title=Coronavirus: Five Serie A matches to be played behind closed doors|publisher=bbc.com|date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.football-italia.net/150647/official-juventus-inter-and-others-moved|title=Official: Juventus-Inter called off and others|publisher=Football Italia|date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/150715/official-sampdoria-verona|title=Official: Sampdoria-Verona is off|publisher=Football Italia|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> as were two [[Coppa Italia]] matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/150787/official-juventus-milan-postponed|title=Official: Juventus-Milan postponed|publisher=Football Italia|date=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/150804/official-napoli-inter-postponed|title=Official: Napoli-Inter postponed|publisher=Football Italia|date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAuthorities in Veneto cancelled the last two days of the [[Carnival of Venice]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51602007|title=Venice Carnival closes amid coronavirus outbreak|date=23 February 2020|work=BBC News|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> Authorities in Piedmont cancelled the last three days of the Carnival of [[Ivrea]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.lastampa.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/ivrea-addio-guerra-delle-arance-e-la-quarta-volta-nella-storia-1.38507893|title=Ivrea, addio guerra delle arance. \u00c8 la quarta volta nella storia|date=23 February 2020|website=la Stampa|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[La Scala]], [[Duomo di Milano]] and [[Piccolo Teatro (Milan)|Piccolo Teatro]] in Milan, as well as [[Basilica Di San Marco]] in Venice, were closed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/23/news/coronavirus_scala_milano_chiusure_nella_storia-249380233/|title=La Scala chiusa per il coronavirus: in pi\u00f9 di due secoli era accaduto soltanto sei volte|date=23 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.corriere.it/notizie/cronaca/20_febbraio_23/coronavirus-chiuse-scuole-palestre-locali-guida-coprifuoco-nord-00193c74-568a-11ea-b447-d9646dbdb12a.shtml|title=Cosa \u00e8 aperto, cosa no? Guida al \"coprifuoco\" da Coronavirus|last=Giannattasio|first=Maurizio|date=23 February 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avvenire.it/chiesa/pagine/milano-l-arcivescovo-delpini-un-pensiero-di-benedizione|title=Coronavirus. Chiese aperte ma Messe sospese. La preghiera dell'arcivescovo Delpini|date=24 February 2020|website=Avvenire|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> A [[Giorgio Armani]] fashion show, which was scheduled on Sunday, the last day of [[Milan Fashion Week]] 2020, went ahead without any media or buyers present; it was instead streamed live online.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Luke Leitch|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/giorgio-armani-to-hold-empty-show-following-italian-coronavirus-outbreak|title=Giorgio Armani to Hold Empty Show Following Italian Coronavirus Outbreak|work=Vogue|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|agency=Associated Press|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/02/23/giorgio-armani-cancels-milan-fashion-week-show-virus-fears/|title=Giorgio Armani cancels Milan Fashion Week show over coronavirus fears|date=23 February 2020|work=The Telegraph|access-date=23 February 2020|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the emergency phone numbers 112 and 118, new dedicated numbers were added for the different regions \u2013 Lombardy 800894545, [[Campania]] 800909699, Veneto 800462340, Piedmont 800333444 and Emilia-Romagna 800033033.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fanpage.it/attualita/coronavirus-quali-sono-i-numeri-di-telefono-di-ministero-e-regione-da-chiamare-in-caso-di-sintomi/|title=Coronavirus, quali sono i numeri di telefono di Ministero e Regione da chiamare in caso di sintomi|website=Fanpage|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.regione.emilia-romagna.it/notizie/attualita/come-prevenire-il-rischio-di-contagio|title=Nuovo coronavirus, come prevenire il rischio di contagio|website=Regione Emilia-Romagna|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/23/news/coronavirus_scuole_chiuse_e_niente_carnevale_tutti_i_provvedimenti-249355737/|title=Coronavirus, scuole chiuse e niente Carnevale di Venezia. I provvedimenti Regione per Regione|date=23 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TollFree\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_i_numeri_verdi_istituiti_dalle_regioni-249494576/|title=Coronavirus, i numeri verdi istituiti dalle Regioni|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020|trans-title=Coronavirus, the toll-free numbers established by the Regions}}</ref> The ''Ocean Viking'', a rescue ship operated by [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res|MSF]] and [[SOS M\u00e9diterran\u00e9e|SOS Mediteranee]] that was carrying almost 300 migrants, was quarantined for 14 days in [[Pozzallo]], Sicily.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/23/europe/italy-novel-coronavirus-spike-intl/index.html|title=Coronavirus cases soar in Italy as authorities scramble to find patient zero|first1=Livia |last1=Borghese |first2=Tara|last2=John|publisher=CNN|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> [[Trenitalia]] and [[Nuovo Trasporto Viaggiatori|Italo]], the major providers for Italy's high-speed trains, ordered the installation of hand-sanitiser dispensers on all trains as well as the distribution of masks, disposable gloves and disinfectants to all onboard staff members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leggo.it/italia/cronache/coronavirus_protocollo_di_ferrovie_dello_stato_passeggeri_misure_iniziative-5070484.html|title=Coronavirus, i protocolli di Trenitalia e Italo per i passeggeri: misure e iniziative|website=leggo.it|language=it|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:EsseLunga Bergamo coronavirus 2020.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.13|Empty shelves at the [[Esselunga]] supermarket in [[Bergamo]], 26 February 2020]]\n\nSupermarkets in Lombardy and Emilia-Romagna were emptied by customers as residents stockpiled food and supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilrestodelcarlino.it/bologna/cronaca/coronavirus-supermercati-vuoti-1.5045265|title=Coronavirus Bologna, razzia ai supermercati. Lunghe file e scaffali vuoti|last=MORONI|first=FRANCESCO|date=n.d.|website=il Resto del Carlino|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_23/coronavirus-supermercati-assaltati-scaffali-vuoti-prove-coprifuoco-milano-zona-rossa-4f29bbd0-5681-11ea-b447-d9646dbdb12a.shtml|title=Supermercati assaltati, slittano anche le consegne a casa|last=Rosaspina|first=Elisabetta Andreis e Elisabetta|date=23 February 2020|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/video/news/supermarket-shelves-empty-as-coronavirus-fears-grip-milan/vi-BB10kd4x|title=Supermarket shelves stripped bare as coronavirus fears grip Milan|publisher=MSN|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> Streets, parks and train stations in multiple cities in Lombardy were left deserted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/ghost-towns-coronavirus-closes-parts-of-italy-11941940|title=Ghost towns: Coronavirus closes parts of Italy|publisher=Sky News|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/lombardia/foto/coronavirus-milano-deserta-mezzi-pubblici-vuoti-e-mercati-abbandonati_15301555-2020.shtml|title=Coronavirus, Milano deserta: mezzi pubblici vuoti e mercati abbandonati \u2013 Foto Tgcom24|website=Tgcom24|language=IT|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 500 additional police officers were assigned to patrol the quarantined areas in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] and Veneto.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb\" /> Additional toll-free numbers were added for other regions \u2014 [[Valle D'Aosta]] 800122121, [[Trentino-Alto Adige/S\u00fcdtirol|Trentino Alto Adige]] 800751751, [[Friuli Venezia Giulia]] 800500300, [[Tuscany|Toscana]] 800556060, [[Umbria]] 800636363, [[Marche]] 800936677 and [[Lazio]] 800118800.<ref name=\"TollFree\" />\n\nThe governor of [[Basilicata]], [[Vito Bardi]], instituted a mandatory 14-day quarantine for people arriving from areas in Northern Italy affected by the outbreak.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Feb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/|title=Coronavirus, quarto morto, \u00e8 un 84enne di Bergamo. Sette regioni coinvolte per 30 milioni di italiani|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> The Ministry of Health announced that it had engaged 31 laboratories in Italy to carry out the analysis of swabs from suspected COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/coronavirus-il-ministero-della-salute-ha-aggiornato-la-circolare-con-le-nuove-disposizioni-analisi-in-31-laboratori_15196699-202002a.shtml|title=Coronavirus, il ministero della Salute ha aggiornato la circolare con le nuove disposizioni: analisi in 31 laboratori|website=Tgcom24|language=IT|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> Minister [[Roberto Speranza]] appointed Walter Ricciardi, a member of [[World Health Organization]]'s executive committee and former president of [[Istituto Superiore di Sanit\u00e0|Italian National Institute of Health]], as a special adviser for relations between Italy and international health organisations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_speranza_nomina_walter_ricciardi_come_consigliere_e_alle_regioni_dice_no_a_scelte_unilaterali_-249447649/|title=Coronavirus, Speranza nomina Walter Ricciardi come consigliere e alle Regioni dice: \"No a scelte unilaterali\"|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica}}</ref> Filming of ''[[Mission: Impossible 7]]'' starring [[Tom Cruise]] in Venice was halted.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/mission-impossible-vii-halts-production-in-italy-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/|title='Mission: Impossible VII' Halts Production in Italy Due to Coronavirus Outbreak|date=24 February 2020|website=TheWrap|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nMajor companies such as [[IBM]], [[Enel]], [[Luxottica]], [[PwC]] and [[Vodafone]] continued to allow employees to work from home. [[Generali Tower]] in Milan and [[Palazzo Madama]] in Rome installed thermal scanners to measure temperatures of visitors and employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.finanza.com/Finanza/Notizie_Italia/Italia/notizia/Coronavirus_Italia_Enel_ricorre_allo_smart_working_General-516928|title=Coronavirus Italia: Enel ricorre allo smart working. Generali installa scanner tecnici per misurazione febbre |website=finanza.com|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/politica/coronavirus_senato_scanner_termici_scolaresche-5072334.html|title=Coronavirus, il Senato corre ai ripari: scanner termici agli ingressi e stop alle scolaresche|website=Il Messaggero|language=it|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> [[FAO Headquarters]] in Rome conducted temperature checks on visitors entering the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://roma.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/alla_fao_obbligatoria_la_misurazione_della_febbre_all_ingresso-249495069/|title=Alla Fao, obbligatoria la misurazione della febbre all'ingresso|date=24 February 2020|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nMultiple regions in Italy such as [[Liguria]], Trentino Alto Adige, Friuli Venezia Giulia, [[Abruzzo]] and Marche decided to close all schools and universities for two days to a week. Court proceedings were postponed until further notice.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n[[File:Is COVID-19 like a flu? ENG.png|upright=1.13|thumb|Starting from the 9th week of the year, ICU cases related to COVID-19 started to appear in the hospitals. Their spike showed a different behaviour than the cases of seasonal flu.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ilgiornale.it/news/cronache/coronavirus-non-affatto-linfluenza-ecco-grafico-che-dimostra-1837298.html|title=Il coronavirus non \u00e8 affatto come l'influenza: ecco il grafico che lo dimostra|publisher=[[Il Giornale]]|language=it|access-date=17 March 2020 |first=Federico |last=Giuliani}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/salute/focus/coronavirus_influenza_differenze_morti_confronto_grafico_associazione_nazionale_biotecnologi_italia-5097008.html|title=Coronavirus-influenza, differenze enormi: picco dei morti oltre 4 volte superiore |language=it|access-date=17 March 2020|date=7 March 2020}}</ref>]]\n\nThe [[FTSE MIB]] Index fell by 6% and other stock market indices across Europe were also affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/italian-stocks-set-to-lead-sharp-decline-for-european-equities-as-coronavirus-spreads-2020-02-24|title=Italian stocks slump nearly 6% as European equities crumble on spreading coronavirus|last=Goldstein|first=Barbara Kollmeyer, Steve|website=MarketWatch|access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> Over 300,000 calls per day were logged on Lombardy's toll-free line as well as the emergency number 112.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_milano_codogno_lombardia_contagi_morti_chiamate_numeri_emergenza-249521977/|title=L'assalto ai centralini per la paura coronavirus: 300mila chiamate in un giorno al numero di emergenza della Lombardia|date=25 February 2020|we